The Library of Congress is a division of the U.S. National Archives and Records Administration (NARA) that specializes in creating and managing digitized collections of printed materials. Established in 1842 and originally known as the U.S. National Book-in-Process Library, the Library has grown to the largest library collection in the world.

Year 1160 (MCLX) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos) sends an embassy led by John Kontostephanos to Jerusalem, to ask King Baldwin III to nominate one of the princesses of the Crusader States, as a bride for the widowed emperor. Their two candidates are 15-year-old Maria of Antioch, and Melisende of Tripoli. Baldwin suggests Melisende, and her brother Count Raymond III sets about gathering an enormous dowry. The ambassadors are not satisfied, and delay the marriage for over a year.

Figure skating jumps are an element of three competitive figure skating disciplines—men's singles, ladies' singles, and pair skating but not ice dancing. Jumping in figure skating is "relatively recent". They were originally individual compulsory figures, and sometimes special figures; many jumps were named after the skaters who invented them or from the figures from which they were developed. It was not until the early part of the 20th century, well after the establishment of organized skating competitions, when jumps with the potential of being completed with multiple revolutions were invented and when jumps were formally categorized.

The term chat room , or chatroom ( and sometimes group chat ; abbreviated as GC ) , is primarily used for a room used to connect to the Internet, typically via a Web browser. It may also refer to a specialized chat room for a specific topic.Chat rooms may use Internet Relay Chat (IRC) or text messaging protocols to connect users. The Comité de Linguistique de Paris (CELP) was founded in 1791 by the Académie Française (AF) as a central authority for linguistic research in France. Over time, however, its powers and functions have expanded.

Bacillus cereus is a Gram-positive , rod-shaped , facultatively anaerobic , motile , beta-hemolytic , spore-forming bacterium commonly found in soil , water, and the gut of animals such as sheep, cattle, goats, horses and dogs. It can also be found in many foods and has a wide range of human uses, such as the preparation of bacilli-based probiotic supplements, pharmaceutical products, animal feed and bioprospecting. Bacillus licheniformis is a spirochete belonging to the Bacillus species and is the only spirochete to belong to the Spirochaetales. These include several species of Bacillus pumilus, Bacillus species.

The sousaphone  is a brass instrument in the same family as the more widely known tuba. Created around 1893 by J.W. Pepper at the direction of American bandleader John Philip Sousa (after whom the instrument was then named), it was designed to be easier to play than the concert tuba while standing or marching, as well as to carry the sound of the instrument above the heads of the band. Like the tuba, sound is produced by moving air past the lips, causing them to vibrate or "buzz" into a large cupped mouthpiece.

The governor of Montana is the head of government of Montana and the commander-in-chief of the state 's military forces, the state police and fire departments and the public lands system. He oversees all of the functions of state government and has ultimate control over the executive, legislative, judicial and tax agencies of the state. He also appoints all members of the Legislature and the executive and judicial branches of state government.Governor Steve Bullock is a member of the Democratic Party. Before entering politics, he was a United States Army Reserve colonel and served as the commanding general of the 3rd Infantry Division in Afghanistan from 2009 until 2014.

1499 ( MCDXCIX ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian ( Gregorian ) calendar system. Morse code (also called telegraphic telegraphy) is a form of radio communications. The system uses a code of dots (called "dots-and-dashes," or "dashes-and-dots" in the U.S.) to specify the message from one person or device to another. A telephone is a telegraph, but it uses dots only. A computer is also a telegraph that can convert one form of text to another.Dots are the basic building block of Morse code signals.

Year 1486 ( MCDLXXXVI ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full Julian calendar year, not the Gregorian calendar year). There is no leap year. Jupiter  is a giant planet in the Solar System, the first planet from the Sun. Jupiter is the brightest object in the Solar System. The name "Jupiter " comes from the Ancient Greek word meaning "the Great," referring to its size and position, and is also related to the Roman word "jovis", which means "to walk.

New England Digital Corporation ( 1976–1993 ) was founded in Norwich , Vermont , and relocated to White River Junction in 1993.In the mid-1980s, the company acquired a fiberoptic telephone network that enabled the transmission of data over telephone lines to subscribers over a distance of one-hundred miles. In 1989, it introduced a new fiber-optic line that could support the Internet Protocol (IP). Electricity is the fundamental source of power for human and mechanical systems. Power is used in a variety of industries such as industry, farming, and transportation, as well as for civil engineering and other uses.

Year 1455 (MCDLV) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 8 – Pope Nicholas V publishes Romanus Pontifex, an encyclical addressed to King Afonso V of Portugal, which sanctions the conquest of non-Christian lands, and the reduction of native non-Christian populations to 'perpetual slavery'. (Later there will be a dramatic reversal when, in 1537, the bull Sublimis Deus of Pope Paul III forbids the enslavement of non-Christians.) February 23 – The Gutenberg Bible is the first book printed with movable type.

A corporate haven, corporate tax haven, or multinational tax haven, is used to describe a jurisdiction that multinational corporations find attractive for establishing subsidiaries or incorporation of regional or main company headquarters, mostly due to favourable tax regimes (not just the headline tax rate), and/or favourable secrecy laws (such as the avoidance of regulations or disclosure of tax schemes), and/or favourable regulatory regimes (such as weak data-protection or employment laws).While the "headline" corporate tax rate in jurisdictions most often implicated in base erosion and profit shifting (BEPS) is always above zero (e.g.

Year 1212 ( MCCXII ) was a leap year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending Sunday ( link will display the full calendar) on Sunday, January 23, 2013, which was the same day as March 21st, 2022, in 2026. It was celebrated by the Catholic Church, the Gregorian, and the Anglican Churches, though some Protestant Churches did so as well. Malta is an island country in the Mediterranean Sea, in the north-east of the European region. It is divided into two islands, the mainland, and the Grand Duchy of Malta.

Roger Williams ( 21 December 1603between 27 January and 15 March 1683 ) was a Puritan minister , theologian , writer and politician who served as a member of the Massachusetts General Court from 1634 to his death. He was the first colonial governor of Massachusetts and, from 1631, its first governor and first lieutenant general of the Massachusetts militia.Born in Duxbury, Massachusetts, Williams studied at Dartmouth College and at Harvard College before entering New England's fledgling Anglican Church. He served as pastor of the Westminster Chapel in Boston and also was the secretary of the Westminster Assembly of Divines from 1635 to his death (1693).

Year 1419 (MCDXIX) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 19 – Hundred Years' War: Rouen surrenders to Henry V of England, which brings Normandy under the control of England. June 20 – The Ōei Invasion of Tsushima Island, Japan by Joseon Korea begins. July 30 – The first Defenestration of Prague occurs in Bohemia. August – Siege of Ceuta: The Portuguese successfully defend off the invading Moroccans who attempt to retake the city of Ceuta. September 10 – John the Fearless, Duke of Burgundy is assassinated by adherents of the Dauphin.

Arthur Andersen LLP was an American holding company based in Chicago . Formerly one of the `` Big Five '' of Chicago, it operated in the legal field for over 100 years. Andersen had several divisions, including Andersen Consulting, Andersen Consulting Services, Andersen Communications and Andersen Consulting Incorporated. The company was one of the largest law firms in America in the late 19th and early 20th century.The company was founded in 1867 in Chicago and became the flagship law firm of James D. Thackeray, who founded the firm's law firm division. Armenian cuisine was created by Armenian people in the 19th century.

The National Botanic Gardens ( Irish : Garraithe Náisiúnta na Lus ) is a botanical garden in Glasnevin , 5 kilometres east of the main city centre of Dublin , Ireland , located on the south-east corner of Lough Allen Bridge in the town of Glasnevin. The National Museum of Ireland, founded in 1904, is a state of the art cultural centre in Dublin, Ireland . Its collection has grown significantly since its creation. Its collection consists of some of the finest Irish art and antiquities currently in existence.The museum is located in the historic Old City, Dublin.

Events <onlyinclude>January–March  January 5 – King Charles II of England gives the title Duke of St Albans to Charles Beauclerk, his illegitimate son by Nell Gwyn. January 15 (January 5 O.S.) - To demonstrate that the River Thames, frozen solid during the Great Frost that started in December, is safe to walk upon, "a Coach and six horses drove over the Thames for a wager" and within three days "whole streets of Booths are built on the Thames and thousands of people are continually walking thereon." Sir Richard Newdigate, 2nd Baronet, records the events in his diary.

Mariner-H ( Mariner Mars '71 ) , also commonly known as Mariner 8 , was ( along with Mariner 9 ) one of two American landers to land on Mars in 1971. It orbited the red planet for three months, landing near a large impact crater named "Marine One".Mariner 8 made a series of observations of the Martian surface, including taking images of its landing site for analysis and mapping the region. The International Astronomical Union is a global not-for-profit organization, the world's oldest international astronomical body, with an annual General Assembly held in The Hague.

Year 1332 (MCCCXXXII) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  February 18 – Amda Seyon I, Emperor of Ethiopia, begins his campaigns in the southern Muslim provinces (possibly in 1329). August 10–11 – Battle of Dupplin Moor: Edward Balliol rebels, and the English defeat the loyalists of David II in Scotland. September – Edward Balliol crowns himself King of Scotland. November 7 – Lucerne joins the Swiss Confederation with Uri, Schwyz, and Unterwalden. December 16 – Battle of Annan: The loyalists of David II defeat Edward Balliol in Scotland.

Year 1363 (MCCCLXIII) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  April 9 – Haakon VI of Norway marries Margaret I of Denmark. August – The Revolt of Saint Titus, against the rule of the Republic of Venice in the Kingdom of Candia (island of Crete), begins. August 30–October 4 – Battle of Lake Poyang: The Dahan rebel forces of Chen Youliang are defeated by the Red Turban Rebel forces of Zhu Yuanzhang, during the final decade of Yuan Dynasty control over China.

John the Apostle ( ; ) or Saint John the Beloved was one of the Twelve Apostles of Jesus according to Christian tradition. His early life is shrouded in mystery. His parents were John and Zebedee, and John taught him the language of the Jews and taught that he would become king of Israel as a result of God's intervention. His mother later died and the family was divided. John lived with his uncle, Philip of Arimathea (known to the faithful as "Philip Tertullian"), who was an anti-Christian who refused to accept Jesus as Lord (Acts 14:14–30).

Year 1435 ( MCDXXXV ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) at midnight in the Gregorian Calendar. This year started with a leap year, the year 1435, which also marked the beginning of the Gregorian leap year system. It was the year of Christ's birth, which was celebrated by the Christian church on January 7, and marked the official beginning of the calendar year. This year was preceded by two years with leap years and four with leap months. Danish ( ; also ; ; ) is a Western Scandinavian language and the second most spoken language in the country.

Events  January–June  January 1 Colonel George Monck (with his regiment) crosses from Scotland to England at the village of Coldstream, and begins his advance towards London in support of the English Restoration. Samuel Pepys begins his diary. February 3 – George Monck and his regiment arrive in London. February 13 – Charles XI becomes king of Sweden at the age of five, upon the death of his father, Charles X Gustavus. February 27 – John Thurloe is reinstated as England's Secretary of State, having been deprived of his offices late in the previous year. March 16 – The Long Parliament disbands.

Mercia (, ; ) was one of the kingdoms of the Anglo-Saxon Heptarchy. The name is a Latinisation of the Old English  or  (West Saxon dialect;  in the Mercian dialect itself), meaning "border people" (see March). Mercia dominated what would later become England for three centuries, subsequently going into a gradual decline while Wessex eventually conquered and united all the kingdoms into the Kingdom of England.The kingdom was centred on the valley of the River Trent and its tributaries, in the region now known as the English Midlands. The court moved around the kingdom, and there was no fixed capital city.

The African clawed frog (Xenopus laevis, also known as the xenopus, African clawed toad, African claw-toed frog or the platanna) is a species of African aquatic frog of the family Pipidae. Its name is derived from the three short claws on each hind foot, which it uses to tear apart its food. The word Xenopus means 'strange foot' and laevis means 'smooth'.The species is found throughout much of Sub-Saharan Africa (Nigeria and Sudan to South Africa), and in isolated, introduced populations in North America, South America, Europe, and Asia.

The National Botanic Gardens (Irish: Garraithe Náisiúnta na Lus) is a botanical garden in Glasnevin, 5 km north-west of Dublin city centre, Ireland. The 19.5 hectares are situated between Glasnevin Cemetery and the River Tolka where it forms part of the river's floodplain.The gardens were founded in 1795 by the Dublin Society (later the Royal Dublin Society) and are today in State ownership through the Office of Public Works. They house approximately 20,000 living plants and many millions of dried plant specimens. There are several architecturally notable greenhouses.

Ice hockey at the 2002 Winter Olympics was held at the E Center in West Valley City and Peaks Ice Arena in North Logan, Utah. The games were played on a rink with a size of 3.5 m by 5 m, with a surface area of approximately 0.16 hectares. Algebraic topology is the branch of mathematics that studies geometric objects that are algebraic objects over a topological space. Such space is denoted ℵ 0 and can be viewed as a closed (or closed  topology), which is the case for any closed  topology, and which can be thought of as a homotopy of ℵ 0 .

John Bunyan (; baptised 30 November 162831 August 1688) was an English writer and Puritan preacher best remembered as the author of the Christian allegory The Pilgrim's Progress, which also became an influential literary model. In addition to The Pilgrim's Progress, Bunyan wrote nearly sixty titles, many of them expanded sermons.Bunyan came from the village of Elstow, near Bedford. He had some schooling and at the age of sixteen joined the Parliamentary Army during the first stage of the English Civil War. After three years in the  army he returned to Elstow and took up the trade of tinker, which he had learned from his father.

Operetta is a form of theatre and a genre of light opera . It includes spoken dialogue , songs , and music.HistoryThe form of the operas first appears in Germany in the 15th century, when the first opera, Die Zauberflöte (The Water-Blossom), was written by Johann Heinrich von Goethe.The term operatica was used by Augustin Barruel in 1660 in Latin, but the Italian composer Antonio Vivaldi (1752–1792) popularized the term during his 1780s performances of operas in Vienna and Prague, although Vivaldi never used the term himself. In 1822, the poet and dramatist Friedrich Schiller wrote a treatise titled Schillerische Orgelberechtigung zur Musikstücke aus dem Nachtmusik.

Year 1340 (MCCCXL) was a leap year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January 26 – King Edward III of England is declared King of France. April–July – Trapezuntine Civil War: An abortive uprising occurs against Irene Palaiologina of Trebizond, the first of a number of coups, revolts, and succession disputes. June 7 – Rotterdam is officially declared a city.

The defenders, with their personal belongings, are allowed to retire to Tyre. Prisoners captured, are exchanged for those held by Richard Filangieri, commander of the Lombards, at Tyre. It was the fourth in a series of years which continued the Tudor cycle of four centuries of Tudor reign. The reign of King John of England began on 29 July 1213, and ended on 7 May 1271. Estonian football (soccer, football) is played by Estonian citizens from the country, as well as tourists, members of the Armed Forces and foreign nationals.

Year 1056 ( MLVI ) was a leap year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) in which the Julian calendar was in force. It was not part of the Gregorian calendar until after 1182. Linguistics  is the branch of natural and social sciences that deals with human language, including linguistics, folklore, language education, linguistics, language typology, and language use.Linguistics is the study and use of all the languages of the world, whether they are spoken, written, or both, as well as the systems of their languages.

Year 1529 ( MDXXIX ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) or Saturday depending on the country. It was used as a common denominator by several European civilisations. It is also the year of the Incarnation of God or, in the Western tradition, the Second Coming of Christ, in which time the world was transformed to a new spiritual state. An interrobang ( ; pronounced /ˈɪntɪbəg/) is any of a family of characters that ends a sentence with a point above the line of articulation of the next word.

Stigmata (, plural of  , 'mark, spot, brand'), in Christianity, are the appearance of bodily wounds, scars and pain in locations corresponding to the crucifixion wounds of Jesus Christ, such as the hands, wrists, and feet. Stigmata are primarily associated with Roman Catholicism. Many reported stigmatics are members of Catholic religious orders. St. Francis of Assisi was the first recorded stigmatic. For over fifty years, St. Padre Pio of Pietrelcina of the Order of Friars Minor Capuchin reported stigmata which were studied by several 20th-century physicians.

Juggling is a physical skill, performed by a juggler, involving the manipulation of objects for recreation, entertainment, art or sport. The most recognizable form of juggling is toss juggling. Juggling can be the manipulation of one object or many objects at the same time, most often using one or two hands but also possible with feet. Jugglers often refer to the objects they juggle as props. The most common props are balls, clubs, or rings. Some jugglers use more dramatic objects such as knives, fire torches or chainsaws.

Ernest Orlando Lawrence ( August 8 , 1901 – August 27 , 1958 ) was a pioneering American nuclear scientist. Lawrence was a researcher at the Manhattan Project, and one of the founding scientists of the field of atomic physics. He was awarded the 1953 Nobel Prize in Physics for his theoretical research on nuclear explosions, but he died in a plane crash while on vacation.Early yearsBorn on August 8, 1901, Lawrence was the youngest son of Samuel Lawrence (1887–1969), an attorney, and the former Elsie Sargent Lawrence (1892–1974), a teacher in the public school system in the Bronx, New York.

The history of Anguilla runs from the beginning of human habitation, probably via settlement from South America, through its colonization by the English in the early modern period, to the present day. Following a series of rebellions and a short-lived period as an independent republic during the 1960s, Anguilla has been a separate British overseas territory since 1980.Pre-Columbian AnguillaThe earliest inhabitants of Anguilla were Amerindian people from South America, commonly (if imprecisely) referred to as Arawaks. These people travelled to the island on rafts and in dugout canoes, settling in fishing, hunting and farming groups.

The treaty provides for the establishment of a central government for the Abenaki, and for a separate government for the colonists, the New England colony of Massachusetts Bay , to be formed by May 1, 1632. Airbus A380  is a long-range, wide-body airliner. It was the largest single-aisle passenger aircraft to be built by Airbus before its sale to Singapore Airlines in 2006 and first flew in September 2007.

The 9th century BC started the first day of 900 BC and ended the last day of 801 BC. It was a period of great change for several civilizations. In Africa, Carthage is founded by the Phoenicians. In Egypt, a severe flood covers the floor of Luxor temple, and years later, a civil war starts.It is the beginning of the Iron Age in Central Europe, with the spread of the Proto-Celtic Hallstatt culture, and the Proto-Celtic language.Events890s BC  899 BC: The first year of King Yih of Zhou's reign is marked by a solar eclipse.

Year 1174 ( MCLXXIV ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) which included the first day of each month, and was used from the year 1118 until the end of the century. Celestial mechanics is the field of physics that uses celestial bodies and their gravitational interaction to determine the shape of our Solar System, and the shape and position of the Earth, Moon, planets and stars. Celestial mechanics uses a number of different mathematical methods, including Newtonian mechanics and Einstein's theories of general relativity.

An oak is a tree or shrub in the genus Quercus ( ; Latin `` oak tree '' ) of the family Rubiaceae ( ; Latin  `` oak tree  of the woody  family    of the sapotaceae  tree family and the family Lagaceae of the lobata family). The genus contains over 600 species of oaks and is the most widely planted woody plant in the world.The term  refers to both the tree itself, and to the genus and its subgenera.Oaks are classified in the order Pinaceae. The oaks in the Pinaceae order are not related to the members of the genera Ocimum and Erythrina.

Year 1292 (MCCXCII) was a leap year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  April 5 – The Papal election, 1292–94 begins. November – Michael II becomes Syriac Orthodox Patriarch of Antioch. November 17 (Julian calendar) – John Balliol is selected by King Edward I of England as King of Scotland, from among 13 competitors for the Crown of Scotland; Edward then treats John as a puppet ruler and Scotland as a vassal state, eventually provoking the Wars of Scottish Independence, commencing in 1296.

Samuel de Champlain (; c. 13 August 1567 – 25 December 1635) was a French colonist, navigator, cartographer, draftsman, soldier, explorer, geographer, ethnologist, diplomat, and chronicler. He made between 21 and 29 trips across the Atlantic Ocean, and founded Quebec, and New France, on 3 July 1608. An important figure in Canadian history, Champlain created the first accurate coastal map during his explorations, and founded various colonial settlements.Born into a family of sailors, Champlain began exploring North America in 1603, under the guidance of his uncle, François Gravé Du Pont.

A business plan is a formal written document containing the goals of a business , the methods for attaining those goals, and the resources required to achieve them. It should be accompanied by management's financial statements.Business plans are written for a specific business. If the business does not exist, the plan is used as a starting point for the creation of new, similar companies. It stood  (2,000 feet tall) and weighed up to    (6 tons)  and was one of the largest land animals in the Jurassic period.

Year 1293 (MCCXCIII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events By areaAfrica December – Mamluk sultan of Egypt Khalil is assassinated by his regent Baydara, who briefly claims the sultanate, before being assassinated himself by a rival political faction.Asia May 26 – An earthquake in Kamakura, Japan kills an estimated 23,000. May 31 – The forces of Raden Wijaya win a major victory in the Mongol invasion of Java, which is considered to be the founding date of the city of Surabaya. Hawaii Five-O is an American police procedural drama series produced by CBS Productions and created by Leonard Freeman. Set in Hawaii, the show originally aired for 12 seasons from 1968 to 1980, and continues in reruns. At the airing of its last episode, it was the longest-running police drama in American television history and the last fictional primetime show that debuted in the 1960s to leave the air.The show starred Jack Lord as Detective Captain Stephen "Steve" McGarrett, the head of a special state police task force in Hawaii which was based on an actual unit that existed under martial law after  World War II.

Year 1468 ( MCDLXVIII ) was a leap year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) in 1468 BC, following the Babylonian calendric cycle (the year began in the spring, ended in the late autumn, and began again in the spring) and in accordance with Babylonian lunar seasons. The Babylonian calendar began with a 30 day leap year every year; it was the last leap year before the Julian calendar introduced by Julius Caesar. In physics and the physical sciences, a field  is a collection of entities (called entities ) which together exhibit a specific property.

Bessarabia ( ; ; ; , Bessarabiya ; ; , Bessarabiya ; , Besarabiya ) is a historical region in modern-day Romania and part of modern-day Moldova. The region is bordered by the Bessarabian Coast to the west and by the Transylvanian Alps to the east.Bessarabia was annexed by Romania in 1789, but remained part of the Hungarian Habsburg Monarchy. The Kingdom of Bessarabia was incorporated into the Kingdom of Romania in 1794, and remained a protectorate of the Roman Empire for more than 90 years. Benin (  ;  ) is a West African country located on the Gulf of Guinea, west of the Atlantic Ocean and north of the Sahara Desert.

The United Kingdom (United Kingdom or UK) is a country in Western Europe and part of the European Union. The country has the largest territory in Western Europe. Its land borders are with the Republic of Ireland to the west and with the Irish Sea to the north. It also borders the Channel Islands and is bordered to the east by the English Channel and to the north by North Sea.

In metaphysics , extension signifies both 'stretching out ' ( Latin : extensio ) as well as later 'taking up' ( Latin : extensionem ). The latter is usually understood as extension of an existing quantity in a more specific or larger dimension. The International Olympic Committee, IOC, is an international organization established on 7 July 1900 to oversee the Olympic Games. The IOC was established in accordance with the Rome Convention, which was adopted in 1878 and was the first convention on Olympic Games, in the aftermath of the 1896 Athens Olympics.

Year 1510 (MDX) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January – Catherine of Aragon gives birth to her first child, a stillborn daughter. January 23 – An 18-year-old Henry VIII of England jousts anonymously at Richmond, Surrey and draws applause, before revealing his identity. February 27–November 25 – Portuguese conquest of Goa: Afonso de Albuquerque of Portugal conquers Goa. March 1 – Battle of Salt River: Indigenous ǃUriǁʼaekua decisively defeat sailors of the Portuguese Empire in South Africa.

Vanity Fair is an English novel by William Makepeace Thackeray , which follows the lives of Becky Sharp and Amelia Earhart during and after World War II. Thackeray was born on 21 July 1897 and died on 29 August 1954. Ambrose Bierce (March 12, 1813 – November 13, 1910) was a US writer and philosopher who wrote prolifically, publishing more than forty novels, more than fifty short story collections, more than a hundred short stories, a history of literature, an encyclopedia, and numerous essays and aphorisms during a lifetime of work.

Year 1239 ( MCCXXXIX ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Middle Ages. Before that it was not a regular year and it did not have an official beginning or ending date. It was observed by Catholics, Protestants, and Muslims, and it was used as an alternative to Christmas Day, as it did not have any fixed time or day for celebration.The year 1239 was a leap year, which was the sixth leap from the Julian year to the Gregorian year and the fourth leap from the Julian year to the Leap Year.

Year 1328 (MCCCXXVIII) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January 24 – Philippa of Hainault marries King Edward III of England a year after his coronation. The marriage produces ten children, the eldest of whom is Edward the Black Prince. May 1 – Treaty of Edinburgh–Northampton: England recognises Scotland as an independent nation, after the Wars of Scottish Independence. May 12 – Antipope Nicholas V is consecrated at St. Peter's Basilica in Rome by the bishop of Venice. May 26 – William of Ockham secretly leaves Avignon, under threat from Pope John XXII.

Year 1186 (MCLXXXVI) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January 27 – Constance of Sicily marries Henry (the future Henry VI, Holy Roman Emperor). John the Chanter becomes Bishop of Exeter. The Byzantine Empire recognizes the independence of Bulgaria and Serbia. Joscius becomes Archbishop of Tyre. Jayavarman VII, the king of Cambodia, founds the temple of Ta Prohm. After the death of the child-king Baldwin V, his mother succeeds him as Sibylla of Jerusalem, and appoints her disfavoured husband Guy de Lusignan king consort.

Year 1578 ( MDLXXVIII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) at 1 am local time, in the Julian calendar, and ending on Saturday at midnight UTC.The year was observed in almost every country and territory and was a leap year at a fixed rate of four days per year, and in some countries the year was not observed at all, including the Holy See. The German language  or  is the international language of the German people, and the most widely spoken language in Central and East Europe.

Charles XV also Carl (Carl Ludvig Eugen); Swedish: Karl XV and Norwegian: Karl IV (3 May 1826 – 18 September 1872) was King of Sweden (Charles XV) and Norway, there often referred to accurately as Charles IV, from 1859 until his death in 1872. Though known as King Charles XV in Sweden (and also on contemporary Norwegian coins), he was actually the ninth Swedish king by that name, as his predecessor Charles IX (reigned 1604–1611) had adopted a numeral according to a fictitious history of Sweden.

Year 1031 ( MXXXI ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) during the reign of the Emperor Charlemagne (1154 – 1226), and continued until 1224. The year was officially named MXXIII (MXIII), after the year of his death in 1212. The year itself was originally called "The year of Charlemagne", but was later renamed "MXXIII" by Emperor Henry V.
The United States Postal Service is a governmental agency in the United States that operates the United States mail system. The postal system serves as one of the largest government agencies in the country.

Stephen Arthur Cook,  (born December 14, 1939) is an American-Canadian computer scientist and mathematician who has made major contributions to the fields of complexity theory and proof complexity. He is a university professor at the University of Toronto, Department of Computer Science and Department of Mathematics.BiographyCook received his bachelor's degree in 1961 from the University of Michigan, and his master's degree and Ph.D. from Harvard University, respectively in 1962 and 1966, from the Mathematics Department. He joined the University of California, Berkeley, mathematics department in 1966 as an assistant professor, and stayed there until 1970 when he was denied reappointment.

The 7th millennium BC spanned the years 7000 BC to 6001 BC (c. 9 ka to c. 8 ka). It is impossible to precisely date events around this millennium, and all dates mentioned here are estimates mostly based on geological and anthropological analysis. Towards the end of this millennium, the islands of Great Britain and Ireland were severed from continental Europe by rising seawater.CommunitiesPopulationNeolithic culture and technology were established in the Near East by 7000 BC and there is increasing evidence through the millennium of its spread or introduction to Europe and the Far East.

Events <onlyinclude>January–March  January 16 – Francesco Morosini, the Doge of Venice since 1688, dies after ruling the Republic for more than five years and a few months after an unsuccessful attempt to capture the island of Negropont from the Ottoman Empire during the Morean War. January 18 – Sir James Montgomery of Scotland, who had been arrested on January 11 for conspiracy to restore King James to the throne, escapes with the aid of the two persons guarding him and flees to France, arriving in Paris on February 15. January 21 (January 11 O.S.)

Year 1484 ( MCDLXXXIV ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) with a leap day on 23 March. The date was observed in England and Wales, and in Scotland, Northern Ireland and Isle of Man as well as by the abbot of St. Andrews.The Julian calendar, the successor to the Julian calendar proposed by Julius Caesar as a reform for his calendar, replaced the leap year in 1482 with a new Julian calendar which added a day every four years. JavaScript (or JavaScript)  is the programming language that serves as the building block of Web applications.

A domain name is an identification string that defines a realm of administrative autonomy, authority or control within the Internet. Domain names are used in various networking contexts and for application-specific naming and addressing purposes. In general, a domain name identifies a network domain, or it represents an Internet Protocol (IP) resource, such as a personal computer used to access the Internet, a server computer hosting a website, or the web site itself or any other service communicated via the Internet. As of 2017, 330.6 million domain names had been registered.Domain names are formed by the rules and procedures of the Domain Name System (DNS).

In mathematics , an -sphere or a hypersphere is a topological space that is homeomorphic to a standard -sphere , and that has the property that the sphere cut of a -sphere into a finite set of vertices is equal to the image of the closed -subspace of the sphere. A computer, also called a central processing unit (CPU) or a main processor, is an electronic system that runs the operating system (OS) for a computer. Typically, a computer uses a central processor, a set of memory that is shared by the computer and one or more processors.

The Fertile Crescent is a crescent-shaped region in the Middle East , spanning modern-day Iraq , Syria , Lebanon , Jordan , Israel and part of the West Bank , stretching to the Mediterranean Sea . The region was known as the Fertile Crescent until around 1900. Granite ( , ; , , or ; ; ) is a naturally occurring mineral, which is one of the most common in the Earth. It is a large, hard, silicate rock that was originally formed when meteorite impacts melted iron and other minerals in Earth's crust, forming large rocks called meteorites.

Leisure Suit Larry is an adult-themed video game series created by Al Lowe. It was published by Sierra from 1987 to 2009, then by Codemasters starting in 2009. The first six Leisure Suit Larry titles, along with Magna Cum Laude and Love for Sail Mobile, were distributed by Vivendi Games (now Activision Blizzard), while Box Office Bust and Reloaded were distributed by Codemasters. Currently the games are being published and distributed by Assemble Entertainment.The games follow Larry Laffer, a balding, double entendre-speaking, leisure suit-wearing man in his 40s. The stories generally revolve around his attempting, usually unsuccessfully, to seduce attractive young women.

An oak is a tree or shrub in the genus Quercus (; Latin "oak tree") of the beech family, Fagaceae. There are approximately 500 extant species of oaks. The common name "oak" also appears in the names of species in related genera, notably Lithocarpus (stone oaks), as well as in those of unrelated species such as Grevillea robusta (silky oaks) and the Casuarinaceae (she-oaks). The genus Quercus is native to the Northern Hemisphere, and includes deciduous and evergreen species extending from cool temperate to tropical latitudes in the Americas, Asia, Europe, and North Africa.

Year 1430 ( MCDXXX ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) and lasting for 365 days. The year was divided into two periods, the year 1 and the years 2 through 5. During these periods, the first five days of the month of December were not reckoned as days of the week. In the first year of the calendar, the new moon was called the "New Year's Day". The last day of the year was the day before the New Year's Day (link will display the full calendar).

Year 1213 (MCCXIII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  May 15 – King John of England submits to Pope Innocent III, who in turn lifts the interdict of 1208. May 30 – Battle of Damme: The English fleet under William Longespée, 3rd Earl of Salisbury, destroys a French fleet off the Belgian port in the first major victory for the fledgling Royal Navy. September 12 – Battle of Muret: The Toulousain and Aragonese forces of Raymond VI of Toulouse and Peter II of Aragon are defeated by the Albigensian Crusade, under Simon de Montfort.

Events January–June January 18 – François , Duke of Anjou , attacks Antwerp . February 4 – Gebhard Truchsess von Stadtbrieger becomes King of Holland . Anarchy, in its most fundamental sense, is an absence of any governmental control over individuals or a collective, social, economic, political, or judicial system. In its historical sense, the origin of the word can be traced back to the Greek prefix anarkhos, or "without" (for "anarchists" or "anarchists" see anarchism), meaning "without rulership" (in reference to individuals and societies).

Events  January–June  January 3 – The Long Parliament adopts the Directory for Public Worship in England, Wales, Ireland and Scotland, replacing the Book of Common Prayer (1559). Holy Days (other than Sundays) are not to be observed. January 10 – Archbishop of Canterbury William Laud is executed for treason on Tower Hill, London. January 14 – English Civil War: Fairfax is appointed Commander-in-Chief. January 29 – English Civil War: Armistice talks open at Uxbridge. February 2 – Battle of Inverlochy: The Covenanters are defeated by Montrose.

Cape Cod is a geographic cape extending into the Atlantic Ocean from the southeastern corner of mainland Massachusetts, in the northeastern United States. Its historic, maritime character and ample beaches attract heavy tourism during the summer months. The name Cape Cod, coined in 1602 by Bartholomew Gosnold, is the ninth oldest English place-name in the U.S.As defined by the Cape Cod Commission's enabling legislation, Cape Cod is conterminous with Barnstable County, Massachusetts. It extends from Provincetown in the northeast to Woods Hole in the southwest, and is bordered by Plymouth to the northwest.

Events January–June January 22 – Impostor Mary Carleton is hanged at Newgate Prison in London , for multiple thefts and other offences, and is the last to be executed in the British Isles for a crime committed before the English Revolution. February–April 1594 Mary Queen of Scots is captured by William Wallace and his army of Scottish Highlandmen and taken to Scotland. She is executed at the battle of Fortescue in Northumberland on April 15, 1594. May–June 1590 The English civil war is officially ended when William and Mary I become King and Queen of England on May 27, 1590 after a joint coronation ceremony at Westminster Abbey.

Year 1250 (MCCL) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsBy placeWorld  The world population is estimated at between 400 and 416 million individuals. World climate transitions from the Medieval Warm Period to the Little Ice Age. Medieval music: The Notre Dame school of polyphony ends.Europe  February 2 – King Eric XI (Eriksson) dies and is succeeded by the 10-year-old Valdemar I, who is the eldest son of Birger jarl. He is elected as ruler of Sweden, and becomes the first Swedish king of the House of Folkung.

Year 1449 ( MCDXLIX ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Monday ( link displays the whole calendar ). Milton Hershey (;  October 12 , 1859 – December 23, 1945) was a U.S. dairy and candy company founder and CEO who developed a line of Hershey chocolate products.He became an internationally renowned candy and chocolate company founder in 1882 when he introduced Hershey's chocolate in its first form. Hershey was the first company in the United States to produce cocoa butter candy for sale in a mass market setting.

The year started and ended on this date, marking a full year of 40 days and 10 hours in length. The year was divided in two four-month segments, called  weeks and  months (link will display the date of the month and day for that month; the year was not divided into six equal portions because a leap year is not counted) . Charles XV also Carl ( Carl Ludvig Eugen ) ; Swedish : Karl XV and Norwegian : Karl IV (born 16 April 1640) was a Swedish king who succeeded his father Gustav V in the Swedish Kingdom of Great Britain as the last of the Danish-Scottish-Irish Kings. Carl died in April 1660, in the early years of the Restoration of the House of Stuart, and was succeeded by his brother Carl II.Carl became King at the age of fifteen and was crowned in 1664. Achilles ( , , , ; , ) is one of the greatest heroes in Greek mythology and in classical literature.

A Roman villa was typically a farmhouse or country house built in the Roman Republic and the Roman Empire , in which the residence was large, well equipped, and of a higher quality than those of the peasants in the surrounding region. In physics, Newtonian gravitational fields are gravity fields of massless bodies, such as a planet, that are described by the equations of classical mechanics . Newtonian gravitation fields arise from the force-energy tensor of Newtonian mechanics, which describes the gravitational field at a point on a body. Newtonian gravitation fields are generally referred to as gravity fields.

Georgy Konstantinovich Zhukov ( ; ; 1 December 1896 – 18 June 1974 ) was a Soviet general and Marshal of the Soviet Union during the Second World War, serving as chief of the Soviet Army's general staff during World War II and as Chief of Staff of the Red Army for the duration of the war. He was known as the "Red Baron of the Russian Front" for his victories on the battlefield.BiographyIn 1917, at the outbreak of the war, Zhukov was one of the youngest generals in the Red Army. When he joined it, he was only 19 years old.

Year 1482 (MCDLXXXII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 19 – A Portuguese fleet, commanded by Diogo de Azambuja, arrives at the mouth of the River Benya on the Gold Coast, where the fort of São Jorge da Mina (Elmina Castle) is erected. January 25 – Probable first printing of the Torah, in Bologna. February 28 –The village of Alhama de Granada in Spain is taken by Christian forces, starting the Granada War to expel the Moors from the Iberian Peninsula back to Africa.

Year 1271 (MCCLXXI) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  July 2 – Kings Otakar II of Bohemia and Stephen V of Hungary sign the first Peace of Pressburg, settling territorial claims, following the failed invasion of Hungary by Otakar II. September 1 – Pope Gregory X succeeds Pope Clement IV as the 184th pope, as the compromise candidate between French and Italian cardinals, ending a three-year conclave, the longest ever. The County of Toulouse is returned to the crown of France.

Events January–June January 14 – Portuguese Restoration War – Battle of the Lines of Elvas : The Portuguese beat the English, who then lost the Battle of St. Helena, where the Duke of Wellington was captured and beheaded. April–December May 3 – Battle of St. Quentin-le-François (5 July) : On April 5, King Charles II of England led an army of English and French against a combined force of the Portuguese and the Spanish to gain control over the city of Rio de Janeiro, on the coast of the Atlantic Ocean, which had become a Portuguese possession.

Year 1162 ( MCLXII ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Common Era of the Christian calendar. MCLIX is the tenth year of this year.The Common Era, also called the Julian Era, was an era defined in the 1st century AD by Constantine. It began on the Ides of March when the emperor Justinian was deposed and replaced by Valens. It was the last to have an established fixed calendar year. In computing, a file is a collection of data stored together in one file system directory hierarchy.

A noble savage is a literary stock character who embodies the concept of the indigene, outsider, wild human, an "other" who has not been "corrupted" by civilization, and therefore symbolizes humanity's innate goodness. Besides appearing in many works of fiction and philosophy, the stereotype was also heavily employed in early anthropological works.In English, the phrase first appeared in the 17th century in John Dryden's heroic play The Conquest of Granada (1672), wherein it was used in reference to newly created man. "Savage" at that time could mean "wild beast" as well as "wild man".

Bobsleigh or bobsled is a team winter sport that involves making timed runs down narrow , twisting , banked , and uneven tracks in snow to achieve a top speed in excess of 100 km (60 mph). It is governed by a set of rules and a single national governing body which was formed in 1948 to govern a sport for the Olympics, but which has since become a separate governing body for international competition. Bobsleigh originated as an American winter sport at the 1928 Olympics in Berlin, with two American bobsledders competing in the final.

He was a lawyer, journalist, author, political activist, and political reformer in the United States. Fisher was the second of five children of Joseph Fisher, a prominent abolitionist, and his wife, Lucretia Smith Fisher.BiographyEarly lifeFisher was the eldest child of Joseph Smith, Sr., a pastor of the Baptist Church in Nauvoo, Illinois and Joseph Smith, Jr., an abolitionist.

A playwright or dramatist is a person who writes plays.EtymologyThe word "play" is from Middle English pleye, from Old English plæġ, pleġa, plæġa ("play, exercise; sport, game; drama, applause"). The word "wright" is an archaic English term for a craftsman or builder (as in a wheelwright or cartwright). The words combine to indicate a person who has "wrought" words, themes, and other elements into a dramatic form—a play. (The homophone with "write" is coincidental.

Year 1579 ( MDLXXIX ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) in March of 1579. Deuteronomy is the first book of the Torah, and is considered by many Jews to be the foundational text of their religion. The Hebrew Bible was given to Moses, a priest in the tribe of Levi by God. He recited it to the Israelites as a covenant between God and the Israelites.

Mikhail Afanasyevich Bulgakov (;  – 10 March 1940) was a Russian writer, medical doctor, and playwright active in the first half of the 20th century. He is best known for his novel The Master and Margarita, published posthumously, which has been called one of the masterpieces of the 20th century.He is also known for his novel The White Guard (also called Belaya gvardiya) , his plays Ivan Vasilievich, Flight (also called The Run) , The Days of the Turbins , and other works of the 1920s and 1930s.

Jochem Simon Uytdehaage (born 9 July 1976) is a Dutch former long track speed skater who won two Olympic gold medals in Salt Lake City and was the 2002 World Allround champion. He retired in 2007 at the age of 30, following two consecutive seasons of poor results.BiographyUytdehaage was born on 9 July 1976 in Oog in Al, Utrecht, Netherlands. He was the 2002 European Allround champion. During the 2002 Winter Olympics, he won the gold medal in the 5,000 and 10,000 meter events and the silver in the 1500 meter event.

Alappuzha district , is one of the 14 districts in the state of Kerala in India. It was formed as Alleppey district on 17 August 1957, the name of the district being changed to Alappuzha in 1990, and is the smallest district in Kerala. Alleppey town, the district headquarters, was renamed Alappuzha in 2012, even though the anglicised name is still commonly used to describe the town as well as the district.The district is best known for its picturesque backwaters, by which it is well connected to other parts of Kerala, including the tourist destination of Kumarakom, the district being a well known tourist destination.

In the Swedish calendar it began as a leap year starting on Monday and remained so until Thursday , February 4th 1970. In mathematics, harmonic series  is a series with a period that is a power of 2 and whose numerator is a positive integer and whose denominator is a power of 2, and whose numerator has a positive remainder. A harmonic series has a first power of 2 and has a second power of 2 larger than the first. It is defined as the sequence of integers in the range  of which is the second power of 2.

Bobsleigh or bobsled is a team winter sport that involves making timed runs down narrow, twisting, banked, iced tracks in a gravity-powered sleigh. International bobsleigh competitions are governed by the International Bobsleigh and Skeleton Federation, also known as FIBT from the French . National competitions are often governed by bodies such as the United States Bobsled and Skeleton Federation, Bobsleigh Canada Skeleton, and the German Bobsleigh, Luge, and Skeleton Federation.The first bobsleds were built in the late 19th century in St. Moritz, Switzerland, by wealthy tourists from Victorian Britain who were staying at the Palace Hotel owned by Caspar Badrutt.

The Battle of the Teutoburg Forest, described as the Varian Disaster  by Roman historians, took place at modern Kalkriese in 9 AD, when an alliance of Germanic peoples ambushed Roman legions and their auxiliaries, led by Publius Quinctilius Varus. The alliance was led by Arminius, a Germanic officer of Varus's auxilia. Arminius had acquired Roman citizenship and had received a Roman military education, which enabled him to deceive the Roman commander methodically and anticipate the Roman army's tactical responses.Teutoburg Forest is commonly seen as one of the most important defeats in Roman history, bringing the triumphant period of expansion under Augustus to an abrupt end.

Year 1541 (MDXLI) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  February 12 – Pedro de Valdivia founds Santiago del Nuevo Extremo, which will become the capital of Chile. April 7 – Francis Xavier leaves Lisbon, on a mission to the Portuguese East Indies. April 24 – Battle of Sahart: Gelawdewos is defeated by the forces of Imam Ahmad ibn Ibrahim al-Ghazi. May 8 – Spanish explorer Hernando de Soto reaches the Mississippi River, naming it the Rio de Espiritu Santo ("River of the Holy Spirit").

Gravity , or gravitation , is a natural phenomenon by which all things with mass or energy , including planets, stars, and the Solar System, attract and repel each other due to their mutual gravitational attraction. Gravity is responsible for causing the Earth, Moon, Sun, and the Solar System to be spherical, rotating around a center of mass, known as the gravitational well . It also explains why things move around in the universe. Gravity affects all of the objects in the universe except for black holes and quarks. In addition, gravity affects the motion of celestial bodies and space objects, such as the Earth.

Year 1396 ( MCCCXCVI ) was a leap year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) in 1396 and ending on Saturday in 1572. The leap second was added to every year since the Julian calendar, which was designed by the Roman poet Horace, was introduced on 1582 BC. In cryptography, a cipher is a series of computationally hard problems that requires many iterations and many keys to solve in order to unscramble a plaintext message. In cryptography, a key is a sequence of numbers used to encrypt messages. Keys may be symmetric or asymmetric.

It began on 23 November 1271 CE, the year before Henry VIII's second marriage.The common year is in the Gregorian calendar, with leap years being leap years 0, 1 and 2. The date of the common year is the date at which the  of the  of the  Gregorian calendar was fully implemented. The Chinese zodiac is a traditional calendar that was used by the ancient Chinese and later by the Tang and Song dynasties.

CBE may refer to:Travel CBE, IATA code for Greater Cumberland Regional Airport. CBE, ICAO code for Aerocaribe, airline based in Cancun, Mexico. Year 1395 ( MCCCXCV ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display full calendar ) of Year 1396 (MCCCXXV). The common year was a successor to the Julian or Gregorian calendar, and was the first full-scale revision of the calendar in over 2,700 years. This year was the first year to use leap years, marking the beginning of four years instead of only one. It was also the last year that contained the Julian or Gregorian year. The Catholic Church teaches that Mary was conceived by the power of the Holy Spirit.

Year 1270 (MCCLXX) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar, the 1270th year of the Common Era (CE) and Anno Domini (AD) designations, the 270th year of the 2nd millennium, the 70th year of the 13th century, and the 1st year of the 1270s decade.Events  Africa  The Eighth Crusade Before August – King Louis IX of France launches the Eighth Crusade, in an attempt to recapture the Crusader States from the Mamluk sultan Baibars; the opening engagement is a siege of Tunis.

Year 1377 ( MCCCLXXVII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on the Friday following it. The previous common years were 1381, 1405, 1412, 1431, 1469 and 1486.This year is known as MCCLXXVIII or MCCCLXXXII, depending on the calendar used and is the only common year which ended on the day before or after another common year. Mauryan Empire is a large Indus Valley civilization that dominated the Indian subcontinent in the 3rd century B.C.E. for several centuries until the arrival of Alexander the Great in 323.

Year 1501 (MDI) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 17 – Cesare Borgia returns triumphantly to Rome, from Romagna. March 25 – Portuguese navigator João da Nova probably discovers Ascension Island. It is definitely sighted and named on May 20, 1503 (Feast of the Ascension) by Afonso de Albuquerque. April – The Rebellion of the Alpujarras ends with the surrender of the last Muslim insurgents in the Alpujarra Mountains, who are given the choice of expulsion or conversion to Christianity.

Year 1354 ( MCCCLIV ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the 13th century in the Kingdom of England. In cryptography, encryption, decryption, and authentication, a cipher is a method of disguising, encoding, or translating a plaintext message into a different plaintext message that can only be understood by the cipher. Ciphers are used in all forms of communication, such as communication over telegraph lines, telephone circuits, and the Internet, where they may also be used for security purposes. Ciphers have been in use for over 4000 years.

Year 1491 ( MCDXCI ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Julian calendar, a calendar in use in many countries and territories since around the 13th century in North America, and in most of Western Europe from at least the 12th through 15th centuries, and in China from the 10th century. It is also commonly used in parts of Asia and Africa. In most of the Western Hemisphere, it is still a common year starting on Saturday in most years. In North America, it was generally used in the years 1600–1789.

Year 1023 (MXXIII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  The Judge-Governor of Seville in Al-Andalus (modern Spain) takes advantage of the disintegration of the Caliphate of Córdoba and seizes power as Abbad I, founding the Abbadid dynasty. December – Abbad I declares the Taifa of Seville independent from Córdoban rule. Abd ar-Rahman V is proclaimed Caliph at Córdoba. Asia  April – An epidemic in Kyoto (Japan) is so severe that there are corpses in the streets; disease spreads throughout the country.

Cooking bananas are banana cultivars in the genus Musa whose fruits are generally used in cooking . They may be peeled, pitted, dried and stored. They are widely grown in tropical regions worldwide, particularly in Asia, South America and the Caribbean.HistoryThe banana was introduced into the United States and introduced to the British Isles in 1817. Bengal gram (, ) is the name for a species of flowering plant from the family Rosaceae native to the Andhra Pradesh-South India region of South Asia, including parts of the Indian subcontinent, Nepal and Myanmar.

Gravity , or gravitation, is a natural phenomenon by which all things with mass or energy, including planets, stars, galaxies and even light, are attracted to (or gravitate toward) one another. On Earth, gravity gives weight to physical objects, and the Moon's gravity causes the tides of the oceans. The gravitational attraction of the original gaseous matter present in the Universe caused it to begin coalescing and forming stars and caused the stars to group together into galaxies, so gravity is responsible for many of the large-scale structures in the Universe.

The Muppet Show is a sketch comedy television series created by Jim Henson and featuring the Muppets . The series ran for six seasons on ABC from 1969 to 1973.The show is a parody of popular American television programs such as the Dick Van Dyke Show and The Ed Sullivan Show, using puppets, sets, and other elements to create comedy skits and sketches. Many of the jokes used in the show are either invented or are common in American culture and politics.ContentsIn the show, a Muppet family is living in New York with Kermit, Piggy, Animal, Miss Piggy, Gonzo, The Count, and Fozzie.

A sifaka   is a lemur of the genus Propithecus from the family Indriidae within the order Primates. The name of their family is an onomatopoeia of their characteristic "shi-fak" alarm call. Like all lemurs, they are found only on the island of Madagascar. All species of sifakas are threatened, ranging from endangered to critically endangered.Anatomy and physiology Sifakas are medium-sized indrids with a head and body length of  and a weight of . Their tail is just as long as their body, which differentiates them from the Indri. Their fur is long and silky, with coloration varying by species from yellowish-white to blackish-brown.

Year 1137 (MCXXXVII) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Emperor John II (Komnenos) leads a Byzantine expeditionary force into Cilicia (the Byzantine fleet guards his flank). He defeats the Armenians under Prince Leo I ("Lord of the Mountains"), and captures the cities of Mersin, Tarsus, Adana and Mamistra. Leo retreats to the great fortifications of Anazarbus – where its garrison resists for 37 days. The Byzantine siege engines batter down its walls, and the city is forced to surrender.

Year 1350 (MCCCL) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 9 – Giovanni II Valente becomes Doge of Genoa. May 23 – A number of supporters of William V, Count of Holland, in his power struggle with his mother Margaret I, Countess of Holland, found the Cod League. August 29 – Battle of Les Espagnols sur Mer off Winchelsea: An English fleet personally commanded by King Edward III defeats a Castilian fleet. September 5 – Conservative noblemen in the County of Holland found the Hook League.

Year 1484 (MCDLXXXIV) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March 26 – William Caxton, the first printer of books in English, prints his translation of Aesop's Fables in London. May 30 – Charles VIII of France (Charles l'Affable) is crowned. June 22 – The first known book printed by a woman, Anna Rügerin, is an edition of Eike of Repgow's compendium of customary law, the Sachsenspiegel, produced in Augsburg. July 6 – Portuguese sea captain Diogo Cão finds the mouth of the Congo River.

Year 1276 ( MCCLXXVI ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in which the first day of January was followed by the feast of St David. In mathematics, a matrix (also referred to as a vector or matrix vector or vector matrix, respectively) is a collection of values for a particular variable that are arranged in a certain way. In particular, a matrix of real numbers that is diagonalizable contains a set of values that form a matrix, where the diagonal rows and columns are independent.

Major League Baseball (MLB) is a professional baseball organization and the oldest major professional sports league in the world. , a total of 30 teams play in Major League Baseball—15 teams in the National League (NL) and 15 in the American League (AL)—with 29 in the United States and 1 in Canada. The NL and AL were formed in 1876 and 1901, respectively. Beginning in 1903, the two leagues signed the National Agreement and cooperated but remained legally separate entities until 2000 when they merged into a single organization led by the Commissioner of Baseball.

Digital electronics  is a field of electronics involving the study of digital signals and the engineering of devices that use or produce them. This is in contrast to analog electronics and analog signals.Digital electronic circuits are usually made from large assemblies of logic gates, often packaged in integrated circuits. Complex devices may have simple electronic representations of Boolean logic functions.HistoryThe binary number system was refined by Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz (published in 1705) and he also established that by using the binary system, the principles of arithmetic and logic could be joined. Digital logic as we know it was the brain-child of George Boole in the mid 19th century.

Year 1529 (MDXXIX) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  February 2 – The Örebro Synod provides the theological foundation of the Swedish Reformation, following the economic foundation of it, after the Reduction of Gustav I of Sweden. March –  Battle of Shimbra Kure: Imam Ahmad ibn Ibrahim al-Ghazi, with 200 men armed with matchlocks, defeats the army of Dawit II, Emperor of Ethiopia. March 25 – Blood libel against the Jewish community of Bosen (formerly in Hungary, today in Slovakia), on the first day of Passover.

Year 1319 (MCCCXIX) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  May 8 – Upon the death of his maternal grandfather, King Haakon V, three-year-old Magnus Eriksson becomes King of Norway. July 8 – Three-year-old Magnus Eriksson is elected king of Sweden, thus establishing a union with Norway. His mother Ingeborg of Norway is given a place in the regency, in both Sweden and Norway. July 23 – A Knights Hospitaller fleet scores a crushing victory over an Aydinid fleet, off Chios.

Year 1532 ( MDXXXII ) was a leap year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) that occurred on the Gregorian calendar on the 23rd day of the month of December. The year started on Thursday, 1401, at midnight. It was a year of 14 days. It was the second-shortest in the modern calendar.The year 1532 is also known as 1431–31–2, 1431, 1431–31–3, 1431–31–10, 1531, 1502, and 1602.Year 1533 (MDXXXVIII) was an extra long leap year that began on Friday, 16 December. The year started on Tuesday, 15 September at noon.It was the seventh-shortest in the modern calendar.

In the Swedish calendar it was a common year starting on Tuesday , one day ahead of the Julian and Gregorian calendar's start date. It was a special day in Sweden because it was the day before Christmas and the day after Yule. The Künstlerwerk (literally, "classical music workshop") is an association of composers, conductors, and performers. It is located in Göteborg, in the city centre of Göteborg. The association was founded in 1907 by Johannes Künstler (1871–1955), who had already created a concert orchestra and an association of chamber musicians called the Königsbrück.

Year 1193 ( MCXCIII ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) in Britain, but in France, Switzerland, Germany and other European countries starting on Sunday. The year begins with Christmas Day, on which there are six official days of public observance, one on Monday, one each Tuesday, Friday, Monday, Wednesday, Thursday, and Saturday, and Christmas Day itself. This is in contrast to the United States, which has four days of public observance in addition to Christmas Eve, but none of the official national holidays.

Charles Pierce (July 14, 1926 – May 31, 1999) was one of the 20th century's foremost female impersonators, particularly noted for his impersonation of Bette Davis.Life and careerBorn in Watertown, New York, he began his show business career playing the organ and acting in radio dramas at station WWNY. He branched out into a comedy routine, attired in tuxedo, yet managing to evoke eerily convincing imitations of popular movie actresses. Eschewing the term drag queen, which he hated, he billed himself as a male actress.Initially playing in small gay clubs, his fame spread.

Mariner 3 ( together with Mariner 4 known as Mariner-Mars 1964 ) was one of two identical deep-space probes designed by the American National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) in response to the need for a spacecraft capable of operating in a polar orbit at high-latitude. It was a derivative of a predecessor project called Mariner 2 and was designed primarily to study the Sun. The probe was launched on 20 May 1964 by a Titan IIIB booster and completed one of its planned 12 orbits around the Sun before being lost at around 1.1 million kilometers (649,000 mi) from the Sun.

Year 1194 ( MCXCIV ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Roman Catholic Gregorian calendar, which replaced the Julian calendar. In this calendar year, April 20 is the first Sunday of Lent—the start of Lent. In computer science, a hash function is a function that maps an arbitrary input to an arbitrary output. This is accomplished through a sequence of operations called the hash function function calculation, or hash function iteration, that iterates through a set of fixed inputs and outputs the hash value of each.

Michelangelo Antonioni ( , ; 29 September 1912 – 30 July 2007 ) was an Italian film director , screenwriter, and composer, known for his avant-garde works, such as La Jetée (1960), L'Age d'Or (1961), The 400 Blows (1966), and L'avventura (1970).BiographyBiographyBorn in Milan to a professional dancer and actress, Antonioni was raised in his family's opera house, and as a teenager developed a taste for film. While in high school, Antonioni joined the Milan Film School and graduated in 1924 with a BSc degree.

Year 1302 ( MCCCII ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Gregorian calendar.It was one of the first years of the Eleventh Hour of the calendar.The eleventh hour, which is a measure equal to 365.2425 minutes, was created at the Council of Trent in the year 1546 when Pope Gregory XII gave it the status of the ninth hour. The International Monetary Fund or IMF is an organization that is an international institution established by the United Nations to manage the flow of monetary and financial resources among participating countries.

Year 1298 (MCCXCVIII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events By areaAsia August 28 – Emperor Go-Fushimi succeeds Emperor Fushimi on the throne of Japan. John Tarchaneiotes is appointed governor of the southern portions of Byzantine Anatolia.Europe April 20 – Rintfleisch-Pogrom: The Jews of Röttingen are burned en masse; other Jewish communities are destroyed later in the year. June 1 – Battle of Turaida: Residents of Riga and the Grand Duchy of Lithuania defeat the Livonian Order. July 2 – Battle of Göllheim: Albert I of Habsburg defeats and kills Adolf of Nassau-Weilburg.

Year 1354 (MCCCLIV) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  Early in the year – Ibn Battuta returns from his travels at the command of Abu Inan Faris, sultan of Morocco, who appoints a scribe to write an account of the adventures. February 12 –  The Treaty of Stralsund settles border disputes between the duchies of Mecklenburg and Pomerania. March 2 –  The Gallipoli earthquake occurs, followed within a month by Turkish capture and settlement (see Fall of Gallipoli).

Ernest Orlando Lawrence (August 8, 1901 – August 27, 1958) was a pioneering American nuclear scientist and winner of the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1939 for his invention of the cyclotron. He is known for his work on uranium-isotope separation for the Manhattan Project, as well as for founding the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory and the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory.A graduate of the University of South Dakota and University of Minnesota, Lawrence obtained a PhD in physics at Yale in 1925. In 1928, he was hired as an associate professor of physics at the University of California, Berkeley, becoming the youngest full professor there two years later.

Andrew Stuart `` Andy '' Fastow ( born December 22 , 1961 ) is a convicted felon and former financier and stockbroker. As a former stockbroker and director of Fidelity National Bank, Fastow was convicted of federal securities fraud and racketeering in 2000. He served 30 months of a five-year sentence, which was reduced to 19 months because of good conduct, on September 13, 2006. He is currently in the process of appealing the conviction, which is scheduled to be decided in late 2016.Early life and careerIn 1969, Fastow was born in the Bronx to an American Jewish family.

Year 1439 (MCDXXXIX) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  May 4 – Battle of Grotnik: Władysław III's royal army defeats the Hussite movement in Poland. June 29 – Date of Venerable Macarius' Miracle of the Moose, according to Russian hagiographers. July 6 – Pope Eugene IV issues the Bull of Union with the Greeks, proclaiming the end of the East–West Schism, which was repudiated by most eastern bishops shortly thereafter. September 8 – Cardinal Giovanni Vitelleschi captures Foligno, ending Trinci's signoria.

Year 1446 ( MCDXLVI ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) in England, Wales and Scotland, and on Sunday in Ireland. In Scotland, it is the 12 th of July, while in England, Wales and Northern Ireland its year starts on the Friday after Easter Sunday. Anarchism and syndicalism are two of the four schools of political and economic thought in anarchism. While they have very different roots and different emphases, the two can be grouped together in that they share a strong focus on political decentralisation and voluntary organisation, and an opposition to institutionalised authority and class society.

Year 1406 ( MCDVI ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Sunday, or Saturday depending on when the day before and the day after Monday fall. In mathematics (mathematical logic), modus ponens is a modus  for which the proposition "for every natural number x, and for every non-zero natural number y, the cardinality of  is " can be proved. It was introduced in 1582 by Leonhard Euler and named after Ponce de León's use of it to prove a result about the power set.

Year 1373 (MCCCLXXIII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March 24 – The Treaty of Santarém is signed between Ferdinand I of Portugal and Henry II of Castile, ending the second war between the two countries. April 28 – Hundred Years' War: The French re-capture most of Brittany from the English, but are unable to take Brest. May 13 – English anchoress Dame Julian of Norwich receives the sixteen Revelations of Divine Love. June 16 – The Anglo-Portuguese Treaty is signed in London, and is the oldest active treaty in the world.

Year 1056 (MLVI) was a leap year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  August 31 – Empress Theodora (a sister of the former Empress Zoë) dies after a 18-month reign, by a sudden illness at Constantinople. She is succeeded by Michael VI (the Old), who had served as military finance minister under the former Emperor Romanos III. Michael is appointed through the influence of Leo Paraspondylos, Theodora's most trusted adviser. This ends the Macedonian Dynasty.

Gerard Pieter Hendrik van Velde (born 30 November 1971) is a Dutch retired speed skater who specialised in sprinting. He won an Olympic gold medal in 2002.BiographyVan Velde was considered the best Dutch sprinter during the early 1990s, but did not manage to win a medal in either the 1992 or 1994 Winter Olympics. The 1992 Games were particularly frustrating, as he missed a bronze medal by only one-hundredth of a second.During the late 1990s, clap skates became standard in Olympic competition. Van Velde had such difficulty adjusting to the techniques required with these new skates that he retired from skating and became a car salesman.

A semi-automatic rifle is an autoloading rifle that fires one round each pull of the trigger. For comparison, a bolt-action rifle requires the user to cycle the bolt manually before they can fire a second time, and a fully automatic rifle, provided it has ammunition, will continue to fire until the trigger is released. Most modern automatic rifles are selective fire, meaning the user can fire semi-automatically if desired.HistoryThe first design of a recoil-operated semi-automatic rifle is attributed to Ferdinand Mannlicher, who unveiled the design in 1885 based on work begun in 1883.

Mariner 10 was an American robotic space probe launched by NASA on 3 November 1973, to fly by the planets Mercury and Venus. It was the first spacecraft to perform flybys of multiple planets.Mariner 10 was launched approximately two years after Mariner 9 and was the last spacecraft in the Mariner program. (Mariner 11 and Mariner 12 were allocated to the Voyager program and redesignated Voyager 1 and Voyager 2. )The mission objectives were to measure Mercury's environment, atmosphere, surface, and body characteristics and to make similar investigations of Venus.

A mace is a blunt weapon , a type of club or virge that uses a heavy head on the end that is swung to inflict various forms of harm, including crushing blows. It is also used to threaten and intimidate. They were popular weapons in the Roman military.Maces were popular weapons in the Roman military and they were also used as weapons during the early medieval period in Germany. A mandolin  or mando  (also  or ) is a traditional mandolin-style guitar. It is played with an acoustic guitar neck attached to the mandolin body.

Year 1538 ( MDXXXVIII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Julian or Gregorian calendar system.The year is considered to start on the first Tuesday in February, which is known as Epiphany Day in the Catholic Church. During the Renaissance, the Julian calendar gradually evolved into the Gregorian calendar, with February 29 moving to the first day of the following month. The Green Bank Telescope (GBT) is a United States observatory located in West Virginia. It was built in the 1970s to replace the Mount Wilson Observatory (MWO).
