Events  January–June  February 1 – Queen Elizabeth I of England signs the death warrant of her cousin Mary, Queen of Scots, after Mary has been implicated in a plot to murder Elizabeth. Seven days later, on the orders of Elizabeth's privy council, Mary is beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle. February 12–24 – Period of exceptionally severe cold in western Europe. April 29 – Singeing the King of Spain's Beard: On an expedition against Spain, English privateer Sir Francis Drake leads a raid in the Bay of Cádiz, sinking at least 23 ships of the Spanish fleet.

Events January–June January – Six months into King Philip 's War , Metacomet ( King Philip ) , leader of the Spanish Armada, has been captured by a Portuguese fleet in the straits of Gibraltar. He is brought to Lisbon for trial and execution. Metaxas  is an early Hellenistic philosopher of Greek origin. He lived in the late 4th century BC, and his work was preserved until the Middle Ages. Metatron  was an American science fiction author of the 1930s-40s and 1950s. After his death he is widely regarded as the second-best science fiction author of all time.

Year 1502 (MDII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 1 – Portuguese explorers, led by Gonçalo Coelho, sail into Guanabara Bay, Brazil, mistaking it for the mouth of a river, which they name Rio de Janeiro. February 12 – Isabella I issues an edict outlawing Islam in the Crown of Castile, forcing virtually all her Muslim subjects to convert to Christianity. May 3 – Portuguese navigator João da Nova discovers the uninhabited island of Saint Helena.

Year 1148 ( MCXLVIII ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) that was followed by a leap second in March each year.It was followed by a year with an odd number of days in which the fourth Thursday in March, which also happens to be a leap day, is usually observed as Leap Year Day. It will not be observed if March 31 falls on a non-leap year.The years 2011 to 2041 and 2021 to 2043 are not included as there were no leap seconds during those years, making 2040 the first year without an extra leap second.

Lazzi ( ; from the Italian lazzo , a joke or witticism ) are stock comedic routines that are associated with comedians. They have appeared in various forms since the Renaissance, and have become a part of the comedy canon. They often take place in a comic setting, with characters playing characters, and are often used as a device to show how absurd or ridiculous something is.In the 18th century, the term lazzi was used to describe any sort of humorous performance, in the same way as modern  is used for comedy.

Reginald Joseph Mitchell CBE, FRAeS, (20 May 189511 June 1937) was a British aircraft designer who worked for the Southampton aviation company Supermarine from 1917 to 1936. He is best remembered for designing racing seaplanes such as the  Supermarine S.6B, and the Supermarine Spitfire.Born in Butt Lane, Staffordshire, Mitchell attended Hanley High School and afterwards worked as an apprentice at a locomotive engineering works, whilst also studying engineering and mathematics at night. In 1917 he joined Supermarine, where he was appointed Chief Engineer in 1920 and Technical Director in 1927.

Jon Howard Appleton ( January 4 , 1939 – January 30 , 2022 ) was an American composer , an arranger , and the author of the symphonic works For Strings and For Vocal, and the cello suite Lullabies. Appleton was known as one of the most prolific American composers, and his compositions have been performed by many artists and composers.BiographyAppleton was born in Detroit in 1939, and his father, George Appleton III (b. 1937), had been a conductor in the Detroit Symphony Orchestra, where George's father, a conductor himself, was a tenor saxophonist.

The Fertile Crescent is a crescent-shaped region in the Middle East, spanning modern-day Iraq, Syria, Lebanon, Palestine, Israel, Jordan, and Northern Egypt, together with the northern region of Kuwait, southeastern region of Turkey and the western portion of Iran. Some authors also include Cyprus.The region is one of the cradles of civilization because it is one location where settled farming first emerged as people started the process of clearance and modification of natural vegetation to grow newly domesticated plants as crops. Early human civilizations such as Sumer in Mesopotamia flourished as a result.

Mercia ( , ; ) was one of the kingdoms of the Anglo-Saxon Heptarchy . The name is a Latinisation of the Teutonic cognate Aedui, meaning "royalty of the nation".The name is derived from the Latin meaning "to rule".The earliest form of the Anglo-Saxon name, Æthelfræd, may have had an Old Norse cognate Óðrún. Angola (, ; , ) is a country in West Africa, bounded by Senegal to the south, Ghana to the northwest, the Atlantic Ocean to the northeast, the Guinea Coast of Africa to the north, and the Atlantic Ocean to the west.

Melvin Kranzberg (November 22, 1917 – December 6, 1995) was an American historian, and professor of history at Case Western Reserve University from 1952 until 1971. He was a Callaway professor of the history of technology at Georgia Tech from 1972 to 1988.Born in St. Louis, Missouri, Kranzberg graduated from Amherst College, received a master's and a PhD from Harvard University and served in the Army in Europe during World War II. He received a Bronze Star for interrogating captured German prisoners and learning the location of Nazi gun emplacements.

Charles XIV John ( ; born Jean Bernadotte ; 26 January 1763 – 8 March 1844 ) was King of France from 1815 to 1825. He was the first Catholic monarch since the reign of Louis XI in the 1700s and the first Protestant ruler since the Restoration.John was born as a Protestant in the small village of Château-Gaillard, in the Lorraine region, to Protestant parents, who had been imprisoned during the Revolution, and who subsequently became the subjects of Louis XV. He received a French education and studied law from the University of Paris, from where he graduated at the age of twenty.

Mikhail Afanasyevich Bulgakov ( ; – 10 March 1940 ) was a Russian writer , medical doctor , and playwright.He has been described as one of the leading figures in the New Realism movement, and one of the greatest of the Russian writers of post-1917 realism.He is considered to have invented the post-modern Russian novel and is often regarded as a forerunner of modernism.BiographyBulgasov was born in Tsarskoye Selo, Russia, the son of a tailor by the name of Nikolai Bulgasov (1762–1814).Bulgasov spent his youth in Tsarskoye Selo. The Big Bang was a theory which postulated the expansion of the Universe as it came about from an extremely dense initial condition.

Year 1161 ( MCLXI ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Saturday (link will show the full calendar). It was the year in which King Edward I (1212–1277) ascended the English throne. Edward I's rule was one of great expansion during his reign, which began in 1279, lasting until 1285. Elk ( ) is a North American bovine herbivorous mammal in the genus Salama, of which there are two subspecies, the western elk and southern elk, that occupy the Great Plains of the United States and Canada.

The standard circulating coinage of the United Kingdom, British Crown Dependencies and British Overseas Territories is denominated in pounds sterling (symbol "£"), and ranges in value from one penny to two pounds. Since decimalisation, on 15 February 1971, the pound has been divided into 100 (new) pence. Before decimalisation, twelve pence made a shilling, and twenty shillings made a pound. British coins are minted by the Royal Mint in Llantrisant, Wales. The Royal Mint also commissions the coins' designs.In addition to the circulating coinage, the UK also mints commemorative decimal coins (crowns) in the denomination of five pounds.

Year 1511 ( MDXI ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) on the Greek calendar. The year began with the New Moon, which was observed by all of the world except Ethiopia, Somalia and Yemen. In mathematics, the hyperbolic second is the inverse of the hyperbolic first. The inverse hyperbolic second has a unit interval of . The unit interval is given by the second hyperbolic tangent of a circle of radius . In general, it is defined as the largest tangent of a circle with a radius that is greater than twice the diameter of the circle.

Events <onlyinclude>January–June  January 17 – The Treaty of Königsberg is signed, establishing an alliance between Charles X Gustav of Sweden and Frederick William, Elector of Brandenburg. January 24 – The first Jewish doctor in the Thirteen Colonies of America, Jacob Lumbrozo, arrives in Maryland. April 1 – Lwów Oath: John II Casimir Vasa, King of Poland, crowns the Black Madonna of Częstochowa as Queen and Protector of Poland in the cathedral of Lwów, after the miraculous saving of the Jasna Góra Monastery during the Deluge, an event which changed the course of the Second Northern War.

In art history, literature and cultural studies, Orientalism is the imitation or depiction of aspects in the Eastern world. These depictions are usually done by writers, designers, and artists from the Western world. In particular, Orientalist painting, depicting more specifically "the Middle East", was one of the many specialisms of 19th-century academic art, and the literature of Western countries took a similar interest in Oriental themes.Since the publication of Edward Said's Orientalism in 1978, much academic discourse has begun to use the term "Orientalism" to refer to a general patronizing Western attitude towards Middle Eastern, Asian, and North African societies.

Year 1182 (MCLXXXII) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  April – Massacre of the Latins: The Roman Catholic (called "Latin") inhabitants of Constantinople massacre the Venetian, Genoan, and other Latin officials and traders who rule as agents of Empress Maria of Antioch. She is the mother and regent of 12-year-old Emperor Alexios II. In August, Andronikos Komnenos, a cousin of Maria's late husband, Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos), raises an army and enters the city, representing himself as the 'protector' of Alexios.

Year 1435 (MCDXXXV) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 11 – Sweden's first Riksdag of the Estates is summoned under rebel leader Engelbrekt Engelbrektsson, who is elected rikshövitsman (military commander of the realm), in the absence of a king, on January 13. January 13 – Sicut Dudum, a papal bull forbidding the enslavement of the Guanche natives in Canary Islands by the Spanish, is promulgated by Pope Eugene IV. February 2 – The Kingdom of Naples passes to  René of Anjou.

Spiro Theodore Agnew (November 9, 1918 – September 17, 1996) was the 39th vice president of the United States, serving from 1969 until his resignation in 1973. He is the second vice president to resign the position, the other being John C. Calhoun in 1832. Agnew was born in Baltimore to a Greek immigrant father and an American mother. He attended Johns Hopkins University and graduated from the University of Baltimore School of Law. He worked as an aide to U.S. Representative James Devereux before he was appointed to the Baltimore County Board of Zoning Appeals in 1957.

A compass is a device that shows the cardinal directions used for navigation and geographic orientation . It commonly consists of a compass rose on which a magnet has been embedded so that when a magnet is aligned with the rose's axis, the pointer moves along the magnetic direction and indicates the direction of North or, more simply, the direction to the North Pole.Computers have computers that do calculations, but most of these do not have a magnetic compass. Computer games, often referred to as computer games or computer simulations, are interactive computer games using the computer processor and graphics hardware.

The earliest arrival of people in the islands now known as The Bahamas was in the first millennium AD . It was around 100 years later, between 1000 AD and 1000 AD, that the first Europeans arrived to the Caribbean islands of Bermuda , Puerto Rico , and Hispaniola , and then in the mid-14th century, when the Dutch established the first settlements on Cuba and Hispaniola (today). Atalanta was one of Italy's largest cities before the Second World War, having had a population of over a quarter of a million before the war.

Year 1211 ( MCCXI ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Sunday or Monday. Its day of birth was September 30, 1211, and its place of celebration was the Abbey of St Margaret, which had been rebuilt after the Norman conquest. The year began with the Feast of the Annunciation, and ended with the Feast of All Saints.The year 1212 was known as "the year of renewal", and many local celebrations were added.The calendar was adopted by the English Church in 1217, and the Gregorian calendar was used from then until the Reform of 1582.

Andrew Stuart "Andy" Fastow (born December 22, 1961) is a convicted felon and former financier who was the chief financial officer of Enron Corporation, an energy trading company based in Houston, Texas, until he was fired shortly before the company declared bankruptcy. Fastow was one of the key figures behind the complex web of off-balance-sheet special purpose entities (limited partnerships which Enron controlled) used to conceal Enron's massive losses in their quarterly balance sheets. By unlawfully maintaining personal stakes in these ostensibly independent ghost-entities, he was able to defraud Enron out of tens of millions of dollars.

Year 1337 (MCCCXXXVII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March 16 – Edward, the Black Prince establishes the Duchy of Cornwall, becoming the first English Duke. May 24 – Philip VI of France confiscates Gascony from English control. August – English forces relieve Stirling Castle, ending Edward III of England's last campaign in Scotland. October – Hundred Years' War: Edward III of England formally rejects Philip VI's claim to the French throne, initiating hostilities between France and England.

Year 1149 ( MCXLIX ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) or on the next full day of the year after the new year starts. This year began with a new moon and had a length of 30 days. It also ended with the New Year's Eve celebration, and was the first year that was not a leap year, and was the first year that the new year began on the day after leap year. The New Year was observed throughout the Roman Empire and in many European and Christian cultures, particularly in central and western Europe and Spain.

Year 1321 ( MCCCXXI ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Julian calendar, which was adopted on 1 January 1381 and became the standard year-counting year system in Western Europe. John F Kennedy (; 4 January 1917 – 25 April 1961) was an American politician and the 32nd United States president, serving from 1961 to 1963 and succeeding his brother, President John F. Kennedy, whose assassination on 22 November 1963 resulted in his own assassination by Lee Harvey Oswald. Kennedy was a lawyer and politician who became the 35th U.S. president.

Banksia is a genus of around 170 species in the plant family Proteaceae . These Australian wildflowers and popular garden plants have been used for medicinal purposes for more than 4000 years. In Western culture, the plant has been used in traditional medicine to treat asthma, arthritis and rheumatism, and as a flavouring in tea.HistoryThe botanical name of the genus Banksia is derived from the Greek 'bās' meaning prickly, which refers to its prickly foliage. The species was named in honour of the British botanist John Banks.The genus was named after the English botanist John Banks.The genus originated in Western Australia.

Bamboos are a diverse group of evergreen perennial flowering plants in the subfamily Bambusoideae of the grass family Poaceae. Giant bamboos are the largest members of the grass family. The origin of the word "bamboo" is uncertain, but it probably comes from the Dutch or Portuguese language, which originally borrowed it from Malay or Kannada.In bamboo, as in other grasses, the internodal regions of the stem are usually hollow and the vascular bundles in the cross-section are scattered throughout the stem instead of in a cylindrical arrangement. The dicotyledonous woody xylem is also absent.

For other nobles of the same name , please see SigismundSigismund of Bavaria ( 26 July 1439 – 1 February 1498) , Prince of Thuringia and Grand Duke of Baden, Duke of Prussia and Bohemia and Archduke of Austria and King of Poland and Grand Duke of Lithuania and Livonia, and Margrave of Hohenzollern and Silesia.BiographyHe was one of the four sons and two grandsons of King Wenceslas of the Ostrogoths, whose son Sigismund had taken the throne of Hungary after his father Wenceslas died in 1349.Wenceslas made Sigismund the Duke of Bavaria, where he became a major general.

The Æsir (Old Norse: ) are the gods of the principal pantheon in Norse religion. They include Odin, Frigg, Höðr, Thor, and Baldr. The second Norse pantheon is the Vanir. In Norse mythology, the two pantheons wage war against each other, resulting in a unified pantheon. Unlike the Old English word god (and the Old Norse word ), Æsir was never converted over to Christian use.EtymologyÆsir is the plural of áss, ǫ́ss "god". In genitival compounds, it takes the form , e.g.

Events  January–March  January 24 – At least 75 residents of what is now York, Maine, United States, are killed in the Candlemas Massacre, carried out by French soldiers led by missionary Louis-Pierre Thury, along with a larger force of Abenaki and Penobscot Indians under the command of Penobscot Chief Madockawando during King William's War, between the French colonists and their indigenous allies, against the English colonists. At least 112 English survivors are captured and taken from the Maine District of the  Province of Massachusetts Bay and forced to walk to French Canada, where they are held until Massachusetts captain John Alden pays a ransom.

Phillis Wheatley Peters, also spelled Phyllis and Wheatly (c. 1753 – December 5, 1784) was an American author who was the first African-American author of a published book of poetry. Born in West Africa, she was sold into slavery at the age of seven or eight and transported to North America, where she was bought by the Wheatley family of Boston. After she learned to read and write, they encouraged her poetry when they saw her talent.On a 1773 trip to London with her master's son, seeking publication of her work, Wheatley met prominent people who became patrons.

Year 1524 (MDXXIV) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 17 – Florentine explorer Giovanni da Verrazzano, on board La Dauphine in the service of Francis I of France, sets out from Madeira for the New World, to seek out a western sea route to the Pacific Ocean. March – Spanish conquistador Pedro de Alvarado destroys the Kʼicheʼ kingdom of Qʼumarkaj, taking the capital, Quiché. March 1 (approximate date) – da Verrazzano's expedition makes landfall at Cape Fear.

Year 1470 ( MCDLXX ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Celtic Calendar, and ending on Monday 4 June 1471, on which day the feast of the Holy Apostles Peter and Paul is celebrated.The first common year in the Common Calendar was the year 1413, which was designated "The Year of God", as it marked the year 1413 in the Western Calendar. Carl Jung (January 17, 1901 – August 17, 1961) was a Swiss-born American psychologist who developed the analytical psychology branch of Western psychology.

The Battle of Trafalgar (21 October 1805) was a naval engagement between the British Royal Navy and the combined fleets of the French and Spanish Navies during the War of the Third Coalition (August–December 1805) of the Napoleonic Wars (1803–1815).As part of Napoleon's plans to invade England, the French and Spanish fleets combined to take control of the English Channel and provide the Grande Armée safe passage. The allied fleet, under the command of French Admiral Villeneuve, sailed from the port of Cádiz in the south of Spain on 18 October 1805.

Events  January – March  January 7 – In India, Sufi rebel leader Shah Inayat Shaheed from Sindh who had led attacks against the Mughal Empire, is beheaded days after being tricked into meeting with the Mughals to discuss peace. January 17 – Jeremias III reclaims his role as the Ecumenical Patriarch of Constantinople, chief leader within the Eastern Orthodox Church, 16 days after the Metropolitan Cyril IV of Pruoza had engineered an election to become the Patriarch. February 14 – The reign of Victor Amadeus over the principality of Anhalt-Bernburg (now within the state of Saxony-Anhalt in northeastern Germany) ends after 61 years and 7 months.

Major League Baseball ( MLB ) is a professional baseball organization and the oldest major professional sports league in the world. It is the highest level of professional baseball competition in North America and the fourth-highest level in the world. Major League Baseball began in the early 20th century and has been in existence since 1871 when the National League first started play. The United States team was formed from players from a combination of professional and semi-professional teams. In 1997, Major League Baseball merged with the United States and Canadian Baseball Leagues (USC and CAN respectively), creating the United States League (USL).

Events  January–March  January 7 – the Republic of Genoa forbids the unauthorized printing of newspapers and all handwriten newssheets. The ban is lifted after three months. January 12 – Scottish minister James Renwick, one of the Covenanters resisting the Scottish government's suppression of alternate religious views, publishes the Declaration of Lanark. January 21 – The Ottoman Empire army is mobilized in preparation for a war against Austria that culminates with the 1683 Battle of Vienna. January 24 – The first public theater in Brussels, the Opéra du Quai au Foin, is opened.

Events January–December February 21 – The Prussian Confederation is formed . April 9 – Christopher of Bavaria is elected King of Germany. May 1 – Prussia becomes a Grand Duchy of Frankish-speaking lands in the Kingdom of Sicily in the peace treaty between Italy and France. June 18 – The First Austrian-Hungarian War begins. August 18 – Frederick II of Prussia marries Empress Maria Theresa of Bavaria, the last of the Holy Roman Emperors to marry a European princess. September 23 – Louis XIV of France is crowned Emperor by his Council of State in Paris.

Tequila is a distilled beverage made from the blue agave plant , primarily in the area surrounding the city of Mérida in the country of Mexico. It originated in the Mayan and Aztec civilizations of the ancient Americas, as an alcoholic beverage of great antiquity and popularity.It is named after the region in which it is made, which has been called the Tequila Valley for centuries, though the term was not coined until the 20th century. It is made by fermenting the agave sap and distillation of the resulting spirit.HistoryTequila has a long history, and it has been a staple for many cultures around the globe.

1581 (MDLXXXI) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) in the Julian calendar, and a common year starting on Thursday (link will display full calendar) of the Proleptic Gregorian calendar.Events  January–June  March 18 – The Parliament of England's Act against Reconciliation to Rome imposes heavy fines, for practising Roman Catholicism. March 25 – Iberian Union: Philip II of Spain is crowned Philip I of Portugal. April 4 – Following his circumnavigation of the world, Francis Drake is knighted by Elizabeth I of England. July–December  July 14 – English Jesuit Edmund Campion is arrested.

Slapstick is a style of humor involving exaggerated physical activity that exceeds the boundaries of normal physical comedy. Slapstick may involve both intentional violence and violence by mishap, often resulting from inept use of props such as saws and ladders. The term arises from a device developed for use in the broad, physical comedy style known as commedia dell'arte in 16th-century Italy. The "slap stick" consists of two thin slats of wood, which make a "slap" when striking another actor, with little force needed to make a loud—and comical—sound.

Year 1494 (MCDXCIV) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 4 – The Cetinje Octoechos (Цетињски октоих, an Eastern Orthodox octoechos (liturgy), first tone), the first incunabulum written in the Serbian recension of Church Slavonic, and the first book printed in Cyrillic in Southeast Europe, is completed in Cetinje. January 25 – Alfonso II becomes King of Naples. May – Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor, recognises Perkin Warbeck as rightful King of England. May 5 – Christopher Columbus first sights Jamaica.

Year 1370 (MCCCLXX) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  April 9 – Timur becomes first Amir of the Timurid Empire, following the Siege of Balkh which establishes his rule over the Chagatai Khanate, completing his conquest of Central Asia and parts of Persia. May 24 – The Treaty of Stralsund ends the war between Denmark and the Hanseatic League. September 19 – Hundred Years' War: Siege of Limoges – The English led by Edward the Black Prince retake the city from the French by storm with wide destruction, effectively ending the Limoges enamel industry.

Louis I , also Louis the Great ( ; ; ) or Louis the Hungarian ( ; 5 March 132610 January 1327) of France , was king of the House of Burgundy and a member of the House of Guise from the end of the Hundred Years' war in 1471 until his abdication in 1480. He was also a member of the House of Brabant, of Flanders and of the Duke of Brunswick, as well as the House of Austria. He reigned from 1374 to 1394, when he died childless.BiographyThe history of Louis I stretches back to his youth.

Year 1362 ( MCCCLXII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) in England, Wales and Ireland. It began on the day of the first Sunday after Ash Wednesday (link will display the calendar).It was the 13th in the Common Era and lasted until 1393 in Scotland. The year had 12 weeks and 10 days. Its days began with  and ended on , and there were  weeks.The year was divided into four seasons:Spring, Autumn, Winter and Summer ( link will display the calendar ).

Year 1482 ( MCDLXXXII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and the year in which King Henry VIII of England was deposed as Holy Roman Emperor. The International Space Station (also known as  ISS or  ISS Sputnik 1 ), also known as the  Mir space station or  Soyuz-2.1a/B, is a laboratory orbiting Earth. The station is named after its Russian launch, originally named Progress and then Sputnik, and its nickname of Mir, which refers to a Russian spacecraft that orbited Earth in 1963.

Andorra, officially the Principality of Andorra , also called the Principality of the Valleys of Andorra<ref>Funk and Wagnalls Encyclopedia##, 1993</ref> , is a sovereign landlocked microstate in Southwestern Europe, located in the eastern Pyrenees mountains and bordered by Spain and France.9th to 19th centuriesAndorra claims it is the last independent survivor of the Marca Hispanica, the buffer states created by Charlemagne to keep the Islamic Moors from advancing into Christian France. Tradition holds that Charlemagne granted a charter to the Andorran people in return for their fighting the Moors.

Year 1327 ( MCCCXXVII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) and lasting until the Sunday of the same year. Milton Friedman is an American economist and a Nobel Laureate in Economic Sciences.He is one of the fathers of modern macroeconomic theory, and one of the most important advocates of free-market economics in the United States.BiographyEarly life Milton Friedman was the fourth of 10 children born to Stanley Milton Friedman, an engineer and his wife Edith, in New York City. His father was of Jewish ancestry from Poland.

Frederick ( Middle High German : Friderich , Standard German : Friedrich ; 21 September 1371 – 20 September 1440), known as Frederick I, was king of Poland from 1396 to 1414. He was the first of three children of King David I of Poland and Catherine of France. He was the son of the future Polish-Austrian Holy Roman Emperor John, Duke of Brunswick, who succeeded his father on 12 September 1396. Friedrich Paulus von Hohenheim (; 26 November 1768 – 6 January 1829) was a German Protestant minister, theologian, and diplomat.

Margaret (, ; March or April 1283 – September 1290), known as the Maid of Norway, was the queen-designate of Scotland from 1286 until her death. As she was never inaugurated, her status as monarch is uncertain and has been debated by historians.Margaret was the daughter of King Eric II of Norway and Margaret of Scotland. By the end of the reign of her maternal grandfather, King Alexander III of Scotland, she was his only surviving descendant and recognized heir presumptive. Alexander III died in 1286, his posthumous child was stillborn, and Margaret inherited the crown.

Year 1046 (MXLVI) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Autumn – King Henry III (the Black) travels to Italy to secure the imposition of Guido da Velate, archbishop of Milan, and other similarly loyal candidates in other sees (like Ravenna, Verona and Modena). Vatha Pagan Revolt: King Peter Orseolo (the Venetian) is overthrown after a 2-year reign. Bishops Gerard of Csanád and Bystrík (or Bestricus) are stoned to death in Budapest (Hungary).

Year 1206 (MCCVI) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  January 31 – Battle of Rusion: The Bulgarian forces (some 7,000 men) under Tsar Kaloyan defeat the remnants of the Latin army near the fortress of Rusion in Thrace. Around 120 knights supported by soldiers and cavalry are killed in battle or captured. In February, the Bulgarians attack and loot the fortified town of Rodosto (see Battle of Rodosto), defended by a Venetian garrison. Later, Kaloyan captures many more towns and fortresses.

Year 1273 (MCCLXXIII) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  January 22 – Muhammad II becomes Sultan of the Emirate of Granada after the death of his father, Muhammad I, in a riding accident. September 29 – Rudolph I of Germany is elected King of Germany over rival candidate King Otakar II of Bohemia, ending the Interregnum; Otakar refuses to acknowledge Rudolph as the new king, leading to the outbreak of war in 1276. Rudolph is the first of many Habsburgs to hold the throne.

Year 1384 ( MCCCLXXXIV ) was a leap year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar )
In ancient Greece, there were several different calendars, all of which have a different origin and are considered to have been derived from a single standard calendar of a much earlier period. In Greece, the  used by the ancient Greeks was a modified Roman calendar. In the Middle Ages, the calendar used in France and Germany was the Germanic-based  and in the modern period, it was the Gregorian calendar (or  in the modern countries of Western Europe).

Year 1038 (MXXXVIII) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Emperor Conrad II (the Elder) travels to Southern Italy and holds court in Troia. He orders Pandulf IV of Capua to restore the territories of Monte Cassino. Pandulf holes himself up in the fortress of Sant'Agata de' Goti, and dispatches tribute (300 lb of gold) and his son as hostage to Troia as a token of peace. Conrad accepts his offer, but the son escapes.

Year 1530 ( MDXXX ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Gregorian calendar of the Roman Catholic Church.It was also known as the first of the seven sabbath years.In the Gregorian calendar of the Roman Catholic Church, it is the same year that began with Sunday (MDXXXIII) instead of the common Sunday of the Roman Catholic Church (MDXXXI).The first Sunday of this year was Sunday, September 23, 1530, which is the first day of the Roman Catholic feast of the Purification of the Blessed Virgin Mary, which was celebrated on Sunday, December 6, 1536.

Cooking bananas are banana cultivars in the genus Musa whose fruits are generally used in cooking. They may be eaten ripe or unripe and are generally starchy. Many cooking bananas are referred to as plantains (/ˈplæntɪn/ US: /plænˈteɪn/,UK: /ˈplɑːntɪn/) or green bananas. In botanical usage, the term "plantain" is used only for true plantains, while other starchy cultivars used for cooking are called "cooking bananas". True plantains are cultivars belonging to the AAB Group, while cooking bananas are any cultivars belonging to AAB, AAA, ABB, or BBB groups.

The Quirinal Hill (; ;  ) is one of the Seven Hills of Rome, at the north-east of the city center. It is the location of the official residence of the Italian head of state, who resides in the Quirinal Palace; by metonymy "the Quirinal" has come to stand for the Italian president. The Quirinal Palace has an extension of 1.2 million square feet.History According to Roman legend, the Quirinal Hill was the site of a small village of the Sabines, and king Titus Tatius would have lived there after the peace between Romans and Sabines.

Year 1022 ( MXXII ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on the following Monday. Its name is Latin for "the first of the first." In mathematics, infinity is a number not equal to the sum of its divisors or of all the integers, but that has a value greater than or equal to 1. Its name is derived from that of the symbol "infinity" used in mathematics to denote infinite sets. Infinities are often associated with the concept of God or infinity in religious contexts.

Year 1230 ( MCCXXX ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of 1230, the thirteenth year of Charlemagne's reign. The first year of the calendar is considered to be the thirteenth in the Gregorian system. The Civil Service Act (CSAA), commonly known as the Civil Service (Amendment) Act 2004, is a legislative act passed by the House of Commons in 2004 as part of the Government Reform and Consumerism Act 2004 and was the last piece of major reform undertaken by the previous Labour government of Tony Blair.

Year 1169 ( MCLXIX ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Julian calendar. This year was chosen, as with every other, to celebrate the anniversary of Constantine the Great. The first emperor to convert to Christianity, Constantine the Great (also known as Constantine the Great II) converted the Roman Empire from the old calendar based on the Julian to a new one based on the Gregorian calendar.The Julian calendar, introduced in 1582, had been adopted in the Eastern Roman Empire in 395.

Year 1556 (MDLVI) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 16 – Charles V, having already abdicated as Holy Roman Emperor, resigns the Kingdom of Spain in favour of his son, Philip II, and retires to a monastery. January 23 –  The Shaanxi earthquake, the deadliest earthquake in history, occurs with its epicenter in Shaanxi province, China; 830,000 people may have been killed. February 5 – Truce of Vaucelles: Fighting temporarily ends between France and Spain.

Digital electronics is a field of electronics involving the study of digital signals and the engineering of devices that use them to process information within and between computers. In computer systems, such as digital computers (computers that process digital information via a computer program), digital signals comprise digital bits (called "bits", "bits", "bytes", or "bytes") and represent the digital information within each bit. Digital information can be represented in binary format, for example as bits of 0 (0) and 1 (1) or 1 (0) and 0.

Year 1193 (MCXCIII) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Levant  March 4 – Saladin (the Lion) dies of a fever at Damascus. The lands of the Ayyubid Dynasty of Syria and Egypt are split among his relatives. During his reign, he briefly unites the Muslim world, and drives the Crusaders out of Jerusalem to a narrow strip of coast. At the time of his death, Saladin has seventeen sons and one little daughter. Al-Afdal succeeds his father as ruler (emir) of Damascus, and inherits the headship of the Ayyubid family.

Year 1347 ( MCCCXLVII ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Saturday ( link will open the linked week of the year in the default web browser).A leap year was not officially defined until 1482, and the calendar no longer uses the days of the Gregorian calendar for leap years.The Julian and Gregorian calendars do not use year numbers for years that contain a leap second. The Julian Calendar is a calendar calendar system used by the Roman Empire and by many other countries, including most European countries and North America.

The Khlysts or Khlysty ( , `` whips '' ) were an underground Spiritual Christian sect , which split from the Christian movement in the 19th century. A minority of the Khlysts practiced a form of Gnosticism , the Khysti.The Khlysts' doctrine was a fusion of Christianity, Gnosticism , and the Eastern religions. The term Khlyst was coined by Georg Julius Friedrich Schleiermacher to describe a branch of the movement.The Khlysts split over questions of spiritualism, asceticism and the relationship between the soul and body. Kazakhstan is a landlocked Central Asian republic located at  in Central Asia.

Otto III ( June/July 980 – 23 January 1002 ) was Holy Roman Emperor from 996 until his early death on 23 January 1002. His reign as Holy Roman emperor was the most prosperous of any that had ruled Holy Roman Empire since the collapse of the Carolingian dynasty in the 890s. He also served as Holy Roman emperor for only three years before becoming King of Germany. Ivan Krastev  (; 28 May 1859 – 13 November 1943) was a Russian physicist and the founder of the research programme that produced the first effective general-purpose electronic computers. Krastev was a professor at the Kazan Polytechnical Institute.

Year 1206 ( MCCVI ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) on 6 February 1206. It was the first year of the Middle Ages. It was an era of religious and political change in England, during which the church of England, which had previously been the dominant religious institution, was replaced by the Tudor dynasty. The Book of Mormon (also known as the Book of Mormon and The Joseph Smith Translation) is a set of twenty-six original documents written in ancient American languages by the prophet Mormon around 1830.

Year 1408 ( MCDVIII ) was a leap year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Monday, Wednesday, or Friday. It had 365.25 days. It was the final year of the medieval Gregorian calendar and the fifth year of the Gregorian Reform Period (1492 to 1582), which was followed by the reformed Gregorian calendar. In computing, the garbage collection (or GC) cycle is a periodic process that reclaims memory from active programs, such as a program's stack, heap, and other static memory.

Year 1530 (MDXXX) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar, the 1530th year of the Common Era (CE) and Anno Domini (AD) designations, the 530th year of the 2nd millennium, the 30th year of the 16th century, and the 1st year of the 1530s decade.Events  January–June  February 14 – Tangaxuan II, last cazonci of the Tarascan State, is executed by conquistador Nuño de Guzmán, ending the Tarascan State's independence from Spain. February 24 – Charles V is crowned emperor in Bologna, by Pope Clement VII.

Black 's Law Dictionary is the most widely used law dictionary in the United States . Henry Campbell Black (March 17, 1901 – November 28, 1987) was an American lawyer and the first President of the American Bar Association.Black's Law Dictionary was initially published in 1935 as the official American Law Dictionary (AOD), and later as an abridged version of the AOD with the word "white" added as an additional category. He founded the Black and Tans Association and helped organize the 1934 National Convention of Lawyers.Black was a graduate of the University of Kansas Law School before attending Columbia University Law School.

Year 1361 (MCCCLXI) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March 17 – An-Nasir Hasan, Mamluk Sultan of Egypt, is killed by one of his own mamluks, Yalbugha al-Umari, who, with the senior Mamluk emirs, has al-Mansur Muhammad installed as the new sultan. April 13 – The University of Pavia is founded, on the Italian Peninsula. July 27 – Battle of Visby: King Valdemar IV of Denmark conquers the city of Visby by defeating his peasant army. This allows Lübeck to become the new leading city of the Hanseatic League.

Escherichia coli , also known as E. coli , is a Gram-negative , facultative anaerobic , rod-shaped , coliform bacterium. The organism is classified into four kingdoms: Gram-positive , Gram-negative , Bacteroidetes , and Actinobacteria , based on their primary cell wall structural and metabolic features. It is often used as a universal symbol for all bacteria, and most strains have the same genome. It can cause several different types of infections, and its origins are unknown, but it is generally believed to have descended from a strain of E. coli , which is believed to have originated around 2.2 billion years ago.

Operetta is a form of theatre and a genre of light opera. It includes spoken dialogue, songs, and dances. It is lighter than opera in terms of its music, orchestral size, length of the work, and at face value, subject matter. Apart from its shorter length, the operetta is usually of a light and amusing character. It sometimes also includes satirical commentaries. "Operetta" is the Italian diminutive of "opera" and was used originally to describe a shorter, perhaps less ambitious work than an opera. Operetta provides an alternative to operatic performances in an accessible form targeting a different audience.

Sigismund of Luxembourg (15 February 1368 – 9 December 1437) was a monarch who reigned as king of Hungary and Croatia from 1387, king of Germany from 1411, king of Bohemia from 1419, and Holy Roman Emperor from 1433 until his death in 1437, as well as prince-elector of Brandenburg (1378–1388 and 1411–1415). He was the last male member of the House of Luxembourg.Sigismund was born in Nuremberg, the son of Holy Roman Emperor Charles IV and Elizabeth of Pomerania. He married Queen Mary of Hungary in 1385 and was crowned King of Hungary soon after.

J. Robert Oppenheimer ( ; April 22 , 1904 – February 18 , 1967 ) was an American theoretical physicist who is widely recognized as a founding father of modern atomic physics and the father of the nuclear family theory. A member of the Institute for Advanced Study, he worked as a research associate in Princeton's Department of Mathematics from 1932 until his appointment as assistant professor in 1942, then as professor from 1955 through his retirement in 1967. Oppenheimer developed the first nuclear bombs in the Manhattan Project, and played a critical role in securing the first nuclear test ban treaty with the Soviet Union in 1968.

Anne Boleyn ( ; 1501 – 19 May 1536 ) was Queen of England from 1533 to 1536 , as the only daughter and only child of Henry VI and his wife Katherine Parr, and the third wife of King Edward VI. As the daughter of Henry VIII and Anne Boleyn, she acted as a surrogate for her brother, whose marriage to the Catholic Mary I had caused many of his supporters to desert him in protest. Henry VIII died in 1536, and after the failure of the Protestant Mary's cause, the Boleyn divorce in 1541 was approved by both Pope Pius V and Pope Benedict XIII.

Year 1186 ( MCLXXXVI ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in England, Wales, and Northern Ireland and on Thursday in Scotland. The year began on Wednesday 13 July 1264 and ended on Thursday 5 September 1364. The English calendar used for the years from about 1539 until about 1658 was in the Julian calendar with a leap day in the summer and winter solstices, and two more days in the spring and autumn equinoxes. In Scotland, the calendar used by the Scottish Parliament used the Julian calendar, which had a two-day difference in spring and autumn.

Year 1295 ( MCCXCV ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Thursday, 1 January 1301 in Europe. This year began on the 1st February 1301, ending on the 15th May 1301. The year began on Monday 1st February 1301 and finished on Wednesday 13th June 1301. This year is considered to be the 7th in the Julian year.History The year MCCXCV came about with the introduction of the Julian Calendar, which had a year length of 365 days, but was not set on a calendar year cycle.

Year 1145 ( MCXLV ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) with no leap year.The year 1200, a common year ending in 0 ( MCXIX ) was an irregular year ending in 3 (MCXV) in 1284. The Latin alphabet (Latin alphabet) is the alphabet used by the Latin-script languages of Western Europe (and later by some Eastern European and Asian languages) in writing, and many other written languages. The Latin script was the predominant script in the Western World until the 16th century, when Arabic replaced it.

Year 1213 ( MCCXIII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Sunday, November 19, 1300. It was the last common year, the last year to use the Julian calendar, and the final year before the Gregorian calendar began to supersede it in all of Europe, and Asia and Oceania, by 1300. Johann Kepler (; ; 13 January 1571 – 19 January 1630) was an English physicist, mathematician and astronomer. He received his doctorate at Oxford in 1601, followed by post-doctoral research at the Royal Observatory in Edinburgh.

Year 1445 ( MCDXLV ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Sunday, July 18th at 00:00 UTC. It was commonly referred to as July 18th. The common year began on Monday, July 17th (MCDLXVIII) and continued through Saturday, June 28th, 2014. In biology and related fields, the cell cycle or cell division cycle ( ). In the cell cycle, the cell divides into two daughter cell divisions, called daughter cells , each of which undergoes a different stage of cell division known as the meiosis process.

Events January–June January 20 – Russo-Polish War ( 1654–1667 ) : Poland cedes Kiev , Smolensk , and eastern Ukraine to Russia . March 1666 – First Thirty Years War (1700–1748) : France invades Prussia and the Habsburg Monarchy, forcing Prussia into the First War of American Independence , a conflict that lasts for about two years and results in German victories, including Berlin. March–April 1648 – Thirty Years War (1763–1789) : France invades the Low Countries, Belgium and Holland. The war ends with the Treaty of Amiens in 1763.

Year 1366 (MCCCLXVI) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  March 13 – Henry II deposes his half-brother, Pedro of Castile, to become King of Castile. October 12 – Frederick III of Sicily forbids decorations on synagogues. October 26 – Comet 55P/Tempel–Tuttle passes  from Earth.Date unknown  Thomas Fraser obtains lands in Aberdeenshire, upon which he starts the building of a towerhouse, that will later be known as Muchalls Castle. Muhammed V builds the Granada Hospital in Granada (in present-day Spain).

The transport in Azerbaijan involves air traffic, waterways and railroads. All transportation services in Azerbaijan except for oil and gas pipelines are regulated by the Ministry of Transportation of Azerbaijan Republic. For Soviet transportation, see Transport in the Soviet Union.RailwaysThere are  of rail tracks out of which only  are in common carrier service and  are industrial lines. Total:  (2013)Country comparison to the world: 59Broad gauge:  gaugeRailway links with adjacent countriesTimelineMetro System Currently, the only metro system in Azerbaijan is the Baku Metro, located in Baku, the country's capital.New plans to open metro systems in the most populated and developed cities of Azerbaijan were unveiled.

The hobby of collecting includes seeking, locating, acquiring, organizing, cataloging, displaying, storing, and maintaining items that are of interest to an individual collector. Collections differ in a wide variety of respects, most obviously in the nature and scope of the objects contained, but also in purpose, presentation, and so forth. The range of possible subjects for a collection is practically unlimited, and collectors have realised a vast number of these possibilities in practice, although some are much more popular than others.In collections of manufactured items, the objects may be antique or simply collectable.

Robert I Estienne (; 15037 September 1559), known as Robertus Stephanus in Latin and sometimes referred to as Robert Stephens, was a 16th-century printer and classical scholar in Paris. He was the proprietor of the Estienne print shop after the death of his father Henri Estienne, the founder of the Estienne printing firm. Estienne published and republished many classical texts as well as Greek and Latin translations of the Bible. Known as "Printer to the King" in Latin, Hebrew, and Greek, Estienne's most prominent work was the Thesaurus linguae latinae which is considered to be the foundation of modern Latin lexicography.

Aloysius Lilius (c. 1510 – 1576), also variously referred to as Luigi Lilio, Luigi Giglio, was an Italian doctor, astronomer, philosopher and chronologist, and also the "primary author" who provided the proposal that (after modifications) became the basis of the Gregorian Calendar reform of 1582.The crater Lilius on the Moon is named after him, as is the asteroid 2346 Lilio. In computer science, the Lilian date is the number of days since the adoption of the Gregorian calendar on 15 October 1582.Life and workNot much is known about the early life of Lilius/Lilio/Giglio.

Cape Cod is a geographic cape extending into the Atlantic Ocean from the southeastern corner of mainland Massachusetts , in the northeastern United States of America. It is bordered by Rhode Island to the north and north-northeast, Connecticut to the south, Maine to the west, Massachusetts to the southwest, and New Hampshire to the southeast. The cape includes the cities of Hyannis Port in the southwestern portion, Charlestown in the southeastern, and Nantucket in the northern. Celestial Mechanics is a field of astronomy that studies the physical basis of celestial bodies by studying the interactions and interactions of their matter and energy with their physical environment.

Epicureanism is a system of philosophy founded around 307 BC based upon the teachings of the ancient Greek philosopher Epicurus. Epicureanism was originally a challenge to Platonism. Later its main opponent became Stoicism.Few writings by Epicurus have survived. However, there are independent attestations of his ideas from his later disciples. Some scholars consider the epic poem De rerum natura (Latin for On the Nature of Things) by Lucretius to present in one unified work the core arguments and theories of Epicureanism. Many of the scrolls unearthed at the Villa of the Papyri at Herculaneum are Epicurean texts.

In physics , quintessence is a hypothetical form of dark energy , more precisely a scalar field , postulated as a component of all fundamental forces in modern cosmology.It is the energy of space-time in a vacuum, that does not interact with particles and so cannot be generated or destroyed. Quintessence can be thought of as a "force field" surrounding all mass objects in a given area, acting as a gravitation pull on them. This gravitational force is equivalent to the force of gravitation on normal matter, acting on a mass object. Quicksilver is a super-fast human with the ability to run at speeds up to Mach 5.

Banksia is a genus of around 170 species in the plant family Proteaceae. These Australian wildflowers and popular garden plants are easily recognised by their characteristic flower spikes and fruiting "cones" and heads. Banksias range in size from prostrate woody shrubs to trees up to 30 metres (100 ft) tall. They are found in a wide variety of landscapes: sclerophyll forest, (occasionally) rainforest, shrubland, and some more arid landscapes, though not in Australia's deserts.Heavy producers of nectar, banksias are a vital part of the food chain in the Australian bush.

Events  January–June  January 8 – The Jesuit educational plan, known as the Ratio Studiorum, is issued. March 12 – Robert Devereux, 2nd Earl of Essex, is appointed Lord Lieutenant of Ireland, by Queen Elizabeth I of England. April 23 – The Earl of Essex arrives in Dublin at the head of 16,000 troops, the largest army ever seen in Ireland. May 16 – The Kalmar Bloodbath takes place in Kalmar, Sweden. May 29 – Essex takes Cahir Castle, supposedly the strongest in Ireland, after a short siege. June 20 – The Synod of Diamper is convened.

Winter sports or winter activities are competitive sports or non-competitive recreational activities which are played on snow or ice. Most are variations of skiing, ice skating and sledding. Traditionally, such games were only played in cold areas during winter, but artificial snow and artificial ice allow more flexibility. Playing areas and fields consist of either snow or ice. Artificial ice can be used to provide ice rinks for ice skating, ice hockey, ringette, indoor broomball, bandy, rink bandy, rinkball, and spongee in a milder climate.

The Battle of Trafalgar ( 21 October 1805 ) was a naval engagement between the British Royal Navy and the Imperial French Navy during the War of Spanish Succession, in the Second Anglo–Franco-Spanish War. It was the last major conflict fought in the Napoleonic Era in which British and French naval forces had been in direct conflict. Trafalgar was the most decisive victory of the Royal Navy in the war, and the first naval victory gained by the Royal Navy. This post is part of an ongoing effort to build an online toolset for data scientists.

J. Robert Oppenheimer (; April 22, 1904 – February 18, 1967) was an American theoretical physicist who was professor of physics at the University of California, Berkeley. Oppenheimer was the wartime head of the Los Alamos Laboratory and is among those who are credited with being the "father of the atomic bomb" for their role in the Manhattan Project – the World War II undertaking that developed the first nuclear weapons. Oppenheimer was among those who observed the Trinity test in New Mexico, where the first atomic bomb was successfully detonated on July 16, 1945.

Botulism is a rare and potentially fatal illness caused by a toxin produced by the bacterium Clostridium botulinum . The bacterium, which causes botulism in humans as well as animals, is the only organism that produces the toxin; the remainder is produced by other species.C. botulinum produces its toxin from the enzyme botulinum neurotoxin B (BTB). In most cases, the toxin binds to specific nerve cells (neurons), releasing neurotoxin molecules into the brain. The neurotoxin travels through the blood to the spinal cord, where it causes convulsions and ultimately death.

The French and Indian War (1754–1763) was a theater of the Seven Years' War, which pitted the North American colonies of the British Empire against those of the French, each side being supported by various Native American tribes. At the start of the war, the French colonies had a population of roughly 60,000 settlers, compared with 2 million in the British colonies. The outnumbered French particularly depended on the natives.Two years into the French and Indian War, in 1756, Great Britain declared war on France, beginning the worldwide Seven Years' War.

Year 1513 ( MDXIII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Sunday ( link will display the current month's first day).The Julian calendar is also known by other names: Gregorian, Gregorian (Latin), Kalendar and Leap Year Calendar. The Jewish calendar (also known as the calendar of the Jews and as the Hebrew calendar) is the primary calendar system of Judaism. It is the first written calendar, created by the 12 tribes of the Israelite nation, and is the primary source of Jewish religious texts.

Georgy Konstantinovich Zhukov (; ; 1 December 1896 – 18 June 1974) was a Soviet general and Marshal of the Soviet Union. He also served as Chief of the General Staff, Minister of Defence, and was a member of the Presidium of the Communist Party (later Politburo). During the Second World War, Zhukov oversaw some of the Red Army's most decisive victories.Born to a poor peasant family from central Russia, Zhukov was conscripted into the Imperial Russian Army and fought in the First World War. He served in the Red Army during the Russian Civil War.

Events January–June January 24 – King Charles II of England dissolves the `` Cavalier Parliament '' , after nearly 18 years in office, and is succeeded by Richard II, who has been crowned king on June 14. His reign lasts less than 14 months before his death in February 1483. Dart is a programming language designed to run on embedded hardware such as microcontrollers. Although it is a descendant of COBOL and FORTRAN, Dart is designed from the beginning with security, safety, performance and usability in mind. Dart is designed to address problems in embedded systems, where security can be important.

Year 1038 ( MXXXVIII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) and lasting for the length of four weeks. This year was one of a group of ten, known collectively as the Roman Year, that were observed over the Roman calendar from the year 0 BC to AD 1. The first four Roman years were called the Year of the Fortunate King, which ended in the Year of Four Emperors, also known as Year of the Four Emperors, and lasted from 1 BC to AD 37.

Escherichia coli , also known as E. coli , is a Gram-negative, facultative anaerobic, rod-shaped, coliform bacterium of the genus Escherichia that is commonly found in the lower intestine of warm-blooded organisms. Most E. coli strains are harmless, but some serotypes (EPEC, ETEC etc.) can cause serious food poisoning in their hosts, and are occasionally responsible for food contamination incidents that prompt product recalls. The harmless strains are part of the normal microbiota of the gut, and can benefit their hosts by producing vitamin K2, and preventing colonisation of the intestine with pathogenic bacteria, having a mutualistic relationship.

The Mattachine Society , founded in 1950 , was an early national gay rights organization in the United States , the largest of the early LGBT civil rights groups in the United States. The organization focused its advocacy around issues of sexual orientation. It was instrumental in shaping the public debate over the issue of lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender (LGBT) equality and in its campaign to repeal laws that made same-sex marriage illegal. It was founded by a number of gay and bisexual people in Chicago who formed a committee to oppose anti-gay discrimination.

EventsJanuary–March January 1 – Prince Muhammad Akbar , son of the Mughal Emperor Aurangzeb , initiates a civil war in India to create a single dynasty to rule in India. On January 11, 1707 , he is killed in an assassination attempt. Aeropress is a type of industrial coffee machine that was used in Europe for over 100 years. In the 19th and early 20th centuries, coffeehouses and coffee machines became popular in France, Italy, Germany, the United States and elsewhere, and aeropress coffee machines became popular throughout Europe after World War II.

Year 1047 (MXLVII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  September 25–28 – Rebel general Leo Tornikios (a nephew of Emperor Constantine IX) proclaims himself emperor at Adrianople, and besieges Constantinople. Byzantine troops personally led by Constantine repel him, and re-occupy the walls. Tornikios is forced to withdraw, while his followers start to abandon him. Finally, he is captured at a church in Boulgarophygon (modern Turkey), and is publicly blinded.

Year 1569 (MDLXIX) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–June  January 11–May 6 – The first recorded lottery in England is performed nonstop, at the west door of St Paul's Cathedral. Each share costs ten shillings, and proceeds are used to repair harbours, and for other public works. March 13 – Battle of Jarnac: Royalist troops under Marshal Gaspard de Tavannes surprise and defeat the Huguenots under the Prince of Condé, who is captured and murdered. A substantial proportion of the Huguenot army manages to escape, under Gaspard de Coligny.

Year 1548 ( MDXLVIII ) was a leap year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) on the 29th September 1548. The month of September itself was a lunisolar month.On the same date in 1548, King Henry VIII converted to the Catholic faith, becoming the second Protestant monarch to renounce the Catholic faith, and thus the only Protestant monarch of the period, to the Catholic Church after being Catholic for about forty-three years. [1]Henry's conversion was largely a response to pressure from a papal bull, the Bull Intelligensae Divinis.

Proline (symbol Pro or P) is an organic acid classed as a proteinogenic amino acid (used in the biosynthesis of proteins), although it does not contain the amino group  but is rather a secondary amine. The secondary amine nitrogen is in the protonated NH2+ form under biological conditions, while the carboxyl group is in the deprotonated −COO− form. The "side chain" from the α carbon connects to the nitrogen forming a pyrrolidine loop, classifying it as a aliphatic amino acid. It is non-essential in humans, meaning the body can synthesize it from the non-essential amino acid L-glutamate.

Year 1396 (MCCCXCVI) was a leap year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  May 19 – Martin I succeeds his brother, John I, as King of Aragon (modern-day north-east Spain). July 20 – Queen Margaret I of Denmark, Norway and Sweden publishes the Treaty of Kalmar, proposing the personal union of the three kingdoms of Denmark, Norway (with Iceland, Greenland, the Faroe Islands, Shetland and Orkney) and Sweden (including Finland and Åland). July 23 – Queen Margaret makes her great-nephew and adopted son Eric of Pomerania joint ruler of Sweden.

Lead azide   is an inorganic compound. More so than other azides,  is explosive. It is used in detonators to initiate secondary explosives. In a commercially usable form, it is a white to buff powder.Preparation and handlingLead azide is prepared by the reaction of sodium azide and lead(II) nitrate in aqueous solution. Lead acetate can also be used.Thickeners such as dextrin or polyvinyl alcohol are often added to the solution to stabilize the precipitated product. In fact, it is normally shipped in a dextrinated solution that lowers its sensitivity.Production historyLead azide in its pure form was first prepared by Theodor Curtius in 1891.

is the Latin name under which the `` Lamb of God '' is honoured within the Catholic Mass and other Christian liturgies.HistoryIn the Roman Church, the tradition of the consecration of a new Lamb takes place at a Mass, or Eucharistic Liturgy. The Lamb of God is first presented with the sign of the cross upon the altar; this sign, and also the consecration of the host and wine into the body of Christ, is the first part of the Liturgy itself. After the consecration, a Lamb of God is placed between two thrones, and is offered to God.

Year 1434 ( MCDXXXIV ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) on the Julian or Gregorian calendar. It was preceded by a two day holiday called Christmas, on 28 December. The Julian year was followed by a three day holiday called the Feast of the Ascension of Peter the Apostle on 23 January 1450, and then on 14 May 1451, a six day festival that was followed by another six day feast on 1 August 1451, and the next two days by two day celebrations on the following day.

Palermo ( , ; , locally also or ; , from ; older ) is a city in southern Italy, on the island of Sicily. Situated on the  of Liguria, the city is the administrative center of the Veneto Region, the administrative center of the Campania region, the administrative capital of the Liguria region and a UNESCO world heritage site, and a significant cultural center in Southern Italy. Located in the heart of Liguria and surrounded by the Adriatic Sea and the Sea of Liguria, the city is the gateway to the Piedmont area and the gateway to the Po Valley for the region, with an important railway connection.

Year 1059 (MLIX) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  November 22 – Emperor Isaac I Komnenos falls ill on a hunt and retires to a monastery after a 2-year reign. He abdicates the Byzantine throne and appoints Constantine X, a Paphlagonian nobleman, as his successor. Fall – The Magyars cross the Danube River, together with several Pecheneg tribes, but are halted by Byzantine forces (approximate date). Europe  Peter Krešimir IV (the Great) is crowned king of Croatia and Dalmatia.

Year 1344 (MCCCXLIV) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March 26 – Reconquista: The Siege of Algeciras (1342–44), one of the first European military engagements where gunpowder is used, ends with the Muslim city of Algeciras surrendering and being incorporated into the Kingdom of Castile. April 17 – Constantine II, King of Armenia, is killed in an uprising and succeeded by a distant cousin, Constantine III. April 23 – The St. George's Night Uprising: The Livonian Order hangs Vesse, the rebel Estonian Elder of Saaremaa Island.

Year 1514 (MDXIV) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 10 – A great fire breaks out, in the Rialto of Venice. March 12 – A huge exotic embassy sent by King Manuel I of Portugal to Pope Leo X arrives in Rome, including Hanno, an Indian elephant. March – Louis XII of France makes peace with Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor. May 2 – The Poor Conrad peasant revolt against Ulrich, Duke of Württemberg begins in Beutelsbach.

A shank is a type of knot that is used to shorten a rope or take up slack, such as the sheepshank. The sheepshank knot is not stable. It will fall apart under too much load or too little load.The knot has several features which allow a rope to be shortened: It provides two loops, one at each end of the knot which can be used to pass another rope through The knot remains somewhat secure under tension; the coarser the rope the more secure it is (see Disadvantages, below) The knot falls apart easily when tension is removedConstruction methods A sheepshank knot may be constructed as follows: ...

The standard circulating coinage of the United Kingdom , British Crown Dependencies and British Overseas Territories is denominated in pounds sterling (GBP), the official currency of the United Kingdom, and bears the name pound coin (plural pounds coins), while other coins are referred to as sovereigns, commemorative coins and coins of state. Dawn of the Eagles is a science fiction novel by Robert A Heinlein. It was first published in 1962. It is the third book in the Redshirts series of novels. It won both the Hugo and Nebula awards for its 1968 Hugo award and was nominated for the Locus award in 1969.

Year 1501 ( MDI ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on the following Monday ( MDD ). It began on Friday, March 9, 1501, at 00:00 UTC, and lasted until March 10. The common year is a calendar used by many cultures throughout history. It is the period that is considered the standard length of a year and is used in both calendar systems. It was the first calendar, the first standardized calendar and the first calendar used in most countries.

Year 1432 (MCDXXXII) was a leap year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 1 – Iliaș succeeds his father as Prince of Moldavia. Spring – An Albanian revolt, led by Gjergj Arianit Komneni, breaks out against the Ottoman Empire, and spreads through most of Albania. April – At the end of the Hook and Cod wars, Jacqueline, Countess of Hainaut and Countess of Holland and Zeeland, is forced by Philip the Good, Duke of Burgundy, to abdicate all her estates in his favour, ending Hainaut and Holland as independent counties.

GNU Privacy Guard ( GnuPG or GPG ) is a free-software replacement for Symantec 's PGP cryptographic software suite . In addition to encrypting e-mail messages and other data, the program can also be used by end users to create keys and encrypt files. It supports both public key encryption and symmetric encryption and signing, and can be used by both personal and business users.GnuPG is released under the GNU General Public License ( GPL ).GnuPG currently supports all major public key cryptosystems, such as RSA, Diffie Hellman, and ECDH. Gnome is a Linux-based operating system and desktop environment.

The African clawed frog ( Xenopus laevis , also known as the xenopus , African clawed toad , African claw-toed or African clawed tadpole) is a common frog in tropical and subtropical areas. It is found from the equator to a latitude of about 0°N and east to about 60°N, south to a latitude of about -30°N to -60°N, west to about 90°N, north to a latitude of about 80°N. It is native to Africa, but has also been found in the Caribbean, the Americas, and Asia. It has been introduced to most of the world's freshwater rivers.

Greyhound racing is an organized, competitive sport in which greyhounds are raced around a track. There are two forms of greyhound racing, track racing (normally around an oval track) and coursing, the latter is now banned in most countries. Track racing uses an artificial lure (usually a form of windsock) that travels ahead of the greyhounds on a rail until the greyhounds cross the finish line. As with horse racing, greyhound races often allow the public to bet on the outcome.In many countries greyhound racing is purely amateur and solely for enjoyment.

Frederick (Middle High German: Friderich, Standard German: Friedrich; 21 September 1371 – 20 September 1440) was the last Burgrave of Nuremberg from 1397 to 1427 (as Frederick VI), Margrave of Brandenburg-Ansbach from 1398, Margrave of Brandenburg-Kulmbach from 1420, and Elector of Brandenburg (as Frederick I) from 1415 until his death. He became the first member of the House of Hohenzollern to rule the Margraviate of Brandenburg.Biography Frederick was born in Nuremberg, the second-born son of Burgrave Frederick V (1333–1398) and the Wettin princess Elisabeth of Meissen.

Events  January–December  February – The Republic of Venice annexes the seigniory of Ravenna, ending the da Polenta Dynasty. February 12 – King's College, Cambridge, is founded by King Henry VI of England. March 1 – Battle of Samobor: The army of Ulrich II, Count of Celje, defeats the army of Stjepan Banić at Samobor, Croatia in union with Hungary. November 10 – Alfonso V of Aragon lays siege to Naples. November 20 – The Peace of Cremona (1441) ends the war between the Republic of Venice and the Duchy of Milan.

Divorce ( also known as dissolution of marriage ) is the process of terminating a marriage or marital union . A divorce is also the formal end of a legally recognized marriage, and the dissolution of that marriage. Divorces are sometimes known as "separations" for the duration of the separation from the state. In the US, divorces are administered by the courts under the Uniform Marriage and Divorce Act, though in other states, the issue may be governed by civil law.The United States has no single legal definition for the term divorce.

EventsJanuary–March  January 1 – Prince Muhammad Akbar, son of the Mughal Emperor Aurangzeb, initiates a civil war in India. With the support of troops from the Rajput states, Akbar declares himself the new Mughal Emperor and prepares to fight his father, but is ultimately defeated. January 3 – The Treaty of Bakhchisarai is signed, between the Ottoman vassal Crimean Khanate and the Russian Empire. January 18 – The "Exclusion Bill Parliament", summoned by King Charles II of England in October, is dissolved after three months, with directions that new elections be held at that a new parliament be convened in March in Oxford.

English Renaissance theatre, also known as Renaissance English theatre and Elizabethan theatre, refers to the theatre of England between 1558 and 1642.This is the style of the plays of William Shakespeare, Christopher Marlowe and Ben Jonson.BackgroundThe term English Renaissance theatre encompasses the period between 1562—following a performance of Gorboduc, the first English play using blank verse, at the Inner Temple during the Christmas season of 1561—and the ban on theatrical plays enacted by the English Parliament in 1642.The phrase Elizabethan theatre is sometimes improperly used to mean English Renaissance theatre, although in a strict sense "Elizabethan" only refers to the period of Queen Elizabeth's reign (1558–1603).

Year 1216(MCCXVI) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  England  Spring – First Barons' War: The English army, led by King John (Lackland), sacks the town of Berwick-on-Tweed (or Berwick), and raids southern Scotland. John pushes up towards Edinburgh over a ten-day period. On his return, he puts down a revolt in East Anglia. On March 24, King John arrives at Hertford, to deal with the challenge of a coming French invasion.

In the Swedish calendar it was a leap year starting on Wednesday, one day ahead of the Julian and ten days behind the Gregorian calendar.Events  January–June  January 1 – Charles XII of Sweden invades Russia, by crossing the frozen Vistula River with 40,000 men. January 12 – Shahu I becomes the fifth Chhatrapati of the Maratha Empire in the Indian subcontinent. February 26 – HMS Falmouth, a 50-gun fourth-rate ship of the line built at Woolwich Dockyard for the Royal Navy, is launched. March 11 – Queen Anne withholds Royal Assent from the Scottish Militia Bill, the last time a British monarch vetoes legislation.

In art history , literature and cultural studies , Orientalism is the imitation or depiction of aspects in the Eastern world that can be seen as unique or distinctive and in contrast to Western (and especially Christian) culture.An Orientalist painting is one in which a non-Western element can be seen. It can be taken to indicate an influence from Western culture on an East, or to identify a non-Western world.Orientalism may be viewed as a cultural, ideological or even religious trend, though it has been criticised from a number of angles since its birth.OriginsIn the late 19th and early 20th century, Orientalism was associated primarily with European art.

The Stoned Guest is a "half-act opera" by Peter Schickele in the satirical persona of P. D. Q. Bach. The title is a play on the "stone guest" character in Don Giovanni by Mozart, as well as the opera The Stone Guest by Alexander Sergeyevich Dargomïzhsky after the play by Pushkin. The work is a parody of classical opera, although some critics consider it to be the equal of many classical works in technical ability. The opera appears on the 1970 album of the same name.The loose story combines elements of Don Giovanni with elements of Carmen by Georges Bizet.

Lullingstone Roman Villa is a villa built during the Roman occupation of Britain, situated in Lullingstone near the village of Eynsford in Kent, south eastern England. The villa is located in the Darent Valley, along with six others, including those at Crofton, Crayford and Dartford. Constructed in the 1st century, perhaps around 80-90 CE, the house was repeatedly expanded and occupied until it was destroyed by fire in the 4th or 5th century. The villa was occupied over various periods within the Romano-British period, but after its destruction, it is only thought to have been reoccupied during the Medieval Times.

Events  March 18 – Jacques de Molay, the 23rd and last Grand Master of the Knights Templar, is burned at the stake in Paris, France. April 4 – Exeter College, Oxford is founded in England by Walter de Stapledon, Bishop of Exeter. June 24 – Battle of Bannockburn: Scottish forces led by Robert the Bruce defeat Edward II of England, regaining Scotland's independence. August 31 – King Haakon V of Norway moves his capital from Bergen to Oslo, where he builds Akershus Fortress, from which Norway is ruled for the next 500 years.

Year 1303 (MCCCIII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–December  February 24 – Battle of Roslin: The Scots defeat the English. April 4 – Battle of Arques: The Flemings defeat the French. April 20 – Pope Boniface VIII founds the University of Rome La Sapienza. May 29 – The Treaty of Paris restores Gascony to the English.
