August 8 – 1303 Crete earthquake: An earthquake destroys the Lighthouse of Alexandria in Egypt, one of the seven wonders of the world.

Year 1552 (MDLII) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–June  January 15 – Henry II of France and Maurice, Elector of Saxony, sign the Treaty of Chambord. February 12 – Pedro de Valdivia founds the Chilean city of Valdivia, as Santa María la Blanca de Valdivia. February 24 – The privileges of the Hanseatic League are abolished in England. March – The Act of Uniformity imposes the Protestant Book of Common Prayer on England. March 26 – Guru Amar Das becomes the Third Sikh Guru.

In cosmology, the cosmological constant (usually denoted by the Greek capital letter lambda: Λ), alternatively called Einstein's cosmological constant, is the constant coefficient of a term Albert Einstein temporarily added to his field equations of general relativity. He later removed it. Much later it was revived and reinterpreted as the energy density of space, or vacuum energy, that arises in quantum mechanics. It is closely associated with the concept of dark energy.Einstein originally introduced the constant in 1917 to counterbalance the effect of gravity and achieve a static universe, a notion which was the accepted view at the time.

The Cross of Gold speech was delivered by William Jennings Bryan , a former United States Representative from Nebraska , on October 17, 1896. It was part of The Great Transcontinental Debate, a televised national debate between Bryan and future U.S. President Theodore Roosevelt, Jr. The speech won Bryan the presidential nomination and won Roosevelt the election, with Bryan winning a plurality of the popular vote. The Crown is the English legal system of the United Kingdom, based on the English common law. A Crown Prince is head of the royal household and head of government in the monarchical monarchy.

Stigmata ( , plural of , 'mark , spot , brand ' ) , in Christianity , are the appearance of wounds in the human body during the course of life. In Christianity, all forms of stigmata are symbolic wounds, but in some sects, specific wounds are considered significant signs of spiritual or religious importance. Many denominations of Christianity and other faiths hold that only the visible signs of these wounds are visible, not other types of healing or signs of spiritual significance. Sir John Harington (,  ; 14 December 1724 – 6 March 1813) was a Scottish author, poet and dramatist.

Year 1430 (MCDXXX) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 7 – Philip the Good, Duke of Burgundy, marries Isabella of Portugal. January 10 – Philip the Good founds the Order of the Golden Fleece. March 29 – The Ottoman Empire, under Murad II, captures Thessalonica after an eight-year siege. May 14 – The French first attempt to relieve the Siege of Compiègne. May 23 – Joan of Arc is captured by the Burgundians, while leading an army to relieve Compiègne.

Kazimierz Funk (; February 23, 1884 – November 19, 1967), commonly anglicized as Casimir Funk, was a Polish and American biochemist, generally credited with being among the first to formulate (in 1912) the concept of vitamins, which he called "vital amines" or "vitamines".AchievementsAfter reading an article by the Dutchman Christiaan Eijkman that indicated that persons who ate brown rice were less vulnerable to beri-beri than those who ate only the fully milled product, Funk tried to isolate the substance responsible, and he succeeded. Because that substance contained an amine group, he called it "vitamine".

Events  January–March  January 17 – Tuscarora War: Colonel James Moore leads the Carolina militia out of Albemarle County, North Carolina, in a second offensive against the Tuscarora. Heavy snows force the troops to take refuge in Fort Reading, on the Pamlico River. February 1 – Skirmish at Bender, Moldova: Charles XII of Sweden is defeated by the Ottoman Empire. February 4 – Tuscarora War: The Carolina militia under Colonel James Moore leaves Fort Reading, to continue the campaign against the Tuscarora. February 25 – Frederick William I of Prussia begins his reign.

Events  January–March  January 8 – Carolean Death March begins: A catastrophic retreat by a largely-Finnish Swedish-Carolean army under the command of Carl Gustaf Armfeldt across the Tydal mountains in a blizzard kills around 3,700 men and cripples a further 600 for life. January 23 – The Principality of Liechtenstein is created, within the Holy Roman Empire. February 3 (January 23 Old Style) – The Riksdag of the Estates recognizes Ulrika Eleonora's claim to the Swedish throne, after she has agreed to sign a new Swedish constitution. Thus, she is recognized as queen regnant of Sweden.

Year 1137 ( MCXXXVII ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) in England, which began on 1 January. This is the first of eleven years in the eleven-year cycle of the year. This calendar was known by a variety of names: the Gregorian calendar, Old English calendar, Julian calendar, Julian month calendar, Old English lunar month calendar.In England, a year started with the Old English leap-year. It was considered to be equivalent to a year consisting of seven complete months and six leap days, since this calendar did not have a new year.

Year 1452 (MCDLII) was a leap year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  February – Alexăndrel retakes the throne of Moldavia, in his long struggle with Petru Aron. February 22 – William Douglas, 8th Earl of Douglas is killed by James II of Scotland, at Stirling Castle. March 17 – Reconquista – Battle of Los Alporchones (around the city of Lorca in Murcia): The combined forces of the Kingdom of Castile, and its subsidiary kingdom of Murcia, defeat the Emirate of Granada.

A horoscope ( or other commonly used names for the horoscope in English include natal chart , astrological chart , horoscope , natal chart , horoscope, astrology or horoscopy ) is a chart showing the position of a person's birth chart over the course of their lifetime. In addition to the usual planets, signs, and houses, it includes the zodiac and other features that denote a person's place in astrological heaven or hell.The horoscopes of all recorded human cultures have had a long association with astrology and the supernatural, and can be found in both oral tradition as well as written records.

Year 1575 (MDLXXV)  was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 21 – Queen Elizabeth I of England grants a monopoly on producing printed sheet music, to Thomas Tallis and William Byrd. February 8 – William I of Orange founds Leiden University. February 13 – Henry III of France is crowned at Reims. February 14 – Henry III of France marries Louise de Lorraine-Vaudémont. March 3 – Battle of Tukaroi: The Mughal Empire decisively defeat the Karrani dynasty of Bengal. June 24 – William I of Orange marries Charlotte of Bourbon.

Mariner 10 was an American robotic space probe launched by NASA on 3 November 1973 , to fly by the Martian equator on its first orbit. It was designed to collect data on how much of the Martian surface had changed since previous Viking landings. It also carried the Mars Science Laboratory, which was intended to remain on the surface for one Martian year and conduct experiments. The probe's primary scientific instrument, the Mars Lander, was intended to land safely on Mars.The first four Mariner 7 landings took place on October 12 and 14, 1973, and the remaining six landed between November 1972 and March 1973.

"Coven"  usually refers to a group or gathering of witches. The word "coven" (from Anglo-Norman covent, cuvent, from Old French covent, from Latin conventum = convention) remained largely unused in English until 1921 when Margaret Murray promoted the idea that all witches across Europe met in groups of thirteen which they called "covens".NeopaganismIn Wicca and other similar forms of neopagan witchcraft, such as Stregheria and Feri, a coven is a gathering or community of witches, like an affinity group, engagement group, or small covenant group.

A conjugate acid , within the Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory , is a chemical compound formed when an acid donates a hydrogen-bonded molecule, usually hydroxide or peroxide, to an acid, usually an amine, such that the double bond between the two species gives rise to the chemical compound. Acid-base conjugation occurs when an acid ion, such as hydrogen ions, dissociates from a hydrogen ion (or other cation) such as peroxide or hydroxyl, forming a hydrogen-bonded molecule. The two molecules join together in an amide, giving rise to two compounds.

Nature versus nurture is a long-standing debate in biology about the balance between two competing factors which determine fate :
In genetics, the term genetic inheritance, also known as genetic coding, describes the process by which a gene (i.e., a copy of a specific gene) is passed on from one generation to another from generation to generation. This process is commonly known as genetic inheritance; the word genetic code comes from its scientific definition of the process of inheritance of a set of genes.The term is also used in the field of human genetics and genetics, in reference to inherited information, and sometimes in an informal sense.

Proline ( symbol Pro or P ) is an organic acid classed as a proteinogenic amino acid ( used in many synthetic processes to produce protein ). Proline is used as a building block of ribosomes in most living organisms and is essential in the production of RNA, DNA, and other proteins. Proline is the only amino acid found in all eukaryotes, consisting in the amino acid methionine, in the amino acid histidine in plants, in the amino acid lysine in animals and in bacteria. Pegasus was a winged horse that is depicted in the ancient myths of the Greek pantheon as a god of war in mythology.

Dissociative identity disorder ( DID ) , previously known as multiple personality disorder ( MPD ) , is a mental disorder characterised by the ability to experience or to have a wide range of personality states. There is no known cause, although some people believe it is due to a biological abnormality. Edgar Allan Poe (January 1769 – October 19, 1849), was an American writer and poet. Poe's work, published between 1843 and 1849, is known as the "American Gothic" because of the strong horror themes that characterize much of Poe's work.

In mathematics, two sets are said to be disjoint sets if they have no element in common. Equivalently, two disjoint sets are sets whose intersection is the empty set. For example, {1, 2, 3} and {4, 5, 6} are disjoint sets, while {1, 2, 3} and {3, 4, 5} are not disjoint. A collection of more than two sets is called disjoint if any two distinct sets of the collection are disjoint.GeneralizationsThis definition of disjoint sets can be extended to a family of sets : the family is pairwise disjoint, or mutually disjoint if  whenever .

The Khlysts or Khlysty (,  "whips") were an underground Spiritual Christian sect, which split from the Russian Orthodox Church and existed from the 1600s until the late 20th century.NameThe members of the sect referred to themselves by various names, including "God's People" (liudi bozh'i), "followers of Christ's faith" (Khristovovery), or simply "Christs" (Khristy). The appellation "Khlysty" is a derogatory term applied by critics of the sect. The origin of the term is disputed.

Year 1211 (MCCXI) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  June 17 – Battle of Antioch on the Meander: Seljuk forces led by Sultan Kaykhusraw I are initially victorious with the Latin mercenary cavalry (some 800 men) bearing the brunt of the casualties due to their flanking charge; exhausted by the effort in their attack, the Latin army under Emperor Theodore I (Laskaris) is struck in the flank and rear by the Seljuk forces.

Year 1349 (MCCCXLIX) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–December January 22 – An earthquake affects L'Aquila in southern Italy with a maximum Mercalli intensity of X (Extreme), causing severe damage, and leaving 2,000 dead. February 14 – Jewish persecutions during the Black Death: Strasbourg massacre – Because they are believed by the residents to be the cause of the Black Death, roughly 2,000 Jews are burned to death. February 19 – Jewish persecutions during the Black Death: The entire Jewish community in the remote German village of Saulgau is wiped out.

Jan Bos ( born 29 March 1975 ) is a Dutch speedskater and sprint cyclist . In the late 1990s he became one of the world's fastest men when he won three individual titles. He has won the Winter Olympics four times and the World Championships twice, both in Sochi, Russia; the 2014 Winter Games in PyeongChang, South Korea; and two World Cups (2007 and 2014). Giovanni Bemer (; born September 27, 1962) is an American actor, voice actor, and comedian who has starred in numerous television shows and animated series.

A battering ram is a siege engine that originated in ancient times and was designed to break open the masonry walls of fortifications or splinter their wooden gates. In its simplest form, a battering ram is just a large, heavy log carried by several people and propelled with force against an obstacle; the ram would be sufficient to damage the target if the log were massive enough and/or it were moved quickly enough (that is, if it had enough momentum). Later rams encased the log in an arrow-proof, fire-resistant canopy mounted on wheels. Inside the canopy, the log was swung from suspensory chains or ropes.

In metaphysics, extension signifies both 'stretching out' (Latin: extensio) as well as later 'taking up space', and most recently, spreading one's internal mental cognition into the external world.The history of thinking about extension can be traced back at least to Archytas' spear analogy for the infinity of space. How far can one's hand or spear stretch out until it reaches the edge of reality? “If I arrived at the outermost edge of the heaven, could I extend my hand or staff into what is outside or not?

New England Digital Corporation (1976–1993) was founded in Norwich, Vermont, and relocated to White River Junction, Vermont. It was best known for its signature product, the Synclavier Synthesizer System, which evolved into the Synclavier Digital Audio System or "Tapeless Studio." The company sold an FM digital synthesizer/16-bit polyphonic synthesizer and magnetic disk-based non-linear 16-bit digital recording product, referred to as the "Post-Pro." The Synclavier was developed as the "Dartmouth Digital Synthesizer" by Dartmouth College Professors Jon Appleton and Frederick J. Hooven, in association with NED co-founders Sydney A. Alonso and Cameron W. Jones.

Microware was a US corporation based in Clive, Iowa that produced the OS-9 real-time operating system.Microware Systems Corporation existed as a separate entity from 1977 until September 2001, when it was bought by RadiSys Corp., and became a division of that company. The rights to Microware OS-9 and related software were purchased by a group of distributors on 1 March 2013. The new owner was Microware LP. Microware initially produced a version of BASIC and a real-time kernel for the Motorola 6800 processor, and was asked by Motorola to develop what turned into BASIC09 for the then-new Motorola 6809 processor.

Hide-and-seek is a popular children 's game in which at least two players ( usually at least three ) conceal themselves by playing in the shadows, with each player looking for the other player. The objective is not necessarily to see the other hidden player, although it is often expected. There are variations of hide-and-seek with different strategies, with most of the variations including some kind of hidden target or object to be seen. In some variants, it is also possible to score points and to win points by hiding and finding other players as well as by catching them in one of the many variations of catch.

Howard Kingsbury Smith (May 12, 1914 – February 15, 2002) was an American journalist, radio reporter, television anchorman, political commentator, and film actor. He was one of the original members of the team of war correspondents known as the Murrow Boys.Early life and educationEarly career and CBS yearsWorld War IIUpon graduating, Smith worked for the New Orleans Item, with United Press in London, and with The New York Times. In January 1940, Smith was sent to Berlin, where he joined the Columbia Broadcasting System under Edward R. Murrow.

Robert Sanderson Mulliken ( June 7 , 1896 – October 31 , 1986 ) was an American physicist and chemist. He is best known for his discovery of deuterium, which forms an isotope in nuclear fission reactions, making the process of nuclear power generation from nuclear waste much less environmentally hazardous than nuclear power generation from the use of fission-fusion reactions. In 1956, he won the Nobel Prize for Chemistry with colleagues Walter Gilbert and Harold Urey, and his work with deuterium has since been fundamental to the design of nuclear reactor fuel and power generation methods.Early life and educationIn 1891, at the age of 15, Mulliken's father died.

A trisomy is a type of polysomy in which there are three instances of a particular chromosome, instead of the normal two. A trisomy is a type of aneuploidy (an abnormal number of chromosomes).Description and causesMost organisms that reproduce sexually have pairs of chromosomes in each cell, with one chromosome inherited from each parent. In such organisms, a process called meiosis creates cells called gametes (eggs or sperm) that have only one set of chromosomes. The number of chromosomes is different for different species. Humans have 46 chromosomes (i.e. 23 pairs of chromosomes).

Wellfleet is a town in Barnstable County , Massachusetts , United States , and is located halfway between the ``Bathtub" and ``Roxbury Line''. It is the second-most populous city and the sixth most populous town in the County. It is the largest city and the second-largest town in New Hampshire and the fifth largest town in the United States by population. It is also the sixth-most populated town in New England and the eleventh most populous city in Massachusetts . It is the fifth-most populated town in Rhode Island and the seventh-most populous town in the state of Connecticut.

Microware was a US corporation based in Clive , Iowa that produced the OS-9 real-time operating system.Microware Systems Corporation existed from 1976 to 1983.In 1985, it merged with Microcomputer Systems International (MSI), to create Microcomputer Systems, Inc., an independent company. The Microcomputer name was retained by Microcomputer Systems International and its successors, including Hewlett-Packard, which continued to use the Microcomputer name, with Microcomputer Systems Corporation as its parent.HistoryMicroware was established in 1976 by Dennis Ritchie, working out of his garage, and had just begun producing an operating system for the TRS-80.

In cosmology , the cosmological constant ( usually denoted by the Greek capital letter lambda : Λ ) , alternatively termed the fundamental constant , is the gravitational constant that determines the geometry of the Universe. It is often called the "cosmological constant", though this use is less common nowadays. Coffee, like all psychoactive substances, can induce mental states that can be altered by the drug. It is used as an energy stimulant to improve alertness, attention, and productivity during work, and as a sedative in recreational use.

The hobby of collecting includes seeking , locating , acquiring , organizing , cataloging , displaying , storing , and otherwise interacting with pieces of memorabilia of value.The term is used in its broad sense and includes all collecting activities, including the sale and trading of items. Collectors can be identified as collectors by collecting objects, not simply as individuals. In cryptography, security is the ability to protect data against interference, including eavesdropping, physical attacks, and network eavesdropping.Security is sometimes called secrecy, and it is related to the mathematical concept of secrecy.

Year 1383 (MCCCLXXXIII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  May 17 – King John I of Castile and Leon marries Beatrice of Portugal. July 7 – The childless James of Baux, ruler of Taranto and Achaea, and last titular Latin Emperor, dies. As a result: Charles III of Naples becomes ruler of Achaea (now southern Greece). Otto, Duke of Brunswick-Grubenhagen, the widower of Joanna I of Naples, becomes ruler of Taranto (now eastern Italy).

The Commonwealth Games , often referred to as the Friendly Games , is an international multi-sport event involving athletes from all countries competing for the most medals, and the largest number of individual gold, silver and bronze medals, at the same time, in various disciplines across many disciplines of sport. Organized by the International Olympic Committee (IOF), the Games can be regarded as the largest sporting event worldwide, and are held every four years, except for the Winter Paralympic Games. Czechoslovakia was an independent communist state of the Czech Republic in Central Europe during World War II.

Year 1558 (MDLVIII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar, the 1558th year of the Common Era (CE) and Anno Domini (AD) designations, the 558th year of the 2nd millennium, the 58th year of the 16th century, and the 9th year of the 1550s decade.Events  January–June  January 7 – French troops, led by Francis, Duke of Guise, take Calais, the last continental possession of the Kingdom of England. January 9 – Geneva becomes independent from the Canton of Bern.

Year 1293 ( MCCXCIII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the year 1293 of the Western calendar. In most European countries, it is known as the Leap Year. The year 1293 is the only common year with 12 months, the other 12 months are named after the months of the Julian Calendar. Malta is a Mediterranean island located at the southeastern end of the Adriatic Sea in the island province of Corsica. Malta is part of the European Union and is a founding member state of NATO.

Mai Elisabeth Zetterling (; 24 May 1925 – 17 March 1994) was a Swedish actress, novelist and film director.Early lifeZetterling was born in Västerås, Sweden to a working class family. She started her career as an actress at the age of 17 at Dramaten, the Swedish national theatre, appearing in war-era films.CareerZetterling appeared in film and television productions spanning six decades from the 1940s to the 1990s. Her breakthrough came in the 1944 film Torment written by Ingmar Bergman, in which she played a controversial role as a tormented shopgirl.

In physics, optical depth or optical thickness is the natural logarithm of the ratio of incident to transmitted radiant power through a material.Thus, the larger the optical depth, the smaller the amount of transmitted radiant power through the material. Spectral optical depth or spectral optical thickness is the natural logarithm of the ratio of incident to transmitted spectral radiant power through a material. Optical depth is dimensionless, and in particular is not a length, though it is a  monotonically increasing function of optical path length, and approaches zero as the path length approaches zero.

Robert von Ranke Graves ( 24 July 1895 – 7 December 1985 ) was a British poet , historical novelist and playwright.BiographyGraves began writing in the early 1920s, primarily during the period of the Great Depression. He published several works of poetry during his lifetime.Graves wrote primarily in rhymed couplets, some of which have become standards in the English language. Some of his best known poems include "Tis Pity She is a Whore" (1934) and "Pity the Fool" (1969), which are both inscribed on the National Portrait Gallery. The Greek alphabet is a writing system in use since antiquity.

Freestyle skiing is a skiing discipline comprising aerials , moguls , cross , half-pipe , slopestyle and big air as a single discipline. It is defined by the World Ski Federation (WSF), and is also known as the sport of freestyle skiing.Freeskiers usually start off skiing in their home country before moving to their chosen mountain to begin their journey into the sport of skiing; however, in recent decades, freeskiers have come from all over the world to pursue their dreams of becoming a world-class freeskiing skier.History The sport of ski jumping was developed in the early 1920s in Germany.

Dengue fever is a mosquito-borne tropical disease caused by the dengue virus. Symptoms typically begin three to fourteen days after infection. These may include a high fever, headache, vomiting, muscle and joint pains, and a characteristic skin rash. Recovery generally takes two to seven days. In a small proportion of cases, the disease develops into a more severe dengue hemorrhagic fever, resulting in bleeding, low levels of blood platelets and blood plasma leakage, or into dengue shock syndrome, where dangerously low blood pressure occurs.Dengue is spread by several species of female mosquitoes of the Aedes genus, principally Aedes aegypti.

Year 1148 (MCXLVIII) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place   Second Crusade  January 1 – The French crusaders under King Louis VII defeat a Turkish ambush next to the Meander River. Three days later they arrive at Laodicea – passing the spot where the German contingent led by Otto of Freising has been so disastrously ambushed (see 1147). The Crusaders are badly mauled as they cross Mount Cadmus (around January 8) before reaching Adalia on January 20.

The 12th century BC is the period from 1200 to 1101 BC . The Late Bronze Age collapse in the Middle East and a period of the decline of the Near East's economy caused a massive decline in the populations of cities in the region. These economic downturns began with the collapse of the Assyrian Empire in 718 BC and continued until 721 BC, with the last major urban centers destroyed. The Middle East was a region covering a territory that extended across the northern, central and eastern parts of the modern-day Middle East and North Africa from the Persian Gulf to the Atlantic coast of Africa.

Year 1203 ( MCCIII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in 1203. Year 1203 was followed by year 1204. Year 1311 (MCCIX) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in 1311. The year is the sum of the 365 th day of the calendar year and the 366 th day of the Julian calendar. A leap year is a year that is divisible by 3 . The Julian and Gregorian calendars share the year 365 days with a year divided by 365, giving 365 x 3 days, or  days.

The sousaphone is a brass instrument in the same family as the more widely known tuba . Created around 1893, it was patented by Arthur Gershwin, an American jazz musician and inventor of the clarinet who also invented the saxophone. It was used for both solo and ensemble performances.The sousaphone was also known as the clarion, saxophone clarinet, and clarinet trumpet. Somnambulism, or sleep walking, is a state of partial or total insensibility to external stimuli, and usually involves the sleepwalking condition of parasomnambulism, where the individual is unable to move.

Natural science is one of the branches of science concerned with the description, understanding and prediction of natural phenomena, based on empirical evidence from observation and experimentation. Mechanisms such as peer review and repeatability of findings are used to try to ensure the validity of scientific advances.Natural science can be divided into two main branches: life science and physical science. Life science is alternatively known as biology, and physical science is subdivided into branches: physics, chemistry, earth science, and astronomy. These branches of natural science may be further divided into more specialized branches (also known as fields).

The Caucasus , or Caucasia , is a region between the Black Sea and the Caspian Sea, mainly occupied by Armenia, Azerbaijan, Georgia, and parts of Southern Russia. The Caucasus Mountains, including the Greater Caucasus range, have historically been considered a natural barrier between Eastern Europe and Western Asia.Mount Elbrus, Europe's highest mountain, is in the Western Caucasus. On the southern side, the Lesser Caucasus includes the Javakheti Plateau and the Armenian highlands, part of which is in Turkey.The Caucasus is divided into the North Caucasus and South Caucasus, although the Western Caucasus also exists as a distinct geographic space within the North Caucasus.

Black's Law Dictionary is the most widely used law dictionary in the United States. Henry Campbell Black (1860–1927) was the author of the first two editions of the dictionary.HistoryThe first edition was published in 1891 by West Publishing, with the full title A Dictionary of Law: containing definitions of the terms and phrases of American and English jurisprudence, ancient and modern, including the principal terms of international constitutional and commercial law, with a collection of legal maxims and numerous select titles from the civil law and other foreign systems. A second edition was published in 1910 as A Law Dictionary.

Mai Elisabeth Zetterling ( ; 24 May 1925 – 17 March 1994 ) was a Swedish actress , novelist and filmmaker, best known for the film and television series Dr. Horrible's Singalong Blog.BiographyA native of Stockholm, Zetterling grew up in a middle-class family. Her parents were both successful actors who were married to prominent Swedish society figures, which included the composer Alfred Jonsson, the film director Karel Reis and the playwright and literary critic Gustav Strömberg.As a girl, Zetterling was deeply affected by films of the 1930s and 1940s such as Mary Pickford's The Princess Bride, Fritz Lang's Metropolis, and Orson Welles's Citizen Kane.

Events  January–June  January 11 – The Cortes of Castile approves a new subsidy, the millones. March – Maurice of Nassau, Prince of Orange, takes Breda, by concealing 68 of his best men in a peat-boat, to get through the impregnable defences. March 14 – Battle of Ivry: Henry IV of France again defeats the forces of the Catholic League, under Charles, Duke of Mayenne. May–August – Henry IV of France unsuccessfully attempts to besiege Paris. Henry is forced to raise the siege, when Alexander Farnese, Duke of Parma comes to its rescue with a Spanish army.

Lullingstone Roman Villa is a villa built during the Roman occupation of Britain , situated in Lullingstone near the village of Luton, Bedfordshire . It was designed by John Sargent and was originally intended for King Theodosius the Great . It was built upon a site previously occupied by a house and two shops. The house was demolished, and the buildings were replaced by the new building.The villa was used by King George VI during World War II, and by Queen Elizabeth I during the 1930s. The Law Society of Upper Canada is a statutory law society within the Province of Quebec.

The Tandy 1000 is the first in a line of IBM PC compatible home computer systems produced by the Tandy Corporation for sale in its Radio Shack and Radio Shack Computer Center chains of stores.OverviewIn December 1983, an executive with Tandy Corporation, maker of TRS-80 computers, said about the new IBM PCjr: "I'm sure a lot of people will be coming out with PCjr look-alikes. The market is big". While preparing the Tandy 2000—the company's first MS-DOS computer—for release in November 1983, Tandy began designing the Tandy 1000, code named "August".

Bamboos are a diverse group of evergreen perennial flowering plants in the subfamily Bambusoideae of the grass family Poaceae . Bamboo is one of only two families to produce edible bamboo, the other being angiosperms. Bamboo occurs widely in tropical and subtropical ecosystems and is important to many indigenous cultures.Bamboo can be found in a variety of habitats, but the majority grows in wet tropical forests. Bamboo is commonly found growing at elevations between 10 to 30 metres above sea level in the rainforests and mountains of southeast Asia. Bamboo is cultivated for food, fibre and decorative uses.

In mathematics , two sets are said to be disjoint sets if they have no element in common . Equivalently, two sets may have a unique element if they have no common element. The set of all elements in a single set is called the intersection of the two sets; the set of all elements in two sets that are disjoint is denoted the union of the two sets. For example, the set of all natural numbers has two members, one set to its right (which is the intersection of the integers), and another set to its left.

Year 1160 ( MCLX ) was a leap year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) in England, with the Gregorian calendar adopted in England. It was observed in Wales as well as Scotland and Northern Ireland until at least the 18th century. In England, 1160 was the first year that could be used as an entry in the modern calendar, which was introduced in England at the beginning of the 19th century. Ludwig von Beethoven  ( ; ; 26 February 1770 – 27 March 1827) was a German composer, pianist and organist.

Year 1349 ( MCCCXLIX ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) on 13 March 1349. It began as the 12th year of Henry III and began a new century. The date was not changed until 1376, when King Henry III, at the request of the Pope, altered it to the Julian calendar year 1120 (link will display a table of this year's events). The new Julian calendar year 1349 was one of the last of the Julian calendar, which ended in 1453.

In physics, quintessence is a hypothetical form of dark energy, more precisely a scalar field, postulated  as an explanation of the observation  of an accelerating rate of expansion of the universe. The first example of this scenario was proposed by Ratra and Peebles (1988). The concept was expanded to more general types of time-varying dark energy and the term "quintessence" was first introduced in a 1998 paper by Robert R. Caldwell, Rahul Dave and Paul Steinhardt. It has been proposed by some physicists to be a fifth fundamental force.

Howard Kingsbury Smith ( May 12 , 1914 – February 15 , 2002 ) was an American journalist , radio personality and television host. He was co-founder and CEO of CNN, and was a founding executive producer and co-writer of the Emmy Award winning documentary series Anderson Cooper 360°, and a co-host of The View.Early lifeBorn into a well-to-do family, Smith attended Princeton University where he graduated in 1937 with a degree in English Literature from the Woodrow Wilson School. He spent his early career on radio in New York City, before moving to broadcasting in the late 1940s.

Dari ( , , ) , or Dari Persian , is a political term used for the various dialects of Dari spoken in modern Afghanistan, Iran and Turkmenistan. Afghanistan is the primary language in the region and is the official and common language in many parts of the country, while Farsi is the official language in Turkmenistan. Dari was the official language in the Afghanistan-Pakistan-India-Iran Triple-Partition.The language is a Romance-derived language derived from Sanskrit. Dari is one of the two main Iranian languages. Darjeeling or Darjeeling Hill is a hill on the western side of the Malacca Strait in Southern India.

A pine is any conifer tree or shrub in the genus Pinus  of the family Pinaceae. Pinus is the sole genus in the subfamily Pinoideae. The Plant List compiled by the Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew and Missouri Botanical Garden accepts 126 species names of pines as current, together with 35 unresolved species and many more synonyms. The American Conifer Society (ACS) and the Royal Horticultural Society accept 121 species. Pine may also refer to the lumber derived from pine trees; pine is one of the more extensively used types of wood used as lumber.

The European bison (Bison bonasus) or the European wood bison, also known as the wisent ( or ), or the zubr , or colloquially the European buffalo, is a European species of bison. It is one of two extant species of bison, alongside the American bison. The European bison is the heaviest wild land animal in Europe and individuals in the past may have been even larger than their modern-day descendants. During late antiquity and the Middle Ages, bison became extinct in much of Europe and Asia, surviving into the 20th century only in northern-central Europe and the northern Caucasus Mountains.

Year 1533 ( MDXXXIII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) on the Julian calendar and ending on Saturday, January 1, 1645 on the Gregorian calendar. It was the 15th year of the Roman Empire, and the ninth year of Constantine the Great's reign as Roman Emperor from January 8, 306 BC to December 31, 306 BC. The year 1533 also happened to be the first year of the Middle Ages in Western Europe. In mathematics, exponential notation  is the notation for the exponential function.

Sigismund of Luxembourg ( 15 February 1368 – 9 December 1437 ) was a monarch who reigned as king of Luxembourg from 1369 to his death. Sigismund succeeded his brother Louis duke of Luneville in 1434 and was the last of King Philip II 's children.Sigmund was the eldest son of the Holy Roman Emperor, Charles VI. His paternal grandmother, Princess Constance of Savoy, was married to Charles V of Italy, the son of John of Luxemburg, Duke of Luneville. Sydney Harbour ( , ; ; ; ) ( ; ), officially Sydney Harbour, is a major harbour in Sydney's south-east coastal region.

Year 1318 (MCCCXVIII) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March – King Birger of Sweden is deposed, and forced to flee to Denmark (alternative date is April). April 1 – Berwick-upon-Tweed is retaken by the Scottish from the English. April – The inhabitants of Benevento, Italy rise against the Pope, and demand some political autonomy. The rebellion is crushed by William of Frejus, and the archbishop of Naples. May 11 – Battle of Dysert O'Dea: The Irish armies of Conor O'Dea defeat the Hiberno-Normans under Richard de Clare.

Year 1027 (MXXVII) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  March 26 – Pope John XIX crowns Conrad II ("the Elder") and his wife Gisela of Swabia as Holy Roman Emperor and Empress, respectively, in Old St. Peter's Basilica in Rome. Cnut the Great, King of Denmark and England, attends the coronation, proving his position as sole ruler of the Danish North Sea Empire. May 14 – King Robert II of France ("the Pious") sues for peace with his sons.

The term chat room, or chatroom (and sometimes group chat; abbreviated as GC), is primarily used to describe any form of synchronous conferencing, occasionally even asynchronous conferencing. The term can thus mean any technology ranging from real-time online chat and online interaction with strangers (e.g., online forums) to fully immersive graphical social environments.The primary use of a chat room is to share information via text with a group of other users. Generally speaking, the ability to converse with multiple people in the same conversation differentiates chat rooms from instant messaging programs, which are more typically designed for one-to-one communication.

Year 1378 (MCCCLXXVIII) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January – Charles IV, Holy Roman Emperor, visits his nephew Charles V of France in Paris, to celebrate publicly the friendship between their two nations. January 13 – Balša II succeeds his brother, Durađ I, as ruler of Lower Zeta (modern-day Montenegro). March – In England, John Wycliffe tries to promote his ideas for Catholic reform by laying his theses before Parliament, and making them public in a tract.

Salvador Domingo Felipe Jacinto Dalí i Domènech , 1st Marquess of Dalí of Púbol ( ; ; ; 11 May 1862 – 12 November 1973) was a surrealist painter, designer, printmaker, poet, critic and author, who is considered one of the pioneers of the surrealist movement. Dali is noted for his surrealism and for his unconventional, surrealistic style, which often combines elements of surrealism and modernism. He is widely credited for popularising the word surrealism.Early yearsDalí spent his early years living in Madrid, Spain, with his parents.

Events January–June March 13 – Battle of Tondibi : In Mali , forces sent by the Saadi Dynasty ruler of Timbuktu attack and defeat the invading Roman legions led by Emperor Narses I (12 January 1244–1 May 1246) on the banks of the Niger. The United Kingdom , or United Kingdom and Colonies  is a sovereign state in the Western Hemisphere of Europe consisting of six land mass and two seas, comprising the English Channel and the English and Scottish Borders, as well as a land border with Ireland, and a maritime boundary with the Atlantic Ocean to the northeast.

Year 1035 ( MXXXV ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) for all countries and territories of the Roman Catholic (Catholic), Orthodox, Anglican and other Protestant traditions in the world, with the exception of Russia, which has its own year of 1040. MXXXV is the third year of the Julian Calendar and the seventh year of the Gregorian Calendar. Mathematics refers to any discipline that studies mathematical objects (such as numbers, sets, operations, and relations) or mathematical concepts (such as algebra, geometry and probability).

The Quirinal Hill ( ; ; ) is one of the Seven Hills of Rome , at the north-east of the Tiber. The hill was named in honor of the Roman emperor Augustus and the son of his mother Tiberius. It is the highest point at the north-east edge of Rome proper and the highest point above the river Tiber in the Roman capital. The Roman Forum and Circus Maximus are also situated on the hill. Carlo Carlucci ( ; ;  ; 21 January 1900 – 23 August 1977) was an Italian artist, designer, and sculptor. As such, Carlucci was the first to popularize abstract painting.

Year 1132 (MCXXXII) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Levant  Summer – Imad al-Din Zengi, Seljuk governor (atabeg) of Aleppo and Mosul, marches on Baghdad (the capital of the Abbasid Caliphate) to add it to his dominions. He is defeated by the forces of Caliph Al-Mustarshid near Tikrit (modern Iraq). Zengi flees and escapes with help of Tikrit's governor Najm ad-Din Ayyub (the father of Saladin) who conveys him across the River Tigris.

Eleusine coracana, or finger millet, also known as ragi in India, kodo in Nepal, is an annual herbaceous plant widely grown as a cereal crop in the arid and semiarid areas in Africa and Asia. It is a tetraploid and self-pollinating species probably evolved from its wild relative Eleusine africana.Finger millet is native to the Ethiopian and Ugandan highlands. Interesting crop characteristics of finger millet are the ability to withstand cultivation at altitudes over 2000 m above sea level, its high drought tolerance, and the long storage time of the grains.History Finger millet originated in East Africa (Ethiopian and Ugandan highlands).

Year 1387 ( MCCCLXXXVII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Thursday (link will display the last day of that year, if there are two weeks in this year), in the Gregorian calendar of the Catholic Church. The year follows the same sequence of 28 days and 12 months as other years. The year follows Gregorian calendar rules with only a few exceptions, mainly related to leap years. The Gregorian calendar used by the Roman Catholic Church has been the primary calendar of the Eastern Orthodox Church since 1887.

Casimir IV (in full Casimir IV Andrew Jagiellon;  ; Lithuanian: ; 30 November 1427 – 7 June 1492) was Grand Duke of Lithuania from 1440 and King of Poland from 1447, until his death. He was one of the most active Polish-Lithuanian rulers, under whom Poland, by defeating the Teutonic Knights in the Thirteen Years' War recovered Pomerania, and the Jagiellonian dynasty became one of the leading royal houses in Europe.The great triumph of his reign was bringing Prussia under Polish rule. The rule of Casimir corresponded to the age of "new monarchies" in western Europe.

Events  January–June  January 14 – Portuguese Restoration War – Battle of the Lines of Elvas: The Portuguese beat the Spanish. January 24 – Pierre Corneille's Oedipe premieres in Paris. February 2 – Jan van Riebeeck produces the first South African wine, at the Cape of Good Hope. February 11 – The Assault on Copenhagen by Swedish forces is beaten back, with heavy losses. February 16 – The first known cheque (400 pounds) is written. April 22 – Lord Protector Richard Cromwell dissolves the English Parliament. May 21 – The Kingdom of France, the Commonwealth of England and the Dutch Republic sign the Concert of The Hague.

Michelangelo Antonioni  (, ; 29 September 1912 – 30 July 2007) was an Italian film director, screenwriter, editor, and painter. He is best known for his "trilogy on modernity and its discontents"—L'Avventura (1960), La Notte (1961), and L'Eclisse (1962)—as well as the English-language films Blowup (1966) and The Passenger (1975). His films have been described as "enigmatic and intricate mood pieces" that feature elusive plots, striking visual composition, and a preoccupation with modern landscapes.

Events January–June January 11 – The Cortes of Castile approves a new subsidy , the millones . March – Maurice de Payens is imprisoned in Bordeaux in connection with his involvement in the Guillotine plot. July – Louis XIII signs the Magna Carta, granting the monarch absolute legal authority over all the subjects of the Crown. September 1689 – Louis XVI abdicated in favor of his son François-Joseph, who abdicates the throne in favor of his son Louis Philippe. The Common Market is an economic union comprising 26 Member States of the European Union (EU) formed in 1993.

Year 1502 ( MDII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) (August 15) and ending on Sunday. The year 1502 began with the signing of a treaty of alliance by England and France to combat the Islamic invasions of the Iberian Peninsula, and the subsequent opening of the Strait of Gibraltar. Gothic architecture ( ; ; ; ), also known as classical architecture , is a style of  that was developed in the late Renaissance and lasted from the late 14th through the early 16th centuries.

Year 1412 ( MCDXII ) was a leap year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Sunday ( link displays the full calendar). The first Monday in February of the year 1412 is designated a leap day and this has been used as the basis for calculations for most years since.The year began with Friday 1412 at 1:00 UTC. There are 31 days in a year and a leap year occurs every four years with an extra day every fourth year. This also occurs every 4,095,769 days (about 8,200,000 years).This was the first leap year.

Year 1328 ( MCCCXXVIII ) was a leap year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) and lasting for seven days.The last Thursday of each month began at midnight, and the beginning and ending dates of the week were based on the previous Monday. The name was also used later to denote the seventh of February, a leap month in the Julian or Gregorian calendar, starting on Thursday, February 14 ( MCCCXXIX ) or the first Thursday in March (MCCCXXXII). In classical music notation, an  is a semitone below middle C and a semitone above the lowest note of the scale.

Stephen Arthur Cook , ( born December 14 , 1939 ) is an American-Canadian computer scientist and mathematician who has been associated with Cray Inc. since 1990. Cook began his career as a graduate research assistant at Bell Labs in 1969 before joining Bell Labs in 1970. He then moved to the Department of Electrical Engineering at Bell Labs, and worked there from 1975 to 1985 when he was appointed a professor.Cook holds a number of university and research appointments, including a position of professor at McGill University and the Royal Institute of Technology, Sweden.

The transport in Azerbaijan involves air traffic , waterways and railroads . All transportation services in Azerbaijan except for oil tankers and aircraft are state-owned and under the control of the Ministry of Communications and Transport.The most commonly used means of transportation in Azerbaijan is the bus system. Bus routes are maintained by different private operators. Benito Mussolini (1891 – 1944) was a Italian dictator during World War II. He led the Italian Fascists in overthrowing the Italian government in July 1922. He established Italy as a fascist dictatorship, with an authoritarian military government, that lasted from 1922 to 1943.BiographyBefore World War I, he had been an actor.

Year 1337 ( MCCCXXXVII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and lasting until Sunday, the last day of Lent. It was followed by a second common year on Sunday, which was called the first common year. A day of fasting and penance marked the first and last of the common years. In 1338, the common year was reduced to six days and the first day of Lent was omitted. In chemistry, a bromine (2-bromo-2-imidazo-4-fluoro-1,2,3-triazine) is an ion that has a molecular formula of C2H5Br2.

Year 1051 (MLI) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Spring – William of Normandy consolidates his power in Normandy. He fights over the control of Maine (after the death of Count Hugh IV), and lays siege to the fortresses of Alençon and Domfront (Western France). May 19 – King Henry I of France marries Anne of Kiev at the cathedral of Reims. William of Normandy marries Matilda of Flanders, daughter of Count Baldwin V, which Henry sees as a threat to his throne.

The human leg, in the general word sense, is the entire lower limb of the human body, including the foot, thigh and even the hip or gluteal region. However, the definition in human anatomy refers only to the section of the lower limb extending from the knee to the ankle, also known as the crus or, especially in non-technical use, the shank. Legs are used for standing, and all forms of locomotion including recreational such as dancing, and constitute a significant portion of a person's mass.

Year 993 (CMXCIII) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Spring – The 12-year-old King Otto III gives the Sword of Saints Cosmas and Damian (also known as the Sword of Essen) as a gift to the convent in Essen. It symbolises the martyrdom of Cosmas and Damian, the patron saints of the city. Charles, duke of Lower Lorraine, dies in prison in Orléans (see 991). He is succeeded by his son Otto II, who inherits the full dukedom and pledges his allegiance to Otto III.

Year 1212 (MCCXII) was a leap year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place   England  July 10 – The Great Fire: The most severe of several early fires of London burns most of the city to the ground; over 3,000 people die, many of them by drowning in the River Thames. According to a contemporary account: "An awful fire broke out on the Southwark side of London Bridge; while it was raging, a fire broke out at the other end also and so hemmed in the numerous crowds who had assembled to help the distressed.

Year 1270 ( MCCLXX ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) at noon (12:00 noon) and ending on the following Sunday at noon (12:00 noon). In England it was the year of Queen Elizabeth I.
Cannabis is a variety of cannabis plant used for medicinal and industrial purposes, both in the United Kingdom and elsewhere. It has been in use by humans since at least 7,000 years ago, although its exact usage is unclear. The word cannabis itself may also be derived from the Sanskrit words  "consciousness" and  "mind".

Nature versus nurture is a long-standing debate in biology about the balance between two competing factors which determine fate: environment (nurture) and genetics (nature). The alliterative expression "nature and nurture" in English has been in use since at least the Elizabethan period and goes back to medieval French.The complementary combination of the two concepts is an ancient concept . Nature is what people think of as pre-wiring and is influenced by genetic inheritance and other biological factors. Nurture is generally taken as the influence of external factors after conception e.g.

Year 1024 (MXXIV) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Emperor Basil II prepares a Byzantine expedition to invade Sicily. Governor Ahmed al-Akhal appeals to the Zirids of Ifriqiya for help. They dispatch a fleet, but these are caught up in a storm and destroyed near Pantelleria. Battle of Lemnos:  Kievan Viking raiders (800 men) sail through the straits at Abydos to the Aegean Sea. From there they make for the island of Lemnos, but are defeated by a Byzantine fleet of the Cibyrrhaeot Theme.

Pearl Harbour is a small harbour at the head of the Waiau River, in the town of Manapouri on the South Island of New Zealand.The harbour and town are located at the south-east corner of Lake Manapouri. The name was given to the harbour soon after the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor, Hawaii in 1941.Pearl Harbour is used mainly by ferry and water taxi operators transporting Meridian Energy staff  across Lake Manapouri to the Manapouri Hydroelectric Power Station, on the West Arm of the lake. Ferries also carry tourists travelling to the power station and onwards to Doubtful Sound, located on the coast 10 km beyond the West Arm.

Year 1395 (MCCCXCV) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display full calendar) of the Julian calendar, the 1395th year of the Common Era (CE) and Anno Domini (AD) designations, the 395th year of the 2nd millennium, the 95th year of the 14th century, and the 6th year of the 1390s decade.Events  January–December  February 12 – The army led by Sigismund of Luxembourg is ambushed by Stephen I of Moldavia, on its way back after conquering Neamț Citadel, and the Hungarians must retreat empty handed.

Year 1404 (MCDIV) was a leap year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  April or May – Battle of Blackpool Sands: Local English forces defeat an attempted raid from Saint-Malo on the port of Dartmouth, Devon; the French commander, William du Chastel, is killed. June 14 – Rebel leader Owain Glyndŵr, having declared himself Prince of Wales, allies with the French against the English. He later begins holding parliamentary assemblies. October 17 – Pope Innocent VII succeeds Pope Boniface IX, as the 204th pope.

Palermo ( , ;  , locally also  or ; , from ; older ) is a city in southern Italy, the capital of both the autonomous region of Sicily and the Metropolitan City of Palermo, the city's surrounding metropolitan province. The city is noted for its history, culture, architecture and gastronomy, playing an important role throughout much of its existence; it is over 2,700 years old. Palermo is in the northwest of the island of Sicily, by the Gulf of Palermo in the Tyrrhenian Sea.The city was founded in 734 BC by the Phoenicians as  ("flower").

Arthur Andersen LLP was an American holding company based in Chicago. Formerly one of the "Big Five" accounting firms (along with PricewaterhouseCoopers, Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu, Ernst & Young, and KPMG), the company had provided auditing, tax and consulting services to large corporations. By 2001, it had become one of the world's largest multinational corporations.In 2002, the firm voluntarily surrendered its licenses to practice as Certified Public Accountants in the United States after it was found guilty of crimes in the firm's auditing of Enron, an energy corporation based in Texas, which had filed for bankruptcy in 2001.

Year 1539 (MDXXXIX) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January – Toungoo–Hanthawaddy War – Battle of Naungyo, Burma: The Toungoos decisively defeat the Hanthawaddys. January 12 – Treaty of Toledo: Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor (and Charles I of Spain) and Francis I of France agree to make no further alliances with England. The treaty comes after Henry VIII of England's split with Rome and Pope Paul III. January 14 – Spain annexes Cuba.

McLean Hospital ( formerly known as Somerville Asylum and Charlestown Asylum ) is a psychiatric hospital in Belmont , Massachusetts, USA. It is the only facility in the New England region, and the only psychiatric hospital in the Eastern United States, and the only psychiatric hospital in the United States. It has been named one of the greatest mental health institutions of all time in the Harvard Business Review. It is one of the main medical centers for children who have mental health issues and has the highest rate of child suicides of any American hospital. In computer networking, a packet is a message transmitted over a network.

Jesus is comming this sundayYear 1423 ( MCDXXIII ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display in a popup window ) and ended on Tuesday (link will display in a popup window ), and it was commonly used to identify the year. It was also sometimes associated with the number 1422 (MCDXXV) (MCDXXVIII), indicating a year beginning on 7 January and ending on 14 December.The month of December was originally known as "Jupiter's month", from its Greek name for the god of fire, ἡμῦρας (hórais).

The Cathedral of St. John the Divine ( sometimes referred to as St. John 's and also nicknamed St. John's) is the spiritual and ecclesiastical center of the Orthodox Church in North America. It is one of the three principal cathedrals in the United States; the other two are Sts. Paul and Siloam and St. Nicholas Church in Detroit. Located on the north edge of the Detroit River in Pontiac, Michigan, St. John's was built for the use of the Eastern Orthodox community in Detroit. Flamenco is the genre of music and dance created in South America by the Flamenco dancers in the 19th century.

Frederick Barbarossa ( 1122 – 10 June 1190 ) , also known as Frederick I , was the Holy Roman Emperor from 1127 to his death in 1030. Born in the principality of Bavaria on the Rhine river, Barbarossa was raised in the court of the Duke of Aquitaine. In 1122 he was appointed by Otto I of Brandenburg to succeed Otto I as king of the Danes, but he refused the offer. Babar is the son of King Afzal and Queen Kausambi, and the younger brother of Shah Jahan, son of Shah Abbas.

As of March 1 (O.S. February 19), where then Julian calendar acknowledged a leap day and the Gregorian calendar did not, the Julian calendar fell one day further behind, bringing the difference to 11 days until February 28 (O.S. February 17), 1800.In Sweden, the year started in the Julian calendar and remained so until February 28. Then, by skipping the leap day, the Swedish calendar was introduced, letting February 28 be followed by March 1, giving the entire year the same pattern as a common year starting on Monday.

Year 1372 ( MCCCLXXII ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) in 1372, as well as the 366th anniversary of the publication of the Magna Carta . On 15 November 1372, King John signed a peace treaty with the French barons at the Temple of Solomon in London, the last treaty signed before the death of Edward VI in January 1453. [2][3][4][5]John died on 19 December 1372, the day of the Magna Carta's final session before its final signing.

Ross Powers (born February 10, 1979) is an American world champion halfpipe snowboarder from South Londonderry, Vermont, director of the snowboarding program at the Stratton Mountain School in Stratton, Vermont and a philanthropist.CareerThough he originally rode at Stratton Mountain, Vermont, his home mountain is now Okemo, Vermont. Powers helps with the design of the Superpipe and also helped design the RossCross Family Terrain Park. Powers also runs a snowboard camp through Okemo. He led the U.S. sweep in the 2002 Winter Olympics men's halfpipe competition, one day after his 23rd birthday.

Year 1379 (MCCCLXXIX) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–December  May 29 – John I succeeds his father, Henry II, as King of Castile and King of León. June 30 – New College, Oxford, is founded in England by William of Wykeham, Bishop of Winchester. July 1 – Forces of the Republic of Venice and Ottoman Turks, having invaded Constantinople, restore John V Palaiologos as Byzantine co-emperor. Andronikos IV Palaiologos is allowed to remain as co-emperor, but is confined to the city of Silivri for the remainder of his life.

Year 1316 (MCCCXVI) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 28–March 18 – Llywelyn Bren revolts against English rule in Wales. February 22 – Battle of Picotin: Catalan forces of Ferdinand of Majorca defeat those of Matilda of Hainaut on the Peloponnese. July 5 – Battle of Manolada: Forces of the Duchy of Burgundy defeat the Kingdom of Majorca, kill its king, Ferdinand, and conquer the Principality of Achaea. August – Battle of Gransee: A North German-Danish alliance, led by Henry II of Mecklenburg, decisively defeats the forces of Waldemar of Brandenburg.

Year 1406 (MCDVI) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  April 4 – James I becomes King of Scotland, after having been captured by Henry IV of England. October 7 – French troops comprising 1,000 men at arms land on Jersey, and fight a battle against 3,000 defenders. October 13 – Richard Whittington is elected Lord Mayor of London for a second full term. He holds this office simultaneously, with that of Mayor of the Calais Staple. October 26 – Eric of Pomerania marries Philippa, daughter of Henry IV of England.

Year 1201 ( MCCI ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending after the summer solstice on the last Thursday in September of the following calendar year. It is not a leapyear and therefore has the same date for all years on which it falls during the year. It is the same year 365.2425 days in length. The Middle Ages , also called the High Middle Ages , lasted from about 800 to the year 1200. In Europe and North Africa it lasted from 800 to 1100. In Italy and the Western Mediterranean (including Spain) from about 900 to 1000.

Albert III  (9 November 141411 March 1486) was Elector of Brandenburg from 1471 until his death, the third from the House of Hohenzollern. A member of the Order of the Swan, he received the cognomen Achilles  because of his knightly qualities and virtues. He also ruled in the Franconian principalities of Ansbach from 1440 and Kulmbach from 1464 (as Albrecht I).BiographyEarly lifeAlbert was born at the Brandenburg residence of Tangermünde as the third son of the Nuremberg burgrave Frederick I and his wife, the Wittelsbach princess Elisabeth of Bavaria-Landshut.

Charles Pierce ( July 14 , 1926 – May 31 , 1999 ) was one of the 20th century 's most influential American writers, with an estimated total of more than 150 novels and 60 short stories and essays. He was born in the Bronx , New York City. He was the son of Jewish immigrants.Pierce earned a Bachelor of Arts and a Ph.D. in English from Brown University, studied philosophy at Princeton University, and was awarded a fellowship at the University of Chicago. He was an assistant editor at the New Republic and later served on its editorial staff.

Year 1455 ( MCDLV ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and concluding on Thursday. It was named after Pope Clement V, as he was the archbishop of Bologna who made the day a national day of celebration and proclaimed that it would be observed as the first day of Lent on 22 May 1455.The first day of Lent in 1455 was on Tuesday and it became the first Monday of Lent the following year and then became the third Monday of Lent in 1462. The French Language (French, français) is the official national language of France.

Year 1515 ( MDXV ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Tuesday. The year began with Monday, 1501 and ended with Monday, 1515. The year was known as 1514, and the year itself as 1501, though it did not officially become a Julian year until 1541. John Hutton (14 August 1826 – 24 June 1905) was an English mathematician and astronomer who is best known for discovering Uranus. Hutton was the founder of the Astronomical Society in 1847.

McLean Hospital  (formerly known as Somerville Asylum and Charlestown Asylum) is a psychiatric hospital in Belmont, Massachusetts. It is noted for its clinical staff expertise and neuroscience research and is also known for the large number of famous people who have been treated there. McLean maintains the world's largest neuroscientific and psychiatric research program in a private hospital. It is the largest psychiatric facility of Harvard Medical School, an affiliate of Massachusetts General Hospital, and part of Mass General Brigham, which also includes Brigham and Women's Hospital.History McLean was founded in 1811 in a section of Charlestown, Massachusetts that is now a part of Somerville, Massachusetts.

Year 1131 ( MCXXXI ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) and lasting for the next seven days, which is commonly referred to as an academic year. This year was known as the Great Year.HistoryThere is evidence of the existence of the Gregorian Calendar in the fourth century CE, as written in a text called the Didascalia. It is not possible to date this text, and it may not even exist at all. History of Islam is a book by Imām Alī ibn Husayn al-Rāzī (; 678/681 – 10 May 681).

Donnybrook is a district of Dublin , Ireland . It is situated on the southside of the city , in the Dublin Mountains, and is bordered on the northwest by the city of Dublin, Ireland , to the south by the city of Waterford, Ireland , and on the east by the County of Wexford. The district's northern boundary corresponds to the Wicklow Mountains in the south of the county. In mathematics and computer science, a hash function is a function that maps values of a set A on a set M into a binary representation such that each binary digit is uniquely determined.

Tequila  is a distilled beverage made from the blue agave plant, primarily in the area surrounding the city of Tequila  northwest of Guadalajara, and in the Jaliscan Highlands (Los Altos de Jalisco) of the central western Mexican state of Jalisco.The red volcanic soils in the region of Tequila are well suited for growing the blue agave, and more than 300 million of the plants are harvested there each year. Agave grows differently depending on the region. Blue agaves grown in the highlands Los Altos region are larger and sweeter in aroma and taste. Agaves harvested in the valley region have a more herbaceous fragrance and flavor.

Events January–June January–June – The Swiss Peasant War is fought . January 3 – By the Coonan Cross Oath , French troops led by General de Maitland take over the fort of Maitland in France. January 9 – The British army under Sir Henry Wilson defeats the French army under Napoleon at Waterloo. In politics, the government is a governing body of government. It is a political institution in which a government (usually called a 'government of a country' or simply a 'government') acts as the head of the state by executive power and legislation.

Year 1150 (MCL) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Battle of Tara: The Byzantines defeat the Serbian-Hungarian army under Grdeša, count (župan) of Travunija, near the snow-covered Tara River. The Serbs are overpowered, and Grand Prince Uroš II is forced to accept the peace agreement made by Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos). Uroš is succeeded by his brother Desa, who  becomes co-ruler of the Principality of Serbia (until 1153).

The Polish People 's Party ( , PSL ) is an agrarian political party in Poland . It is currently led by Jarosław Kaczyński , who was formerly prime minister and president, and has a coalition with the centre-right Law and Justice Party (PiS) and the liberal Nowoczesna party. It won 31.6% of the vote, in the 2016 elections, making it Poland's largest opposition party.HistoryThe party traces its origins to a small agrarian party called Kaczyński (Kaczyński,  , ; 7 February 1884 – 14 December 1940) which was active from 1894 to 1924.

Events  January–June  January 18 – François, Duke of Anjou, attacks Antwerp. February 4 – Gebhard Truchsess von Waldburg, newly converted to Calvinism, formally marries Agnes von Mansfeld-Eisleben, a former canoness of Gerresheim, while retaining his position as Archbishop-Elector of Cologne. March 10 – The Queen Elizabeth's Men troupe of actors is ordered to be founded in England. May – Battle of Shizugatake in Japan: Shibata Katsuie is defeated by Toyotomi Hideyoshi, who goes on to commence construction of Osaka Castle. May 22 – Ernest of Bavaria is elected as Roman Catholic Archbishop of Cologne, in opposition to Gebhard Truchsess von Waldburg.

In mathematics, open sets are a generalization of  open intervals in the real line. In a metric space—that is, when a distance function is defined—open sets are the sets that, with every point , contain all points that are sufficiently near to  (that is, all points whose distance to  is less than some value depending on ).More generally, one defines open sets as the members of a given collection of subsets of a given set, a collection that has the property of containing every union of its members, every finite intersection of its members, the empty set, and the whole set itself.

Events  January–June  January 23 – The Triple Alliance of 1668 is formed between England, Sweden and the United Provinces. February 13 – In Lisbon, a peace treaty is established between Afonso VI of Portugal and Carlos II of Spain, by mediation of Charles II of England, in which the legitimacy of the Portuguese monarch is recognized. Portugal yields Ceuta to Spain. May 2 – The first Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle ends the War of Devolution. July–December  July 7 – Bishop Isaac Barrow founds the Bishop Barrow Trust with the intention of establishing a university on the Isle of Man; this becomes King William's College.

Optical rotation, also known as polarization rotation or circular birefringence, is the rotation of the orientation of the plane of polarization about the optical axis of linearly polarized light as it travels through certain materials. Circular birefringence and circular dichroism are the manifestations of optical activity. Optical activity occurs only in chiral materials, those lacking microscopic mirror symmetry. Unlike other sources of birefringence which alter a beam's state of polarization, optical activity can be observed in fluids. This can include gases or solutions of chiral molecules such as sugars, molecules with helical secondary structure such as some proteins, and also chiral liquid crystals.

Bessarabia (; ; ; , Bessarabiya; ; , Bessarabiya; , Besarabiya) is a historical region in Eastern Europe, bounded by the Dniester river on the east and the Prut river on the west. About two thirds of Bessarabia lies within modern-day Moldova, with the Ukrainian Budjak region covering the southern coastal region and part of the Ukrainian Chernivtsi Oblast covering a small area in the north.In the aftermath of the Russo-Turkish War (1806–1812), and the ensuing Peace of Bucharest, the eastern parts of the Principality of Moldavia, an Ottoman vassal, along with some areas formerly under direct Ottoman rule, were ceded to Imperial Russia.

Johan August Arfwedson ( 12 January 1792 – 28 October 1841 ) was a Swedish chemist who discovered the chemical element iridium and was one of the first discoverers of new elements.BiographyEarly life and educationArfwedson was born on 12 January 1792, in Sjöstad, the county capital of Örebro, Sweden, to a poor farmer. He studied at the Royal Academy of Fine Arts in Stockholm, then in Gothenburg. An airfoil is a surface structure that generates lift or thrust as air moves over it (usually as air passes by through the surface).

The Duchy of Anjou (, ; ; ) was a French province straddling the lower river Loire. Its capital was Angers and it was roughly coextensive with the diocese of Angers. Anjou was bordered by Brittany to the west, Maine to the north, Touraine to the east and Poitou to the south. The adjectival form is Angevin, and inhabitants of Anjou are known as Angevins. In 1482, the duchy became part of the Kingdom of France, and from then remained a province of the Kingdom under the name of the Duchy of Anjou.

arXiv ( pronounced `` archive '' —the X represents the Greek letter chi [ χ ] ) is an open-access repository of scientific research on many fields of knowledge. Each year, it is updated by the American Physical Society, with help of the National Science Foundation, in coordination with all participating research societies, and the editors of journals. As of December 2012, it contained 7,934 peer-reviewed, original research articles and books, covering a wide range of topics, from theoretical physics and cosmology to molecular biology, molecular genetics and cell biology.

Renate Titzia Groenewold (born 8 October 1976) is a Dutch former long track speed skater and road bicycle racer.Groenewold has won several Dutch Championships. In 1999, 2002 and 2003 she won the Dutch allround championship. At the European Allround Championships she has won various medals. Five times she came in third in the overall ranking. In 2005, she won the silver medal which was her best result at the European Championships. In 2001, she also came in third in the overall ranking on the World Allround Championships, which she won in 2004.Besides participating in the all-round championships Groenewold has participated in the championships for individual distances.

Year 1151 (MCLI) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  September 7 – Geoffrey of Anjou dies, and is succeeded by his son Henry, aged 18. After the Battle of Ghazni, the city is burned by the Prince of Ghur. The first plague and fire insurance policy is issued in Iceland. Bolton Abbey is founded in North Yorkshire, England. Anping Bridge is completed in China's Fujian province. Its total length will not be exceeded until 1846.

Year 1452 ( MCDLII ) was a leap year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Sunday ( link will open the calendar in a browser ). It also marked a significant milestone in the history of the Julian calendar and marked the year of the Incarnation of Christ.The Julian calendar was derived from the Old Testament (Genesis 12:2–5; Leviticus 22:25–26; Deuteronomy 32:1). It was a modification of the existing Roman, Gregorian and Gregorian reformed Julian calendars, in which twelve months had been added and the vernal equinox was kept the first of March instead of the seventh of December.

Adnams is a regional brewery founded in 1872 in Southwold , Suffolk , England , by George and Ernest Adnams. It is one of the oldest still-operating breweries in the UK and the second oldest still-operating in Europe after the oldest brewery in Poland. The brewery is currently owned by SABMiller Plc as a joint venture with Diageo, though it is known as the "Adnams" brewery to some and "Sebbi" to others. Agroecology is a global approach to crop production and sustainable management of natural resources which seeks to achieve food, feed and fiber security within a sustainable manner while improving human health and the environment.

Year 1343 (MCCCXLIII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 14 – Arnošt of Pardubice becomes the last bishop of Prague and, subsequently, the first Archbishop of Prague. January 27 – Pope Clement VI issues his bull Unigenitus, defining the doctrine of "The Treasury of Merits" or "The Treasury of the Church" as the basis for the issuance of indulgences by the Catholic Church. April 23 – The St. George's Night Uprising begins in Estonia.

Year 1020 (MXX) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  Summer – Emperor Henry II conducts his third Italian military campaign. He makes plans to invade the south, but remains non-commital. June 15 – Byzantine troops under Catepan Basil Boioannes (supported by his ally Prince Pandulf IV) capture the fortress of Troia. The French city of Saint-Germain-en-Laye is founded by King Robert II (the Pious). King Canute the Great codifies the laws of England (approximate date).

Vapor pressure ( or vapour pressure in English-speaking counties other than the US ; see spelling differences ) or equilibrium vapour pressure is the temperature at which vapor pressure equals the atmospheric pressure. This temperature is called the vapor boiling point, or the equilibrium vapour pressure, and is the lowest temperature that can be attained under ordinary conditions. It is defined as the absolute lowest pressure at which an object can hold its vapor phase as a liquid or a gas. In equilibrium conditions, the pressure in a liquid is the lowest pressure at which a gas is liquid at the same ambient temperature.

Poltava ( , ; ) is a city located on the Vorskla River in central Ukraine . It is the fourth largest city after Lviv, Odessa, and Kharkiv in the Dnipro region of Western Ukraine, as well as one of the largest towns in the Ukraine.
