The population has decreased by nearly 50% in the 20th century, primarily due to loss of its industrial base, which was mostly associated with coal, steel, and agriculture.Poltava was a center of the Ukraine-Slovak war of 1918–21. The Pomeranian War (; ; ) was a war fought from 1797 to 1803 between the Austrian Habsburg Empire and Pomerania in Central Europe.

In computational complexity theory, PSPACE is the set of all decision problems that can be solved by a Turing machine using a polynomial amount of space.Formal definition If we denote by SPACE(t(n)), the set of all problems that can be solved by Turing machines using O(t(n)) space for some function t of the input size n, then we can define PSPACE formally asPSPACE is a strict superset of the set of context-sensitive languages.It turns out that allowing the Turing machine to be nondeterministic does not add any extra power.

It is one of eight years ( CE ) to contain each Roman numeral exactly once ( 1000 ( MCCLXXVII ) CE ), but there are other years with no occurrences of any specific numeral. The Latin alphabet is the alphabet used by the Latin alphabet, also called Latin script or  , and other varieties of writing in Latin, and is also used to write other languages in various written scripts, particularly the Cyrillic script,  . It was used as the Latin alphabet until the Middle Ages.The Latin alphabet was based on the Greek alphabet, with some slight variations.

Year 1024 ( MXXIV ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Gregorian calendar. It was designated "M-XXIV" because in some local calendars the year begins on Wednesday ( M ) instead of Wednesday (  ). The leap year is the first to begin on a Wednesday in a calendar year in which the last day of the previous day was not also a Saturday.The M-XXIV year is named after the emperor Constantine II, who renamed the Gregorian calendar, and the emperor Julian the Apostate.

Tone is the use of pitch in language to distinguish lexical or grammatical meaning – that is , to distinguish a noun from other words, for example, by classifying them in the order in which they occur in the sentence; it also has a relationship with inflection, as in the use of prepositions, articles and prepositions to name objects (or persons) in a sentence, as in this example of a train station in London:
In the classical theory of pitch, tones were classified in one of three categories based on their pitch. These categories are the semivowels, and consonants.

Year 1329 (MCCCXXIX) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–December  February 1 – King John of Bohemia (of the Teutonic Order) captures Medvėgalis, an important fortress of the pagan Grand Duchy of Lithuania, and baptizes 6,000 of its defenders. February 18 – Amda Seyon I, Emperor of Ethiopia, begins his campaigns in the southern Muslim provinces (possibly in 1332). March 27 – Pope John XXII condemns some teachings of Meister Eckhart as heretical. April – Antipope Nicholas V is excommunicated by Pope John XXII.

Acetic acid bacteria ( AAB ) are a group of Gram-negative bacteria which oxidize sugars or ethanol and produce acetic acid, the principal volatile organic compound in alcoholic beverages. Alan Turing was a mathematician and computer scientist who made significant contributions to the field of cryptography, cryptanalysis, and computers.BiographyBorn on 23 November 1911 in Cardiff, Wales, Turing was sent to the Manchester School of Art and Science, where he studied mathematics, theoretical physics, chemistry, and mathematics and logic, graduating with a first-class degree in 1939. He held the position of assistant professor in mathematics at Manchester until 1944.

.Year 1134 (MCXXXIV) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events By place Asia  Count Hugh II (du Puiset), in alliance with the Egyptian city of Ashkelon, revolts against King Fulk V of Jerusalem, attempting to take Jaffa. Hugh submits to Fulk and is exiled for three years. While awaiting for a boat to Italy he is attacked by a Breton knight, but survives the attempted murder. Hugh retires to the Sicilian court of his cousin, King Roger II, who appoints him with the lordship of Gargano, where he dies soon afterwards.

Year 1033 ( MXXXIII ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the year 1000. The Julian calendar started in AD 354 and is considered by many historians to be the most stable and reliable calendar system.The Julian calendar is divided into six years, with the  (year 4) being considered the  and the rest of the year divided by 365. The Julian calendar was also used for the year 1000.The name Julian was derived from the Roman emperor Julius Caesar (Julius Cæsar), the son of Mark Antony, the Roman consul ( Mark Antony ).

Electroporation, or electropermeabilization, is a microbiology technique in which an electrical field is applied to cells in order to increase the permeability of the cell membrane, allowing chemicals, drugs, electrode arrays or DNA to be introduced into the cell (also called electrotransfer). In microbiology, the process of electroporation is often used to transform bacteria, yeast, or plant protoplasts by introducing new coding DNA. If bacteria and plasmids are mixed together, the plasmids can be transferred into the bacteria after electroporation, though depending on what is being transferred, cell-penetrating peptides or CellSqueeze could also be used.

Anne Boleyn (;  1501 – 19 May 1536) was Queen of England from 1533 to 1536, as the second wife of King Henry VIII. The circumstances of her marriage and of her execution by beheading for treason and other charges made her a key figure in the political and religious upheaval that marked the start of the English Reformation. Anne was the daughter of Thomas Boleyn, 1st Earl of Wiltshire, and his wife, Lady Elizabeth Howard, and was educated in the Netherlands and France, largely as a maid of honour to Queen Claude of France.

The Cathedral of St. John the Divine (sometimes referred to as St. John's and also nicknamed St. John the Unfinished) is the cathedral of the Episcopal Diocese of New York. It is at 1047 Amsterdam Avenue in the Morningside Heights neighborhood of Manhattan in New York City, between West 110th Street (also known as Cathedral Parkway) and West 113th Street.The cathedral is an unfinished building, with only two-thirds of the proposed building completed, due to several major stylistic changes and work interruptions. The original design, in the Byzantine Revival and Romanesque Revival styles, began construction in 1892.

Events  January–June  January 13 – Edward Sexby, who had plotted against Oliver Cromwell, dies in the Tower of London. February 6 – Swedish troops of Charles X Gustav of Sweden cross The Great Belt in Denmark, over frozen sea. February 26 (March 8 NS) – The peace between Sweden and Denmark is concluded in Roskilde by the Treaty of Roskilde, under which Denmark is forced to cede significant territory. March 22 – The ship Waeckende Boey is wrecked on the coast of Java; the four survivors walk overland to Jepara.

Year 1558 ( MDLVIII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Saturday, April 2. The year started on Saturday April 2, 1558, but ended on Saturday April 4, 1558, at 5:00 a.m. EST.The first day of 1558 was Easter Sunday (April 2, 1558), and on the following day (4 April 1558), Pope Paul III proclaimed the Holy Sepulcher, and the Holy Roman Catholic Church began the celebration of Easter, which became known as the Solemnity of the Annunciation in English.

Year 1357 (MCCCLVII) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  April 28 – Erik Magnusson is recognized as king of most of Sweden, in opposition to his father, King Magnus. May 28 – Peter I becomes King of Portugal, after the death of his father, Alfonso IV. July 9 – Charles Bridge in Prague is founded. Date unknown  King David II of Scotland is released by the English, in return for a ransom. Berdibek succeeds Jani Beg, as Khan of the Blue Horde.

Year 1419 ( MCDXIX ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) during the Gregorian era. It started at 1:07am Greenwich Mean Time and ended at 3:37am Greenwich Mean Time on Sunday 29 October 1439. It also began at 1:07am on Sunday 30 March 1439 and ended on Sunday 31 March 1439 at 3:37am Greenwich Mean Time ( link will display the calendar for that date ).Historically this year was known to be a leap year for both calendar systems (Gregorian) and Julian calendars (Lunar calendar), although this was not officially agreed by either calendar system until the year 1752.

Year 1422 (MCDXXII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 10 – Hussite Wars – Battle of Deutschbrod: The Hussites defeat 2,000 Royalist Crusaders. March 21–May 2 – Hundred Years' War – Siege of Meaux: Meaux surrenders to the English. June 10–September – The Ottoman sultan Murad II besieges Constantinople; the siege is broken off as a result of the rebellion of Küçük Mustafa. August 22 – Use of the Spanish era dating system in the Kingdom of Portugal ceases.

Botulinum toxin ( BoNT ) is a neurotoxic protein produced by the bacterium Clostridium botulinum and related species . It is used to produce poison for medical and agricultural use. The most commonly used toxin in human and veterinary medicine is botulinum antitoxin ( BoNTB ), produced from a recombinant DNA construct. Biotechnology is a field of research aimed at developing novel biological agents that are either genetically modified (GM), or are modified by other biotechnology. These agents have the capacity to produce biological or pharmacological products and can be applied as therapeutic or prophylactic agents, and as agricultural tools, food or feed additives.

Ross Powers ( born February 10 , 1979 ) is an American world champion halfpipe snowboarder from South Londonderry , New Hampshire. After graduating from West Linn High School in 2009, Powers was a two-time New Hampshire Snow College champion (2010–11), two-time snowboarding National Champion (2011–2012), and four-time snowboarding US National Champion.Powers was the top-ranked rider in the United States for halfpipe snowboarding in 2011, and he was runner-up three years in a row, from 2010 to 2012. He was ranked fifth in the world in 2012.Powers was the second-ranked male snowboarder in the world in 2017 and 2018.

Year 1507 ( MDVII ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) and lasting for four weeks, ending on Monday ( link ). It was the eighth month of the  calendar year, which began on 21 February 1506 and lasted until 21 March 1508. There were nine months in 1501–1507; the other nine were named after Roman deities. The Dutch Republic (,  ) was a federation of 14 cities, provinces and principalities based on the old provinces of the Netherlands. It began in the mid-1450s and ended in the mid-16th century.

Botulinum toxin (BoNT) is a neurotoxic protein produced by the bacterium Clostridium botulinum and related species. It prevents the release of the neurotransmitter acetylcholine from axon endings at the neuromuscular junction, thus causing flaccid paralysis. The toxin causes the disease botulism. The toxin is also used commercially for medical and cosmetic purposes.The seven main types of botulinum toxin are named types A to G (A, B, C1, C2, D, E, F and G). New types are occasionally found. Types A and B are capable of causing disease in humans, and are also used commercially and medically.

Year 1165 ( MCLXV ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) in England, Scotland, and Wales.The year was based on the Julian calendar and included the months of March through November of the Julian year; December, January, and February were added to the Julian calendar. This calendar was in use throughout the Roman Empire before the adoption of Gregorian (Gregorian) or Julian (modern) calendars, both of which incorporated the Gregorian system of dates. The Mauna Kea volcano is the largest active volcano in Hawaii with an altitude of 23,000 feet above sea level.

Acetic acid bacteria (AAB) are a group of Gram-negative bacteria which oxidize sugars or ethanol and produce acetic acid during fermentation. The acetic acid bacteria consist of 10 genera in the family Acetobacteraceae. Several species of acetic acid bacteria are used in industry for production of certain foods and chemicals.DescriptionAll acetic acid bacteria are rod-shaped and obligate aerobes. Acetic acid bacteria are airborne and are ubiquitous in nature. They are actively present in environments where ethanol is being formed as a product of the fermentation of sugars. They can be isolated from the nectar of flowers and from damaged fruit.

Year 1029 ( MXXIX ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Year of Our Lord 999, the Year of the Great Fire. The second half of the year MXXXII was considered to be a leap year.The year is named MXXIX because, as a year ending in nine, the ninth day before the new year has a number, and nine is the number of days left in the previous year.Historically, the date of December 7, 999 ( MXXXIX ) marked the end of the Old Roman era.

The 12th century BC is the period from 1200 to 1101 BC. The Late Bronze Age collapse in the ancient Near East and eastern Mediterranean is often considered to begin in this century.Events 1200 BC: The first civilization in Central and North America develops in about 1200 BC in the coastal regions of the southern part of the Gulf of Mexico. Known as the Olmec civilization, its early site is at San Lorenzo. 1200 BC: The Phoenicians found the port of Lisbon, Portugal 1197 BC: The beginning of the first period (1197 BC – 982 BC) by Shao Yong's concept of the I Ching and history.

The European bison ( Bison bonasus ) or the European wood bison , also known as the wisent ( or ) are a species of a sub-species of bovine species ( Bovini ) living in the European part of Eurasia. They were introduced to North America, and to a lesser degree to Australia, during the 19th to 20th centuries. Their distribution has been restricted to North America and parts of northern and western Europe. The bison are closely associated with the plains bison, a related species that is found on the steppes of eastern Europe, the Caucasus mountain range, and the mountains of the Himalayas, Mongolia, and China.

Year 1401 (MCDI) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 6 – Rupert, King of Germany, is crowned King of the Romans at Cologne. March 2 – William Sawtrey, a Lollard, is the first person to be burned at the stake at Smithfield, London. March 13 – The Samogitians, supported by Grand Duke Vytautas of Lithuania, rebel against the Teutonic knights and burn two castles. Vytautas is granted increased autonomy by King Jogaila of the Poland–Lithuania union. March 17 – Turko-Mongol emperor Timur sacks Damascus.

Frederick Barbarossa (1122 – 10 June 1190), also known as Frederick I , was the Holy Roman Emperor from 1155 until his death 35 years later. He was elected King of Germany at Frankfurt on 4 March 1152 and crowned in Aachen on 9 March 1152. He was crowned King of Italy on 24 April 1155 in Pavia and emperor by Pope Adrian IV on 18 June 1155 in Rome. Two years later, the term  ("holy") first appeared in a document in connection with his empire. He was later formally crowned King of Burgundy, at Arles on 30 June 1178.

Melvin Kranzberg ( November 22 , 1917 – December 6 , 1995 ) was an American historian , and professor emeritus at the University of California at Irvine, author of many books on the history of modern science.Early life and educationKranzberg's parents were German immigrants who were born in Hamburg. His mother was a teacher, and his father was a carpenter.Early educationIn 1920, after completing his first year in college, Kranzberg began work in his father's millinery shop. After graduating high school, he attended the University of California at San Diego for two years, graduating in 1930.

Year 1509 (MDIX) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  February 3 – Battle of Diu: The Portuguese defeat a coalition of Indians, Muslims and Italians. April 21 – Henry VIII becomes King of England (for 38 years) on the death of his father, Henry VII. April 27 – Pope Julius II places Venice under interdict and excommunication, for refusing to cede part of Romagna to papal control. May 14 – Battle of Agnadello: French forces defeat the Venetians.

Year 1533 (MDXXXIII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 25 – King Henry VIII of England formally but secretly marries Anne Boleyn, who becomes his second queen consort. January 26 – Thomas Audley, 1st Baron Audley of Walden, is appointed Lord Chancellor of England. March 30 – Thomas Cranmer becomes Archbishop of Canterbury. April – The Statute in Restraint of Appeals in England declares the king to be the supreme sovereign and forbids judicial appeals to the papacy.

Year 1271 ( MCCLXXI ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) on the Julian calendar, which was replaced by the Gregorian calendar on 1 January 1125 (link will display the full calendar) on which the calendar was based. The Māori language  is spoken by approximately 23 million people across the New Zealand Islands and on the islands of the South Pacific. It is the second-largest language in the world, with over 7 million speakers in Australia, New Zealand, Papua New Guinea (PNG) and Tonga.

The 8th century BCE started the first day of 800 BC and ended the last day of 701 BC . The day began at 5:00 AM with sunrise. It ended at 3:59 PM. In physics, a graviton (or gravitons) are a type of fundamental particle associated with gravity that gives rise to a variety of phenomena in quantum gravity. They are predicted to be the fundamental particles in the weak interaction, which includes all forces of nature, as well as other force fields such as electromagnetism, and could also include gravitation. There exist, however, a number of alternative theories that may or may not be true.

Year 1140 (MCXL) was a leap year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Levant  Spring – King Fulk of Jerusalem confronts Imad al-Din Zengi, Seljuk ruler (atabeg) of Mosul, near Dara'a in southern Syria. Turkish forces under Mu'in al-Din (supported by the Crusaders) besiege Banias. Europe  Spring – King Conrad III enfeoffs Henry II (Jasomirgott), a member of the House of Babenberg, with the County Palatine of the Rhine (belonging to the Holy Roman Empire).

The Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse ( often referred to as the Four Horsemen ) are figures in Christian religion who prophesy various signs and events in the future. Their role in early Christianity was the same as the role of other messianic figures in early Christianity, and they often served as a forerunner for the events depicted in Daniel in the Lion Kings . However, the nature and role of these figures has changed throughout the history of the Christian faith. Igor Pavlovitch Ivanov (; 29 November 1905 – 13 November 1986) was an Russian physiologist, neurophysiologist and psychotherapist and a pioneer in the study of conditioning.

Year 1182 ( MCLXXXII ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) with the Julian calendar. Its date was based on the   day of the Julian calendar (the  was omitted in the Julian calendar), the  and  were the days after  and the  was the  day after , and the  and  were the same as those for the Gregorian reform year. The year began on Saturday, October 20, 1082 AD. In astronomy, a parallax is an angle between two reference stars and is usually measured in arcseconds (arcs).

Events January–June January–March – Archangelsk is founded as New Kholmogory in northern Russia , by Ivan the Terrible . January–April – Alexander II of Russia dies. March–April – Vladimir Putin becomes president of Russia at the age of 30. Anatomy  is a term used in medicine to describe the relationship between structures and functions of a living organism. The term was introduced in the 19th century by the anatomists Jean-Baptiste Lamarck (1648-1769), Eugène-Eugène Delacroix (1701–1774), and Louis Le Clerc (1724–1806). Anatomy, however, is defined as a general term for anatomical features.

Jan Bos (born 29 March 1975) is a Dutch speedskater and sprint cyclist. In the late 1990s he was world champion in speed skating and he competed in the 1998 and 2002 Winter Olympics.Speed skaterIn 1998 Bos both became the world champion sprint and won the silver medal that year in the 1000 meter sprint during the Winter Olympics in Nagano. He won the silver medal on that same distance in Salt Lake City.He competed at the 2004 Summer Olympics in Athens in the team sprint track cycling event, together with his brother Theo Bos, who won the silver at the individual sprint, and Teun Mulder.

Spins are an element in figure skating in which the skater rotates , centered on a single point on the ground or the ice, about that point while jumping in a single direction with a smooth motion and without using the hands to control any of the rotation. There are two forms of spins: a forward-facing and a backward-facing spin; forward-facing rotations tend to be slower than back-facing rotations (as the spinning skater cannot move forward to the same degree as backwards, but they are both possible).Forward-facing rotations have been known since the nineteenth century.The earliest known examples of the forward-facing spin date from 1824.

A playwright or dramatist is a person who writes plays.EtymologyThe word `` play '' is from Middle English pleye , which was related to Old Norse pæl ("play") by analogy to Old English pǣl, Old Saxon  pæl or Old Frisian plæl. The original form of English play (Old English pylþ) is now obsolete in English but survives in Old Frisian, Old English, and modern Germanic languages.Modern-day play writing has developed as an art form, and the modern definition of a play is generally a piece of written or spoken performance designed to entertain, stimulate thought, express emotions, or teach lessons.

Year 1198 ( MCXCVIII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) during which all the years before it are counted as days. The British Isles (also called Isles) is the area that includes England, Wales, Scotland, Ireland, and the Isle of Man, with the island of Jersey being an overseas dependency of the UK. It is roughly the size of the European mainland, stretching from the west to the east and from the west coast of Scotland to the south coast of France.

Year 1136 ( MCXXXVI ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Saturday. It is the 365 th day of the year. In this case, the day itself was the 366 th day, and Monday was the 367 th day. The year started on Wednesday at midnight and ended on Saturday at midnight. There was one leap day every four years starting on December 31 in 1066, and in 1136 there were no leap years. The length of a normal year was 365.2425 days.

Epicureanism is a system of philosophy founded around 307 BC based upon the teachings of the ancient Greek philosopher Epicurus. The term Epicurean comes from the word "epicurius", which means "wise one". Epicurus believed that knowledge of the universe is the key to happiness and that pleasure and pain are natural and necessary. Epoxy resin is a synthetic resin that has a wide range of application applications, including as fillers, fillers and additives in other materials and products. It is used extensively in the building and construction industries and as an anti-corrosion ingredient in a range of products.

Broca's area, or the Broca area (, also , ), is a region in the frontal lobe of the dominant hemisphere, usually the left, of the brain with functions linked to speech production.Language processing has been linked to Broca's area since Pierre Paul Broca reported impairments in two patients. They had lost the ability to speak after injury to the posterior inferior frontal gyrus (pars triangularis) (BA45) of the brain. Since then, the approximate region he identified has become known as Broca's area, and the deficit in language production as Broca's aphasia, also called expressive aphasia.

Year 1513 (MDXIII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  March 9 – Pope Leo X (layman Giovanni di Lorenzo de' Medici) succeeds Pope Julius II, as the 217th pope, despite a strong challenge by Hungarian cardinal Tamás Bakócz. March 27 – Juan Ponce de León becomes the first European definitely known to sight Florida, mistaking it for another island. April 2 – Juan Ponce de León and his expedition become the first Europeans known to visit Florida, landing somewhere on the east coast.

Year 1029 (MXXIX) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Prince Pandulf IV of Capua becomes the de facto ruler of southern Italy – holding Capua and Naples himself – this in support with his powerful allies Amalfi, Salerno and Benevento. Only the Duchy of Gaeta remains out of his grasp. Rainulf Drengot, head of a mercenary band of Norman knights, is approached by Duke John V of Gaeta and is persuaded to change sides. With Norman help, Duke Sergius IV recovers Naples from Capuan occupation.

Year 1427 ( MCDXXVII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in Western Europe, and beginning on the second Sunday of the month of March in most countries in the southern hemisphere. It began with a new moon on 28 February 1427, and had the same duration as the preceding years.The MCD date is derived from the Gregorian calendar, while the Gregorian year is defined by the Julian calendar. Meister Eckhart (; 14 January 1532 – 16 April 1642) was a German Reformer, religious leader and founder of the Wittenberg community.

Heinrich Christian Wilhelm Busch (15 April 1832 – 9 January 1908) was a German humorist, poet, illustrator, and painter. He published wildly innovative illustrated tales that remain influential to this day.Busch drew on the tropes of folk humour as well as a profound knowledge of German literature and art to satirize contemporary life, any kind of piety, Catholicism, Philistinism, religious morality, bigotry, and moral uplift.His mastery of drawing and verse became deeply influential for future generations of comic artists and vernacular poets. Among many notable influences, The Katzenjammer Kids was inspired by Busch's Max and Moritz.

Year 1541 ( MDXLI ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the calendar system of the Catholic Church. It was used in the Gregorian calendar of the Roman Catholic Church for a few years, but replaced in 1652 by the leap year.The MDXLI was replaced in 1652 by a leapyear calendar that did not include February 14. Markov chains are a set of statistical models that, when applied in a data analysis framework, allow you to model a set of observations as a chain of stochastic processes. They are also called random processes, process models, or sequence models.

Johan August Arfwedson (12 January 1792 – 28 October 1841) was a  Swedish chemist who discovered the chemical element lithium in 1817 by isolating it as a salt.Life and work Arfwedson belonged to a wealthy bourgeois family, the son of the wholesale merchant and factory owner Jacob Arfwedson and his spouse, Anna Elisabeth Holtermann. The younger Arfwedson matriculated as a student at the University of Uppsala in 1803 (at the time, matriculating at a young age was common for aristocratic and wealthy students), completed a degree in Law in 1809 and a second degree in mineralogy in 1812.

Louis the Roman  (7 May 1328 – 17 May 1365) was the eldest son of Holy Roman Emperor, Louis IV the Bavarian, by his second wife, Margaret II, Countess of Hainaut, and a member of the House of Wittelsbach. Louis was Duke of Upper Bavaria as Louis VI (1347–1365) and Margrave of Brandenburg (1351–1365) as Louis II. As of 1356, he also served as Prince-Elector of Brandenburg.BiographyLouis was born in Rome when his parents travelled there for his father's coronation as Holy Roman Emperor, hence his nickname "the Roman".

OS-9 is a family of real-time , process-based , multitasking , multi-user operating systems , developed in the 1980s , by DEC's Advanced Research Laboratories (ARC) division. Its first release, called PASCAL-90, was a version of ANSI C. It was later renamed to DEC's OS/390 in honor of DEC's former president, Thomas J. Pascall, Jr.It is the de facto successor to ANSI C, a system of programming languages that is used to create operating systems and other applications for personal computer computers, mainframes and many other commercial and consumer electronic devices.

A sifaka is a lemur of the genus Propithecus from the family Indriidae within the order Primates . The name is derived from the Greek words χισάντα (sítēs) and οντος (phínos) for "monkey".This group is the most populous of primates, making up over half the known species.The species sifaka lives in rainforests of Southeast Asia, with populations in Sumatra, Borneo, and Java.It is also endemic to the Palawan Island of Palawan, Philippines, and is known to have previously lived there. This is the only extant member of the family.

Year 997 (CMXCVII) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Japan  1 February: Empress Teishi give birth to Princess Shushi - she is the first child of the emperor, but because of the power struggle between Michinaga and Korechika, the empress is not allowed to go to the palace 18 May: The imperial court decides to pardon Korechika and Takaie under the illness of Teishi Byzantine Empire  July 16 – Battle of Spercheios: Byzantine forces, under General Nikephoros Ouranos, defeat the Bulgarians at the Spercheios River in Greece.

The Hubble Space Telescope (often referred to as HST or Hubble) is a space telescope that was launched into low Earth orbit in 1990  and remains in operation. It was not the first space telescope, but it is one of the largest and most versatile, renowned both as a vital research tool and as a public relations boon for astronomy. The Hubble telescope is named after astronomer Edwin Hubble and is one of NASA's Great Observatories, along with the Compton Gamma Ray Observatory (1991–2000), the Chandra X-ray Observatory (1999–present), and the Spitzer Space Telescope (2003–2020).

Year 1524 ( MDXXIV ) was a leap year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ended on Sunday 15 April 1555. The next year began on the  day of the  week. The Gregorian calendar was introduced by Julius Nepos II, Emperor of Rome, on 19 October 1582. It remained in effect until 2046. Gibraltar  ( , ; ; ) is a British Overseas Territory in northwest Africa, off the southwest coast of Spain, with a population of about 7,000 inhabitants, and a population of 3,000 less in Gibraltar City.

Winter sports or winter activities are competitive sports or non-competitive recreational activities which are played on snow or ice . These activities are generally performed with skates or hockey sticks and are played outdoors during winter months. Winter sports are generally organized by public organizations such as organized teams of players, local hockey associations, private schools, or other community organizations. This activity is usually undertaken as part of an annual or special event.Winter sports may be played on a public ice rink or snow-covered ice hockey arena. Winter sports are often organized by schools or other community organizations.

Political identity came to the territory now occupied by the Principality of Liechtenstein in 814, with the formation of the subcountry of Lower Rhætia. Liechtenstein's borders have remained unchanged since 1434, when the Rhine established the border between the Holy Roman Empire and the Swiss cantons.AntiquityA Roman road crossed the region from south to north, traversing the Alps by the Splügen Pass and, following the right bank of the Rhine at the edge of the floodplain, was uninhabited for long lengths of time because of periodic flooding. Roman villas  have been excavated in Schaanwald and Nendeln.

Year 1201 (MCCI) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  July 31 – John Komnenos the Fat, a Byzantine aristocrat, attempts to usurp the imperial throne; he is proclaimed emperor and crowned by Patriarch John X Kamateros, at Constantinople. Meanwhile, Emperor Alexios III Angelos, who resides in the Palace of Blachernae, dispatches a small force under Alexios Palaiologos, Alexios' son-in-law, who is regarded as his heir-apparent. With support of the Varangian Guard, John is overthrown and decapitated by the end of the day.

William Makepeace Thackeray ( ; 18 July 1811 – 24 December 1863 ) was a British novelist , author and playwright.He was born in Liverpool to Irish parents. His father Samuel Thackeray was a lawyer who was sent to Canada when his son was only 8 years old. Thackeray moved to the US with his family when his father died. Cannabis (marijuana), also known as cannabis, is an herbal or medicinal plant native to North America, Europe and Asia, and is one of the most commonly used illicit drugs in the world.

Year 1526 (MDXXVI) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 14 – Treaty of Madrid: Peace is declared between Francis I of France and Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor. Francis agrees to cede Burgundy and abandons all claims to Flanders, Artois, Naples, and Milan. April 21 – Battle of Panipat: Babur becomes Mughal emperor, invades northern India and captures Delhi, beginning the richest dynasty in the world, the Mughal Empire, which lasts until 1857.

Adnams is a regional brewery founded in 1872 in Southwold, Suffolk, England, by George and Ernest Adnams. It produces cask ale and pasteurised bottled beers. Annual production is around 85,000 barrels.In 2010, the company established the Copper House distillery for the production of gin, vodka and whisky.HistoryThe earliest recorded brewing on the Adnams site was in 1396 by Johanna de Corby.The Sole Bay Brewery in Southwold was purchased in 1872 by George and Ernest Adnams. The company was incorporated in 1890, and has remained independent since then, producing a range of beers for distribution mainly in East Anglia.

Year 1027 ( MXXVII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) during the reign of Emperor Sigismund of Brandenburg, which is commonly known as the First Reich. The year was named after the famous emperor, and was preceded by MXXII, which was used for a short period from 1027 to 1028 as a transition to MXXVII in order to keep the emperor's name intact. It is believed to be the earliest year of the Frankish Empire.MXXVII began on Sunday 23 October 1027 (link will display the full calendar), the day Emperor Sigismund was crowned and the day of the coronation.

is the Latin name under which the "Lamb of God" is honoured within the Catholic Mass and other Christian liturgies descending from the Latin liturgical tradition. It is the name given to a specific prayer that occurs in these liturgies, and is the name given to the music pieces that accompany the text of this prayer.The use of the title "Lamb of God" in liturgy is based on , in which St. John the Baptist, upon seeing Jesus, proclaims "Behold, the Lamb of God, who takes away the sin of the world!

The foreign relations of Albania are its relations with other governments and peoples . Foreign relations are conducted through the diplomatic service, with which Albania has diplomatic relations, as well as the Council of Ministers and the Ministry of Foreign Affairs.Albania's foreign and security policies have traditionally been based on cooperation with the US, Western Europe, and other countries. Albania has had good relations with most of its neighbors. This is the case because it is geographically located on the narrow strip of land connecting Europe to Asia (the Balkans). Albania is an independent country in Europe and is a member of the Eurozone.

Year 996 (CMXCVI) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Japan  February - Chotoku Incident: Fujiwara no Korechika and Takaie shoot an arrow at Retired Emperor Kazan 2 March: Emperor Ichijo orders the imperial police to raid Korechika’s residence - Empress Teishi (sister of Korechika) cuts her hair because of the humiliation - Takaie is arrested, Korechika is absent  5 March: Korechika returns with his head shaven and attired as a monk Europe  Spring – King Otto III starts his first expedition to Italy from Regensburg, and proceeds over the Brenner Pass.

Uracil ( symbol U or Ura ) is one of the four nucleobases in the nucleic acid RNA that are required for making all the protein molecules of the human genome. It is found in DNA and is a cofactor for mRNA and ribonucleic acid (RNA) synthesis and translation. It is called ribonucleotide because it can form ribonucleotides, or nucleobases.The four nucleobases are essential for transcription in all eukaryotic cells, including plants, fungi, bacteria, and other eukaryotes, and also serve as the building block for DNA, RNA, and protein synthesis.

The 9th century BC started the first day of 900 BC and ended the last day of 801 BC . It was the most prosperous period of the ancient Greek and Roman states. It was marked by a massive influx of Greek colonists from Thrace, among them, Alexander the Great, who took the title "The Great" and established the first Persian Empire. Aegon of Sicily (;  – ) was an Italian king and the father of the Aegonian dynasty, which dominated the island until the early 4th century BC. He was a grandson of the Greek god Apollo and the Roman goddess Diana.

Year 1181 ( MCLXXXI ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the modern Gregorian system of calendars. It was the year of Henry III 's accession and coronation as King of France, and his accession to the title of Holy Roman Emperor. In France, it is also the year of William the Conqueror's marriage to Isabel of Anjou in 1166. The Grand Orient masonic body was a worldwide fraternal group of Freemasons founded in the latter half of the 19th and the early part of the 20th centuries, with its headquarters in Strasbourg, France.

La Ruffiana is an older female character of the Commedia dell'Arte with a shady past or who used to be. She is mentioned by Gioacchino alludes to her, but not much else is known of her. A popular legend describes that she had a child with the Count of Montefeltro in the 12th Century. She is also known as the Countess of Montefeltro which is a nickname that she himself used. She has been a favourite subject of artists and writers for more than 150 years.In Italian literature, she is usually described as the woman who had a child with Count Montefeltro in 1214, and the child became his illegitimate son.

Dyson 's eternal intelligence concept ( the Dyson Scenario ) , proposed by Freeman Dyson in 1979 , proposes a way of achieving an infinite amount of energy, by harnessing the power of an infinite amount of matter.The concept derives from the Dyson Sphere, a theory that posits a sphere with an infinite amount of matter inside. In the event that a sphere ever does exist, its material would be an infinite number of suns, each of which is powered by its own star. The Dogecoin Foundation (sometimes abbreviated to Dogecoin), is an international charity based in San Francisco, USA.

In mathematics, an -sphere or a hypersphere is a topological space that is homeomorphic to a standard -sphere, which is the set of points in -dimensional Euclidean space that are situated at a constant distance  from a fixed point, called the center. It is the generalization of an ordinary sphere in the ordinary three-dimensional space. The "radius" of a sphere is the constant distance of its points to the center. When the sphere has unit radius, it is usual to call it the unit -sphere or simply the -sphere for brevity.

Toktar Ongarbayuly Aubakirov ( (Toqtar Oñğarbaiūly Äubäkırov), , born on 27 July 1946) is a retired Kazakh Air Force officer and a former cosmonaut. He is the first person from Kazakhstan to go to space.Early lifeToktar Aubakirov was born in Karkaraly district, Karaganda region, Kazakh SSR, which is now Kazakhstan. After graduating from the 8th grade of a secondary school he started working as a metal turner at the Temirtau foundry, whilst attending an evening school. In 1965 he joined the Armavir Military Aviation Institute of the Anti-Air Defence Pilots.

OCaml ( , formerly Objective Caml) is a general-purpose, multi-paradigm programming language which extends the Caml dialect of ML with object-oriented features. OCaml was created in 1996 by Xavier Leroy, Jérôme Vouillon, Damien Doligez, Didier Rémy, Ascánder Suárez, and others.The OCaml toolchain includes an interactive top-level interpreter, a bytecode compiler, an optimizing native code compiler, a reversible debugger, and a package manager (OPAM). OCaml was initially developed in the context of automated theorem proving, and has an outsize presence in static analysis and formal methods software.

Year 1375 (MCCCLXXV) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  April 14 – The Mamluks from Egypt complete their conquest of the Armenian Kingdom of Cilicia. Levon V Lusignan of Armenia is imprisoned for several years in Cairo, until a ransom is paid by King John I of Castile. April 21 – Mujahid Shah succeeds his father, Mohammed Shah I, as ruler of the Bahmani Sultanate in the Deccan Plateau of southern India. June 18 – The future King John I of Castile marries Eleanor of Aragon.

Year 1420 ( MCDXX ) was a leap year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Thursday ( link will display a list of the leap years ).It used to be observed on 25 March.It was one of the few countries that observed leap years in all of their year, unlike most European countries, where the first four days of the month are considered a leap day because they are considered to be the same day. It is also the only country in which the leap year year ends on a Monday (MCD) in leap years (link).

Latin is a Latin-based writing system that is based on the Roman alphabet and the Latin word order. It was developed from Old Latin, a cursive script used in Italy between the 3rd century BC, and the 4th century.

Year 1184 (MCLXXXIV) was a leap year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  May 20 – Diet of Pentecost: Emperor Frederick I (Barbarossa) organises a conference in Mainz. During the diet Frederick negotiates with Henry the Lion about an anti-French alliance with England. June 15 – Battle of Fimreite: King Sverre of Norway defeats and kills his rival, Magnus V (Erlingsson) near Fimreite. Sverre takes the throne and becomes sole ruler of Norway (until 1202).

DeCSS is one of the first free computer programs capable of decrypting content on a commercially produced DVD video disc.It is the successor to DeCSS, the previous free DVD decryption program. Edward Snowden (, born 28 July 1987) is a US intelligence contractor, currently in Russia under asylum, who has leaked classified NSA documents since 2013. Born in Honolulu, Washington, Snowden is a former technical assistant for the CIA's Technical Services Division.Early life and educationEarly lifeIn 1996, Snowden was hired by Dell Inc as a computer technician, where he worked until 2001.

Gerard Pieter Hendrik van Velde ( born 30 November 1971 ) is a Dutch retired speed skater who specialised in free skating.Vincent van Gogh, a painter, is referred to as a master of the medium of oil painting. He was born to a wealthy merchant from Antwerp, who died when Vincent was only a child. He spent his early years with his father in Antwerp. He was sent to school in the Hague, and went to art school, where he developed his own style. Van Gogh became the most famous artist in the world after his death.

Adrian of Nicomedia ( also known as Hadrian ) or Saint Adrian ( , died 4 March 306 ) was a Christian martyr who was burned at the stake by the Roman emperor Constantine I in AD 313. Adrian was bishop of the Roman see of Ravenna, one of the largest Roman cities and one of the largest cities in Italy at the time, and he was a leading opponent of Justinian I, father of the Byzantine emperor Justinian I (ruled 313–337).Adrian was born in Rome in the Western Roman Empire, but his parents are known only from the inscription to his tomb in Ravenna.

Year 1392 ( MCCCXCII ) was a leap year starting on Monday ( link will display full calendar ) of Year 1392. The French Revolution was a major event in the history of Europe and the world. It was caused by the failure of the French monarchy to deliver on its responsibilities to the revolution's goals, and the radical reforms of French society in the years that followed. In particular, it saw the overthrow of Louis XVI as the constitutional head of state, and the establishment of republicanism in France as a new political ideology.

Year 1301 (MCCCI) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January 14 – The death of Andrew III of Hungary ends the Árpád Dynasty in Hungary, resulting in a power struggle between Wenceslaus III of Bohemia, Otto III, Duke of Bavaria, and Charles Robert of Naples. February 7 – Edward of Caernarvon (later King Edward II of England) becomes the first Prince of Wales. March 3 – Emperor Go-Nijō succeeds Emperor Go-Fushimi on the throne of Japan.

Three bobsleigh events were competed at the 2002 Winter Olympics , at Utah Olympic Park . The competition took place between February 27 and February 30, 2002. The first three events were run by the United States , the second three were run by Canada , and the third three were run by Sweden. The top two finishers in each race would then face off in the final event, a four-person sled race, run in a relay by all three competitors from the other two bobsleigh events. Mariner 2 ( Mariner-Venus 1962 ) , an American space probe to Venus , was the first robotic space probe to enter orbit around Venus since Mariner 4 in 1965. It was the first American probe to orbit Venus since Mariner 3 in 1958.The probe had a three-year prime mission, including an extended mission to study the atmosphere of Venus.In April 1962, Mariner 6 was launched from Cape Kennedy and arrived in Venus orbit in December 1962. Mariner 7 reached Venus orbit in March 1964 and was lost. Mariner 8 was launched from Cape Kennedy in August 1965 and landed successfully in January 1966.

Events January–June January 23 – The Triple Alliance of 1668 is formed between England , Sweden and the United Provinces of the Netherlands after a French victory over the Habsburg forces in the First Battle of Austerlitz. The English Civil War, also referred to as the Anglo-Dutch Wars  or the Anglo-Dutch Wars, is a war between England and various parts of Europe during the 17th century. It began when Charles I was proclaimed king of England on June 9, 1625 and ended with his abdication on October 31, 1649, following the Glorious Revolution of 1688.

Hide-and-seek is a popular children's game in which at least two players (usually at least three) conceal themselves in a set environment, to be found by one or more seekers. The game is played by one chosen player (designated as being "it") counting to a predetermined number with eyes closed while the other players hide. After reaching this number, the player who is "it" calls "Ready or not, here I come!" or "Coming, ready or not!" and then attempts to locate all concealed players.The game can end in one of several ways.

Year 998 ( CMXCVIII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Sunday (link will display the complete calendar) in the Julian calendar system. It was the fifth of twelve Julian years. Carmelites (,  ,  , ) are an Early Christian monastic order, founded in the 4th century C.E. by the apostle Paul. Carmel was one of the twelve apostles who founded the new religion known as Christianity during his missionary journey through the region of Cappadocia, now part of southern Turkey. Carmelites lived as ascetics in monasteries and lived a cloistered existence.

Year 1379 ( MCCCLXXIX ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) in Western Europe and on Monday ( link will display the English-language Gregorian calendar) in eastern Europe. It was the twelfth year of the Julian calendar and the seventh year in the Roman civil calendar. The name MCCCLXXIX is a corruption of the Latin "magnus ecclesiae comitatis" (Latin for "of the episcopal court of the Catholic church"), from the Latin "mercem comitatis" (literally "of the city of Rome"), the Latin name of the Basilica of Saint Peter in Rome.

Otto III (June/July 980 – 23 January 1002) was Holy Roman Emperor from 996 until his early death in 1002. A member of the Ottonian dynasty, Otto III was the only son of the Emperor Otto II and his wife Theophanu.Otto III was crowned as King of Germany in 983 at the age of three, shortly after his father's death in Southern Italy while campaigning against the Byzantine Empire and the Emirate of Sicily. Though the nominal ruler of Germany, Otto III's minor status ensured his various regents held power over the Empire.

Year 1527 (MDXXVII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June January 1 – Croatian nobles elect Ferdinand I of Austria as King of Croatia in the Parliament on Cetin. January 5 – Felix Manz, co-founder of the Swiss Anabaptists, is drowned in the Limmat in Zürich by the Zürich Reformed state church. March 17 – Battle of Khanwa: Babur defeats Rajput ruler Rana Sanga. This and two other major Moghul victories lead to their domination of northern India. Dhaulpur fort is taken by Babur.

Year 1490 ( MCDXC ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) and continuing until 30 December 1490, when it was superseded by the Gregorian calendar. This was not a new calendar, having been introduced in 1382 as the first of more than a dozen such calendars introduced in the 13th and 14th centuries by different monarchs, including Edward III of England, Edward IV of England, and Charles I of France. It replaced the Roman Julian calendar, which was introduced in 47 BC and had a length of 365 days.

Events January–June February 1 – Queen Elizabeth I of England signs the death warrant of her cousin Mary , Queen of Scots, for the execution of Edward Seymour, Earl of Hertford in 1597. The Civil Service  is the branch of government responsible for administering the Government of the United Kingdom, which was created as a constitutional monarchy on 13 March 1946 by the Civil Registration (Scotland) Act 1947, and which is now headed by the Cabinet Office and the Department for Culture, Media and Sport. There are a number of departments of government responsible for the delivery of government policy.

Year 1171 (MCLXXI) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  March 12 – Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos) orders the arrest of all Venetians in his empire, and seizes their ships and goods. In September, Doge Vitale II Michiel leads a Venetian fleet (120 ships) against the Byzantines, conquering the cities of Trogir and Dubrovnik. But the plague takes a heavy toll among the fleet's crewmen; half the ships have to be burned to keep them from falling into enemy hands.

The Tandy 1000 is the first in a line of IBM PC compatible home computer systems produced by the Tandy Corporation from 1966 to 1997. The 1000 system was marketed by IBM as an alternative to competing systems like the Apple Macintosh and the Commodore PET, but is also used by a number of hobbyists. A telecommunication system is any electronic system that allows users to interact over a communication channel with other users, either locally or over the internet. Telecommunication systems often involve multiple endpoints that are separated by an internet-like network.The term telecommunication is sometimes used synonymously with computer network.HistoryTelecommunication networks first emerged in the early 19th century.

Norwich is a town in Windsor County , in the U.S. state of Vermont . The population was 3,612 at the 2010 U.S. census, the largest town in the region. Norwich has a downtown area of 4.3 acres, with a mix of residential, office, and commercial property, as well as a public park. It has a population density of . Norwich is on the northern shore of Lake Champlain, bordering the Canadian province of New Brunswick, and lies on the New York border.The town has a downtown shopping district on East Main Street, and a historic district along Main Street.

Dub mac Maíl Coluim (Modern Gaelic: Dubh mac Mhaoil Chaluim, ), sometimes anglicised as Duff MacMalcolm, called Dén, "the Vehement" and, "the Black" (born c. 928 – died 967) was king of Alba. He was son of Malcolm I and succeeded to the throne when Indulf was killed in 962.While later chroniclers such as John of Fordun supplied a great deal of information on Dub's life and reign, and Hector Boece in his 'The history and chronicles of Scotland' tell tales of witchcraft and treason, almost all of them are rejected by modern historians.

Business is the activity of making one 's living or making money by producing or buying and selling products (often for profit). It often involves the acquisition, use or transfer of money. The term "business" is often used as shorthand for all business activities, regardless of the nature of the goods or services traded.The definition of business activities may vary, and may also vary between different sectors of the economy and across countries. The Canadian Armed Forces (CAF) (or "the CAF" to its members) is an armed force of Canada's federal Parliament.

Year 1318 ( MCCCXVIII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) with an extra day ( MCCCXIX ) each year, which is usually omitted. John Calvin was a Calvinist theologian and theologian, an influential leader in Protestantism, who was the first Grand Master of the Scottish Calvinist Order. A theologian, theologian, and theologian, Calvin was the founder of the Geneva Reformed Church in Geneva (1545–1602). Early life and educationJohn Milton describes Calvin as "a very little man of great stature", and in 1631 he is described as having a "pale complexion".

Year 1150 ( MCL ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Thursday at midnight. MCL was the second-oldest regular year, with the year that began 1 April 1110, and ending 1 July 1182.The name MCL is a variant of Latin malleus , or "little hand" (from malus, "hand"), a reference to the short, sharp fingers of the human hand. In ancient Roman law, malleus was used to indicate a child's right of inheritance.

Year 1439 ( MCDXXXIX ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending either on the Wednesday before the following Wednesday or on the Monday after the following Monday. It was also called the "common year" and the "common year of Christ", and was the only year in which the pope was infallible. It was the year in which the Reformation split the Western Church and split the Western Church, with the Catholic and Eastern branches splitting into Eastern and Western rites on 15 February 1521.

February – Muhammad bin Tughluq succeeds his father Ghiyath al-Din Tughluq, as Sultan of Delhi. July – War of the Bucket breaks out: Modena makes incursions into the territory of Bologna. Year 1377 (MCCCLXXVII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January – Battle of Đồ Bàn: Trần Duệ Tông, Trần dynasty Emperor of Đại Việt (Vietnam), is killed. Influenced by John of Gaunt, 1st Duke of Lancaster, it undoes the work done by the Good Parliament, the previous year, to reduce corruption in the Royal Council.

Year 1363 ( MCCCLXIII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) in 1363. This year was the third to end in 1364, the year after 1361 and the year after 1365. The United Kingdom is a sovereign state in Western Europe and a member of the Commonwealth. It is one of the United Nations's five founding members and one of only four member states of the European Union as of the 2016 United Nations General Assembly. It is the largest, second-largest economy in the United Kingdom, and the third-largest in the European Union.

Tropical Storm Karen was a system that brought record-breaking rainfall and flooding to southeastern Pennsylvania and other Mid-Atlantic states in October 2013. The twelfth tropical cyclone and eleventh named storm of the well below-average 2013 Atlantic hurricane season, Karen originated from a tropical wave that departed from the west coast of Africa on September 16. After passing south of Jamaica and the Cayman Islands, the storm became a tropical cyclone to the northeast of the Yucatán Peninsula. The storm peaked shortly afterward, with 1-minute sustained winds of 65 mph (100 km/h).

Spins are an element in figure skating in which the skater rotates, centered on a single point on the ice, while holding one or more body positions. Blum Blum Shub ( B.B.S . ) is a pseudorandom number generator proposed in 1986 by Lenore Blum , Manuel Blum , and David Goldberg . In physics , optical depth or optical thickness is the natural logarithm of the ratio of incident to transmitted radiant power at a given location on an illuminated surface. This ratio can be expressed in either metric or American system units. For metric units, optical thickness can be expressed in terms of the focal length, the wavelength (or the reciprocal of the wavelength) and the number of reflected photons per unit area. For an object of known volume, a given optical thickness would be equal to its area (the reciprocal of its volume in metric units).

In the Swedish calendar it began as a leap year starting on Monday and remained so until Thursday, February 29. Sweden finally made the switch from the Julian to the Gregorian calendar in 1753. Dyson's eternal intelligence concept (the Dyson Scenario), proposed by Freeman Dyson in 1979, proposes a means by which an immortal society of intelligent beings in an open universe may escape the prospect of the heat death of the universe by extending subjective time to infinity even though expending only a finite amount of energy.Bremermann's limit can be invoked to deduce that the amount of time to perform a computation on 1 bit is inversely proportional to the change in energy in the system. As a result, the amount of computations that can be performed grows over time.

Arthrobacter ( from the Greek , `` jointed small stick ” ) is a genus of bacteria that is commonly found in both fresh and saltwater. Margaret ( , ; March or April 1283 – September 1290 ) , known as the Maid of Norway , was Queen and regent of Norway for the last thirty years of her life, becoming a patron saint of Denmark and Denmark's patron saint.Born into a prominent Norwegian family, she inherited the royal power after her older brother died. As a child she was a popular court jester, and eventually became an accomplished court singer and dancer. At the age of twenty, she was appointed to the governorship of Bergen in southern Norway.

In computational complexity theory , PSPACE is the set of all decision problems that can be solved by a Turing machine. The decision problem is an instance of a computational problem called a Turing problem. PSPACE contains all problems of the class of computational problems called computational complexity theory. PSPACE was originally defined as the smallest number of bits that can be represented in an addressable set, which is the number of possible values of a variable, such as a number, a character, etc. Petrochemical energy is the energy used in the production, refining and distribution of petroleum.

A compass is a device that shows the cardinal directions used for navigation and geographic orientation. It commonly consists of a magnetized needle or other element, such as a compass card or compass rose, which can pivot to align itself with magnetic north. Other methods may be used, including gyroscopes, magnetometers, and GPS receivers.Compasses often show angles in degrees: north corresponds to 0°, and the angles increase clockwise, so east is 90°, south is 180°, and west is 270°. These numbers allow the compass to show azimuths or bearings which are commonly stated in degrees.

The Cape Cod Canal is an artificial waterway in the U.S. state of Massachusetts connecting Cape Cod Bay in the northeast with Martha's Vineyard in the northwest. The Cape Cod Canal, named after the historic town that was the first terminus, was built in the 1840s and 1850s as a transportation infrastructure for the fur trade between Cape Cod Harbor and Martha's Vineyard. The canal connects the Bay with the Gulf of Massachusetts in about 20 miles (32.5 kilometers) at a width of approximately 2.5 miles (3 kilometers). The Canal has been maintained and expanded over the years to serve as a navigable waterway.

Divorce (also known as dissolution of marriage) is the process of terminating a marriage or marital union. Divorce usually entails the canceling or reorganizing of the legal duties and responsibilities of marriage, thus dissolving the bonds of matrimony between a married couple under the rule of law of the particular country or state. Divorce laws vary considerably around the world, but in most countries, divorce requires the sanction of a court or other authority in a legal process, which may involve issues of distribution of property, child custody, alimony (spousal support), child visitation / access, parenting time, child support, and division of debt.

The governor of Montana is the head of government of Montana and the commander-in-chief of the state's military forces. The governor has a duty to enforce state laws, the power to either approve or veto bills passed by the Montana State Legislature, to convene the legislature at any time, and to grant pardons and reprieves.The current Montana Constitution, ratified in 1972, calls for a 4-year term for the governor, commencing on the first Monday in January following an election. The governor is term-limited to 8 years in any 16-year period. The constitution provides for the election of a lieutenant governor for the same term as the governor.

The Roman conquest of Britain was a process that consisted of the conquest of territory located on the island of Britain by occupying Roman forces. It began in AD 43 under Emperor Claudius, and was largely completed by 87 when the Stanegate was established.The Roman army was generally recruited in Italia, Hispania, and Gaul. To control the English Channel they used the newly formed fleet.The Romans under their general Aulus Plautius first forced their way inland in several battles against British tribes, including the Battle of the Medway, the Battle of the Thames, and in later years Caratacus's last battle against Caratacus and the Roman conquest of Anglesey.

Botulism is a rare and potentially fatal illness caused by a toxin produced by the bacterium Clostridium botulinum. The disease begins with weakness, blurred vision, feeling tired, and trouble speaking. This may then be followed by weakness of the arms, chest muscles, and legs. Vomiting, swelling of the abdomen, and diarrhea may also occur. The disease does not usually affect consciousness or cause a fever.Botulism can be spread in several ways. The bacterial spores which cause it are common in both soil and water. They produce the botulinum toxin when exposed to low oxygen levels and certain temperatures.

In the performing arts, a scenario (, ; from Italian: "that which is pinned to the scenery", ) is a synoptical collage of an event or series of actions and events. In the commedia dell'arte it was an outline of entrances, exits, and action describing the plot of a play, and was literally pinned to the back of the scenery. It is also known as canovaccio  or "that which is pinned to the canvas" of which the scenery was constructed.Surviving scenarios from the Renaissance contain little other than character names, brief descriptions of action, and references to specific lazzi with no further explanation.

Year 1373 ( MCCCLXXIII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) that is the last Sunday of July in the Gregorian calendar. The year will end with Saturday, and the following Monday will start the following year. It is the final year before the year 1, the year of the Incarnation.The year 1374 (MCCCLXXV) was not a common year at the time, instead starting on Friday and concluding with Sunday morning. This was the only year that was not the final year before the Year 1.

Year 1378 ( MCCCLXXVIII ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Monday ( link will open to the current month). The year is a direct descendant of the Julian calendar. The calendar year varies from day to day from 1 January, 1 December, 5 January, 8 January, 9 January, 11 January, 12 January, 13 January, 15 January, 21 January, 22 January and 28 January. The current year's first day is 21 February, the last day is 29 February.

Events January–June January 10 – The Royal African Company is granted a Royal Charter by Charles II of England . Kabila (, , ) is the Democratic Republic of the Congo's President since 2003, and its longest-serving president (since 1993). Kabila is widely regarded as one of the most corrupt persons in Africa. Born into one of the largest mining families in Eastern DRC, he was educated at university in Belgium. The kibbutz was an Israeli voluntary association, founded in 1946, whose members used the common agricultural and communal land for mutual benefit, including mutual cultivation and production.

Symbiosis (from Greek , , "living together", from , , "together", and , bíōsis, "living") is any type of a close and long-term biological interaction between two different biological organisms, be it mutualistic, commensalistic, or parasitic. The organisms, each termed a symbiont, must be of different species. In 1879, Heinrich Anton de Bary defined it as "the living together of unlike organisms". The term was subject to a century-long debate about whether it should specifically denote mutualism, as in lichens.

Eric Arthur Heiden ( born June 14 , 1958 ) is an American physician and a former long track speed skater. He has held a degree in biology and graduated from the University of Wisconsin-Madison. He is the oldest active male skater, and the only person to have won both the World and Olympic titles. He has competed in over 100 international races.LifeHeiden was born near Milwaukee, Wisconsin, the eighth of nine children. In 1971, he and his brothers and sister left their home to live with a foster mother in California. Heiden went to college and earned a bachelor's degree in biology.

Casimir IV ( in full Casimir IV Andrew Jagiellon ; ; Lithuanian : ; 30 November 1427 – 7 June 1503) was King of Prussia from 1462 until his death in 1518, during which time he was also Prince-elector of Poland.A descendant of the Visigoth line of Germanic warriors, he was born in the city of Pulský, in present-day Belarus. As a result of his parentage, he was regarded by the early 15th century Polish state as the next in line to become the king. Klaus I (,  or ) was a German emperor from 1469 to 1483.

The Hubble Space Telescope ( often referred to as HST or Hubble ) is a space telescope that was launched into orbit by NASA's Space Shuttle Columbia on November 17, 1990. It was later deployed on March 27, 1992, by a Russian Soyuz launch vehicle. The observatory is part of the NASA Space Telescope Imaging Spectrograph (STIS) instrument suite. The Hubble Space Telescope or simply Hubble, is the successor to the Chandra X-ray Observatory, and the successor to the NASA's Hubble Space Telescope, which was launched in 1990.It is one of the world's largest telescopes.

GNU Privacy Guard (GnuPG or GPG) is a free-software replacement for Symantec's PGP cryptographic software suite. The software is compliant with RFC 4880, the IETF standards-track specification of OpenPGP. Modern versions of PGP are interoperable with GnuPG and other OpenPGP-compliant systems.GnuPG is part of the GNU Project and received major funding from the German government in 1999.Overview GnuPG is a hybrid-encryption software program because it uses a combination of conventional symmetric-key cryptography for speed, and public-key cryptography for ease of secure key exchange, typically by using the recipient's public key to encrypt a session key which is used only once.

Andorra , officially the Principality of Andorra , also called the Principality of the Valleys of Andorra < ref > and known formally as the Kingdom of Andorra or the Principality of Valleys Andorra (also known as the Valley of Andorra), is a sovereign Spanish region within the autonomous principality of the Andorra. Located in the Iberian peninsula of the Mediterranean, it is bounded on the east by Spain, on the south and west by France, and on the north and northwest by Italy.It has a population estimated at approximately 2.9 million people, of which half live in Barcelona, the capital.

Ice hockey at the 2002 Winter Olympics was held at the E Center in West Valley City and Peaks Ice Arena in Provo, Utah. The men's and women's tournaments were won by Canada, who defeated the host United States in both finals.Medal summaryMedal tableMedalistsMen's tournamentQualifyingThe final standings at the end of the 1999 IIHF World Championship were used to determine the path to the Olympic tournament. The top six places were given direct entry to the first round, places seven and eight were given direct entry to the preliminary round, and all other participants were seeded in qualifying tournaments to fill the remaining six spots.

Year 1043 (MXLIII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Emperor Constantine IX Monomachos sends a Byzantine expeditionary force to the Balkans against the rebellious George Maniakes, governor of the Catepanate of Italy. The two armies meet near Thessaloniki in northern Greece. The rebel army – better organized, seasoned and with superior leadership – fights initially successful, but Maniakes is killed by an arrow at the moment of his triumph. After this, his army is routed.

Year 1532 (MDXXXII) was a leap year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 22 – São Vicente is established as the first permanent Portuguese settlement in Brazil. March 18 – The English Parliament bans payment by the English Church to Rome. April – Battle of Quipaipan in Peru: Atahualpa wins the civil war in the Inca Empire, defeating his brother Huáscar. May 13 – Francisco Pizarro lands on the northern coast of Peru. May 16 – Sir Thomas More resigns as Lord Chancellor of England.

Jacques René Chirac (, , ; 29 November 193226 September 2019) was a French politician who served as President of France from 1995 to 2007. Chirac was previously Prime Minister of France from 1974 to 1976 and from 1986 to 1988, as well as Mayor of Paris from 1977 to 1995.After attending the École nationale d'administration, Chirac began his career as a high-level civil servant, entering politics shortly thereafter. Chirac occupied various senior positions, including Minister of Agriculture and Minister of the Interior. In 1981 and 1988, he unsuccessfully ran for President as the standard-bearer for the conservative Gaullist party Rally for the Republic.

Events January–March January 10 – England and the Dutch Republic sign a mutual defense treaty in order to fight against French aggression. May 1 – England and the Netherlands officially declare war on France. September 2 – England and the Netherlands formally begin fighting France at a battle of Eymondwood. September 20 – Napoleon III of the French Empire abdicates the throne to his brother Joseph. Folk-art is the artistic expression of an identifiable community or culture as well as the expression of personal and communal feelings, ideas and aspirations, often expressed through folk art.

Year 1231 (MCCXXXI) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Emperor Frederick II promulgates the Constitutions of Melfi (Liber Augustalis), a collection of laws for Sicily, as well as the edict of Salerno, regulating the exercise of medicine and separating the professions of physician and apothecary, and requiring medical schools to practice dissection. Castillan forces under King Ferdinand III (the Saint) re-conquer the city of Quesada. Battle of Jerez: Ferdinand III defeats Emir Ibn Hud of the Taifa of Murcia.

Eleusine coracana , or finger millet , also known as ragi in India , kodo in Nepal , is an annual seed crop cultivated for its edible seeds, which are cooked and eaten in the traditional Nepali way. It is native to Central and South Asia, in particular Afghanistan and the Punjab region of Pakistan. It has also been cultivated as a cash crop for its seeds in many parts of Nepal, such as in the Himalayan districts of Jhapa, Dang and Bikaner. It has become an important source of food for thousands of poor families in Nepal, as well as an important food staple for Nepalis in Pakistan.

Juggling is a physical skill , performed by a juggler , involving the manipulation of objects for recreation , entertainment or profit. In juggling , the object that is being juggled is often referred to as a "stunner" and the juggler performing the juggling is often referred to as "the master".A juggler can use his arms to hold an object, while placing his feet on one side of the object and his elbows on the other, or he can use his hands while holding the object.A juggler may also use the ball or other objects to catch and hold the other object.

Year 1032 (MXXXII) was a leap year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Emperor Romanos III (Argyros) sends a Byzantine expeditionary army under General Michael Protospatharios, which includes Western auxiliaries and elite troops of Asia Minor, to reinforce the Byzantine position in Calabria (Southern Italy). Europe  September 6 – King Rudolph III dies without any heirs. He bequeaths his entire dominions to Emperor Conrad II (the Elder), dispatching to him the Holy Lance and ring of St. Maurice, symbols of Burgundian investiture.

Year 1464 ( MCDLXIV ) was a leap year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar )
The International Date Line ( ILD ), commonly referred to as the date line of the Earth, is a line of constant length that defines the difference between two dates. It was first calculated in the late 19th century by Pierre Jules Janssen, a French astronomer. It first appears on U.S. currency in 1870. The International Geophysical Year (IGY) or IGY is the name given to the year that the Earth completes a geologic year.

Wellfleet is a town in Barnstable County, Massachusetts, United States, and is located halfway between the "tip" and "elbow" of Cape Cod. The town had a population of 3,566 at the 2020 census, which swells nearly sixfold during the summer. A total of 70% of the town's land area is under protection, and nearly half of it is part of the Cape Cod National Seashore. Wellfleet is famous for its oysters, which are celebrated in the annual October Wellfleet OysterFest.History The area was originally settled by Europeans in the 1650s as Billingsgate (after the famous fish market in East London).

Freestyle skiing is a  skiing discipline comprising aerials, moguls, cross, half-pipe, slopestyle and big air as part of the Winter Olympics. It can consist of a skier performing aerial flips and spins and can include skiers sliding rails and boxes on their skis. Known as "hot-dogging" in the early 1970s, it is also commonly referred to as freeskiing, jibbing, as well as many other names, around the world.History Ski acrobatics have been practiced since the 1930s/1940s. Aerial skiing was popularized in the 1950s by Olympic gold medalist Stein Eriksen. Early US competitions were held in the mid-1960s.

Year 1384 (MCCCLXXXIV) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  May – September 3 – Siege of Lisbon by the Castilian army, during the 1383–85 Crisis in Portugal. August 16 – The Hongwu Emperor of Ming China hears a case of a couple who tore paper money notes, while fighting over them. Under the law, this is considered to be destroying stamped government documents, which is to be punished by a caning with a bamboo rod of 100 strokes. However, the Emperor decides to pardon them, on the grounds that it was unintentional.

English Renaissance theatre , also known as Renaissance English theatre and Elizabethan theatre , refers to the theatre of England during the sixteenth century. The name derives from the reign of Henry VIII, who ordered the execution of most of the plays that were being played in the Elizabethan era, but allowed a few plays to be revived. The theatre of Henry VIII has frequently been referred to as the Elizabethan theatre, but it is now known as the Jacobean theatre due to the reign of Queen Elizabeth I (1558–1603), who abolished most of the ancient plays in favor of works written during Elizabeth's lifetime.

Wenceslaus IV ( also Wenceslas ; ; , nicknamed `` the Idle '' ; 26 February 136116 August 1419 ) was the fourth Holy Roman Emperor of the Holy Roman Empire from 13 February 1311 to 1419 in the name of Charles I. ( ) was the ruler of Saxony at the time of its partition in 1348.
