He came to power in the years before his father's assassination in 1350 and reigned until his death in 1353, at which point his son and heir, Otto I, succeeded him as Regent of the Empire.Early lifeWenceslaus was born at Worms, then in present-day Germany.

Year 1327 (MCCCXXVII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 25 – The 14-year-old Edward III is proclaimed King of England, after his mother Isabella has engineered the abdication of his imprisoned father Edward II of England, on January 20, effective January 25. Isabella and her lover Roger Mortimer rule as regents (the coronation takes place February 1). April 6 (Good Friday) – Tuscan writer Petrarch sees a woman he names Laura in the church of Sainte-Claire d'Avignon, which awakes in him a lasting passion.

Year 1043 ( MXLIII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) and having 30 days and 2 hours. The Magna Carta , or Great Charter , is a charter of the English common law that was signed by King John in 1215, in a ceremony at Runnymede, near Windsor, England. The document is commonly considered to be the first modern constitution and a landmark in the history of English liberties. It established many fundamental rights, including freedom from torture and illegal detention, free speech and freedom from arbitrary arrest or detention.

Lillian Evelyn Gilbreth ( Moller; May 24, 1878 – January 2, 1972) was an American psychologist, industrial engineer, consultant, and educator who was an early pioneer in applying psychology to time-and-motion studies. She was described in the 1940s as "a genius in the art of living." Gilbreth, one of the first female engineers to earn a Ph.D., is considered to be the first industrial/organizational psychologist. She and her husband, Frank Bunker Gilbreth, were efficiency experts who contributed to the study of industrial engineering, especially in the areas of motion study and human factors.

Year 1235 ( MCCXXXV ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Saturday.The year 1235 began on Monday, August 8, 1235, with a leap day and ended on Saturday, September 2, 1235, a day after Easter Sunday.The 1235 leap year was the first leap year since the Gregorian reform in 1652, a reform that was the impetus for the adoption by the United States Congress of the Gregorian calendar by act of July 27, 1862. This article is about a fictional character, group, organization or nation.

Lillian Evelyn Gilbreth ( Moller ; May 24 , 1878 – January 2 , 1972 ) was an American psychologist who specialized in the assessment of mental illness.Gilbreth is the only woman ever to hold the post of president of the American Psychological Association.Gilbreth was a psychologist who received her PhD in psychology at the University of Wisconsin–Madison and spent her postdoctoral work and teaching at Harvard University.Gilbreth later taught at Columbia University, the College of Physicians and Surgeons of Philadelphia, and the University of Pennsylvania before moving to New York University where she taught at both New York Medical College and NYU School of Medicine.

A trisomy is a type of polysomy in which there are three instances of a particular chromosome , instead of one. A trisomy will cause one of the cells in a cell of the affected person to become abnormal. The Thrasher was a small, one-man helicopter owned by Dr. John Frederick Thrasher of the United States Air Force in the late 1950s and 1960s. Thrasher built it as a personal aircraft, and he flew it during the Korean War, the Vietnam War, the Iran-Iraq war, and during the 1991 Persian Gulf War. Thrasher used it primarily for his personal aerial reconnaissance duties.

EventsJanuary–March  January 20 – The Parliament of England (under Tory dominance) limits the size of the country's standing army to 7,000 'native born' men; hence, King William III's Dutch Blue Guards cannot serve in the line. By an Act of February 1, it also requires disbandment of foreign troops in Ireland. January 26 – The Republic of Venice, Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth and Holy Roman Empire sign the Treaty of Karlowitz with the Ottoman Empire, marking an end to the major phase of the Ottoman–Habsburg wars, including the Morean War between Venice and the Ottomans.

Year 1569 ( MDLXIX ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) that was used in most countries, except for England and Ireland, and some colonies and dependencies. The calendar was originally used for civil use and to determine the dates of weddings, baptisms, and funerals, to set the starting date and the end date of religious holidays, and to set the calendar for common events such as fairs, fairs and market days, as well as important events such as the coronation of a king or regent, elections of a president of parliament, and civil war.

Year 1433 ( MCDXXXIII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Julian calendar. It was celebrated by the Western Christian Church on 2 May, in its Easter celebrations and by the Eastern Orthodox churches on 1 May. It was also the first year in which the Feast of the Annunciation was celebrated, and was celebrated as such in Western churches, and as the beginning of Lent in Eastern churches.The first written records of February 1433 date from 1494 and are from Henry II's chronicle.

Dengue fever is a mosquito-borne tropical disease caused by the dengue virus . Symptoms typically begin three to fourteen days after the bite of a dengue-carrying mosquito, with the onset typically occurring one to three weeks after exposure. Fever, a rash, joint and muscle pain, and nausea are typically the first signs of infection, and a rash often develops a week or more following the fever. Symptoms typically last four to fourteen days and resolve on their own. The disease can also cause a condition called Guillian-Barre syndrome, in which the nervous system fails, causing confusion, paralysis, and eventually death.

Optical rotation , also known as polarization rotation or circular birefringence , is the rotation of the orientation of the light source, or the light wave, of an incident light source, that is, the direction of the wave's incident polarization. This includes the polarization of a light beam at the point of its propagation, and also the polarization of the wavefront of the light wave as a whole.Polarization rotations arise when an object with polarizing properties passes a point where its orientation has changed, such as in a mirror, lens, or beam splitter.

Year 1298 ( MCCXCVIII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Gregorian system of civil and calendar years.On 1 February 1299, the new year was celebrated by the Pope, who called upon the whole world to observe the day. The Gregorian calendar was formally adopted as the international civil calendar on 12 November 1366 by Pope John XXII. A microprocessor, also known as a microprocessor-integrated circuit (MIC), is an electronic processor used in digital applications. Microprocessors consist of a central processing unit (CPU) and a memory subsystem.

A lever ( or ) is a simple machine consisting of a beam or rigid rod pivoted at a fixed position. It is typically mounted on a wall, table, or pedestal. It is used as a lifting device to carry objects such as boxes.History The lever (from Old French, ligare, from Latin lignum, 'leaf') is a Greek and Roman architectural term for a fixed, horizontal support for a pillar. It can be found throughout ancient architecture and has been referred to both as a 'pillar' or 'structure' and as 'the leaf'.Historically, ladders were often attached to doors or windows.

Year 1059 ( MLIX ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) on the Gregorian calendar. It was the third in the Common Era, the eleventh month of the Islamic calendar, and it was also known as the "day of the Qur'an". It was also the first Muslim lunar month in which a month was completely absent. Lysistrata ( ) is a Greek playwright of the fifth century BCE. She is one of the three major figures in the Odyssey, with Menelaus and Achilles. Her name is derived from a river in modern-day Turkey.

Year 1151 ( MCLI ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) or Sunday.Mondays were the traditional starting point of the Julian calendar, although this was changed by the Gregorian calendar in 1452 and in 1652 the Julian calendar was modified to make it compatible with the Gregorian calendars.It was replaced in 1752 and 1759. The medieval calendar is a set of Roman numerals (the Iliad and The Odyssey use it as a base, for example) that evolved through the Middle Ages into a unified calendar for use in Western Europe and the rest of Europe.

Events  January–June  January – Six months into King Philip's War, Metacomet (King Philip), leader of the Algonquian tribe known as the Wampanoag, travels westward to the Mohawk nation, seeking an alliance with the Mohawks against the English colonists of New England; his efforts in creating such an alliance are a failure. January 29 – Feodor III becomes Tsar of Russia. January 31 – University of San Carlos of Guatemala, the oldest institution of higher education in Central America, was founded. February 10 – After the Nipmuc tribe attacks Lancaster, Massachusetts, colonist Mary Rowlandson is taken captive, and lives with the Indians until May.

In the Swedish calendar it was a common year starting on Monday , one day ahead of the Julian and Gregorian calendars and on the  before  the Gregorian calendar, but after March 29 of the year. In the United States it begins on Monday, March 22 of the calendar year. The beginning of the year was commonly celebrated on March 21 and 22 in Europe. The Gregorian calendar was widely adopted by many European countries, including Sweden, France, the Netherlands, Germany, Spain, Italy, Portugal, and Greece.

.Year 1134 ( MCXXXIV ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) in England and ending on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ). Elvis Presley  (born Vernon Presley on December 22, 1935)  is an American musician and actor, singer-songwriter, actor, film producer and musician. He is a member of the rock and roll group The Band , which he formed in 1959. He rose to national fame as a teenager with his 1961 debut single "Hound Dog" and later released his debut LP, Memphis Blues, in 1966, which went double platinum.

Events January–December February – The Republic of Venice annexes the seigniory of Ravenna , ending the da Polenta Dynasty . El Salvador is a sovereign country in Central America. It has a land area  and a population of  and a land area  and a population of  since independence from Spain in 1821. It has a population density  of. The government is headed by the President of the Republic, Salvador Sánchez Cerén, since March 2007. El Salvador is divided into ten regions and one federal district, which also includes the island of San Salvador and parts of Guatemala.El Salvador has two main languages - Spanish and the local  language.

Renate Titzia Groenewold ( born 8 October 1976 ) is a Dutch former long track speed skater and road bicycle racer. Groenewold was the Dutch national long-track speed skater team's first woman to compete at the world championships, the world championships on the world's most demanding course. She won the Dutch national long-track team competition at the 2000 Olympic Games. The Ganges is one of the world's oldest rivers. It is the second largest river system in the world and the longest. It is the longest river in the Subcontinent, India, flowing from Punjab through Gujarat to the Arabian Sea.

Year 1198 (MCXCVIII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place The volcano was formed around 4000 years ago and last erupted in 1198 during a phreatic eruption - a powerful steam eruption caused by groundwater interacting with magma. Europe  March 8 – Philip of Swabia, son of the late Emperor Frederick I, is elected "King of Germany" by his supporters at Mühlhausen in Thuringia. Archbishop Adolf of Cologne elects Otto of Brunswick, son of Henry the Lion, as Philip's rival.

DeCSS is one of the first free computer programs capable of decrypting content on a commercially produced DVD video disc. Before the release of DeCSS, open source operating systems (such as BSD and Linux) could not play encrypted video DVDs.DeCSS's development was done without a license from the DVD Copy Control Association (CCA), the organization responsible for DVD copy protection—namely, the Content Scramble System (CSS) used by commercial DVD publishers. The release of DeCSS resulted in a Norwegian criminal trial and subsequent acquittal of one of the authors of DeCSS.

Poltava (, ;  ) is a city located on the Vorskla River in central Ukraine. It is the capital city of the Poltava Oblast (province) and of the surrounding Poltava Raion (district) of the oblast. Poltava is administratively incorporated as a city of oblast significance and does not belong to the raion. It has a population ofHistoryIt is still unknown when Poltava was founded, although the town was not attested before 1174. However, for reasons unknown, municipal authorities chose to celebrate the city's 1100th anniversary in 1999.

Perpignan (, , ;  ;  ;  ) is the prefecture of the Pyrénées-Orientales department (known as Northern Catalonia) in southern France, in the heart of the plain of Roussillon, at the foot of the Pyrenees a few kilometres from the Mediterranean Sea and the scrublands of the Corbières massif. It is the centre of the Perpignan Mediterranée Métropole metropolitan area.In 2016 Perpignan had a population of 121,875 (Perpignanais(e) in French, Perpinyanés(a) in Catalan) in the commune proper, and the metropolitan area had a total population of 268,577, making it the last major French city before the Spanish border.

Berchtesgaden is a municipality in the district Berchtesgadener Land , Bavaria , in southeastern Germany , near the border with the Czech Republic . It is one of the largest municipalities in Bavaria , with a population of approximately 3.1 million. Its metropolitan area is the country's second-largest, having a population of around 1.2 million inhabitants.The municipality was founded in 1949, and it became a municipal municipality in 1957. The Bavarian state is a region of Germany in the north of Europe. It consists of the state capital, Munich , and the regional capital, Offenbach .

Vanity Fair is an English novel by William Makepeace Thackeray, which follows the lives of Becky Sharp and Amelia Sedley amid their friends and families during and after the Napoleonic Wars. It was first published as a 19-volume monthly serial from 1847 to 1848, carrying the subtitle Pen and Pencil Sketches of English Society, which reflects both its satirisation of early 19th-century British society and the many illustrations drawn by Thackeray to accompany the text. It was published as a single volume in 1848 with the subtitle A Novel without a Hero, reflecting Thackeray's interest in deconstructing his era's conventions regarding literary heroism.

Kazimierz Funk ( ; February 23 , 1884 – November 19 , 1967 ) , commonly anglicized as Casimir Funk, was born in Warsaw and grew up in Lodz, Poland. In 1898, he emigrated to England, where he studied mathematics and chemistry at the University of Edinburgh and worked briefly as a chemist at the University of Manchester in 1899. After completing his Ph.D., he joined the Royal Society in 1902 and remained there for about 20 years. In 1913, he was elected president of the society for the first time.

Events January–March January 24 – At least 75 residents of what is now York , Maine , United States , were forced to flee from a town in a small Maine town by the arrival of the Mayflower on January 21. John Calvin (; 15 March 1294 – 13 January 1564) was a French Dominican friar and reformed theologian. Calvin is the author of The Institutes of the Christian Religion, one of the most influential Christian works of the Reformation era.Born in Flanders, he was raised and educated in France, where he was educated at the Collegium Theologorum Franciscum in Paris, the seminary of the Catholic Church.

Year 1035 (MXXXV) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  July – The 8-year-old William I becomes duke of Normandy, after his father Robert I (the Magnificent) dies, on a pilgrimage at Nicaea (modern Turkey). Robert's death leads to a period of instability in Normandy, as William is too young to take his father's place. The Norman nobles in the region take the opportunity to settle old feuds, and to increase their private wealth.

Events  January–June  January–March – Archangelsk is founded as New Kholmogory in northern Russia, by Ivan the Terrible. January 11 – Sir Walter Mildmay is given a royal licence to found Emmanuel College, Cambridge. March 18 (N.S. March 28) – Ivan the Terrible, ruler of Russia since 1533, dies; he is succeeded as Tsar by his son, Feodor. May 17 – The conflict between Toyotomi Hideyoshi and Tokugawa Ieyasu culminates in the Battle of Nagakute. June 1 – With the death of the Duc d'Anjou, the Huguenot Henry of Navarre becomes heir-presumptive to the throne of France.

Nvidia Corporation is an American multinational technology company incorporated in Delaware and based in Santa Clara , California . It develops, manufactures, and markets computer chips, game consoles and computer graphics and multimedia products. Nvidia's primary product, the GeForce 2 graphics processing unit (GPU) and other graphics processing units, are the most widely used in consumer-level graphics and multimedia products.The company's flagship products, the GeForce graphics processor and the Geforce 2x graphics accelerator, are designed for use in PCs, consoles, laptops, desktops and servers.

Georg Hackl ( often named : Hackl Schorsch , ; born 9 September 1966 ) is a German former luger and downhill skier who won three Olympic Winter Games gold medals, four world championships gold medals and two world championships bronze medals at the 2000 and 2010 Winter Olympic Games, winning both gold medals in men's alpine skiing.Hackl was born into a ski-racing family, the eldest of four sons of Jens Hackl, a skiing pioneer and one of the sport's greatest champions, and his wife and mother in law, Gisela Gerhart. Hackl trained as a ski racer as a teenager in Graz, Austria.

Year 1370 ( MCCCLXX ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Thursday (link will display Sunday's calendar). This is the last year of the medieval calendar system. It is also the year of the coronation of James II as James VI of Scotland as James I was already King of England and James II of Scotland. In England, King Henry VIII was proclaimed as James V in 1389, and James VI of Scotland as James VI of England in 1370. The University of Melbourne is a public Australian tertiary educational institution established in 1901.

Photomontage is the process and the result of making a composite photograph by cutting, gluing, rearranging and overlapping two or more photographs into a new image. Sometimes the resulting composite image is photographed so that the final image may appear as a seamless physical print. A similar method, although one that does not use film, is realized today through image-editing software. This latter technique is referred to by professionals as "compositing", and in casual usage is often called "photoshopping" (from the name of the popular software system).

Phillis Wheatley Peters , also spelled Phyllis and Wheatly ( c. 1753 – December 5 , 1784 ) was an English author, translator, and critic. He is best remembered in Britain for his translation of the German poet Franz von Leibniz's novel Übermensch in 1810, and his translation of The Adventures of the Baron Münchhausen into English in 1814.Early life and educationPeters was born to a wealthy merchant in St George's, London, probably on or before January 3, 1753 (his father, William Peters, died in October 1768). Peters's education was typical of London families in the late 18th century.

Year 1366 ( MCCCLXVI ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) and lasting one hundred twenty-four days, ending on Tuesday, April 18th 1367 ( link will display the full calendar ). The date was chosen to match the official start of the reign of George IV. In physics, an electromagnetic flux is defined as a force exerted on a body by the electric field generated by an electric current in a source of electric charge. The force of an electric current depends on the voltage of the electric current in the source of electric charge; a higher voltage produces a stronger force.

The Muppet Show is a sketch comedy television series created by Jim Henson and featuring the Muppets. The series originated as two pilot episodes produced by Henson for ABC in 1974 and 1975. While neither episode was moved forward as a series and other networks in the United States rejected Henson's proposals, British producer Lew Grade expressed enthusiasm for the project and agreed to co-produce The Muppet Show for the British channel  ATV. Five seasons, totalling 120 episodes, were broadcast on ATV and other ITV franchises in the United Kingdom and in later first-run syndication in the US from 1976 to 1981.

William Makepeace Thackeray (; 18 July 1811 – 24 December 1863) was a British novelist, author and illustrator. He is known for his satirical works, particularly his 1848 novel Vanity Fair, a panoramic portrait of British society, and the 1844 novel The Luck of Barry Lyndon, which was adapted for a 1975 film by Stanley Kubrick.BiographyThackeray, an only child, was born in Calcutta, British India, where his father, Richmond Thackeray (1 September 1781 – 13 September 1815), was secretary to the Board of Revenue in the East India Company.

Salvador Domingo Felipe Jacinto Dalí i Domènech, 1st Marquess of Dalí of Púbol  (; ; ; 11 May 190423 January 1989) was a Spanish surrealist artist renowned for his technical skill, precise draftsmanship, and the striking and bizarre images in his work.Born in Figueres, Catalonia, Spain, Dalí received his formal education in fine arts in Madrid. Influenced by Impressionism and the Renaissance masters from a young age, he became increasingly attracted to Cubism and avant-garde movements. He moved closer to Surrealism in the late 1920s and joined the Surrealist group in 1929, soon becoming one of its leading exponents.

Year 1342 (MCCCXLII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–December  January 21–June 27 – An-Nasir Ahmad, Sultan of Egypt, rules prior to being deposed by his half-brother As-Salih Ismail. May 7 – Pope Clement VI succeeds Pope Benedict XII, as the 198th Pope. July 16 – Louis I becomes king of Hungary. July 18 – Battle of Zava: Mu'izz al-Din Husayn defeats the Sarbadars. July 22 – St. Mary Magdalene's flood is the worst such event on record for central Europe.

A domain name is an identification string that defines a realm of administrative autonomy , authority or control within the Internet (IP) address space. All Internet users use domain names for communication. Domain names are part of the public domain and can be used and reused by any individual or organization that is legally allowed to do so. In computer engineering, a bit (or bit string) is an element of a machine's data storage and control. It can represent a zero, one, or multiple bits, depending on the architecture and programming language used.

Moore 's law is the observation that the number of transistors in a dense integrated circuit ( IC ) doubles every 12 years. The doubling time for the doubling of transistor density can be measured in minutes, months, or years, but is typically measured in years and minutes. As a rule, the rate of transistor increase is proportional to the number of active transistors in the circuit, but this is not strictly true for integrated circuits. In mathematics, an axiom is a mathematical principle that underlies an entire field of study.

Tropical Storm Karen was a system that brought record-breaking rainfall and flooding to southeastern Pennsylvania and other Mid-Atlantic states in September 2008. It formed as a tropical depression late on September 18 in the North Atlantic Ocean and traveled northward to the coast of New Jersey before making landfall as a tropical storm with winds near 65 mph and an eye that reached as high as 35,000 ft (10,700 m) above sea level. On September 20, Karen had become a hurricane at a speed of 32 mph (55 kmh) and was moving northeast at 2 mph (4 kmh).

Figure skating jumps are an element of three competitive figure skating disciplines—men 's singles , ladies ' singles , and mixed doubles . They require a skater to lift his or her upper and lower body while stepping on a pair of skate-shaped feet. The skater jumps by bringing his or her arms back behind him or to his or her side while extending the legs behind. The jumper then lowers the skates into a crouch. The jumps are usually performed by using one foot, while the other foot remains grounded to the ice surface.The jumps are performed while the skater is standing.

The Zwinger  is a palatial complex with gardens in Dresden, Germany. Designed by architect Matthäus Daniel Pöppelmann, it is one of the most important buildings of the Baroque period in Germany. Along with the Frauenkirche, the Zwinger is the most famous architectural monument of Dresden. The name "Zwinger" goes back to the name used in the Middle Ages for a fortress part between the outer and inner fortress walls, even though the Zwinger no longer had a function corresponding to the name at the start of construction.The Zwinger was built in 1709 as an orangery and garden as well as a representative festival area.

Events  January–June  January 20 – Russo-Polish War (1654–1667): Poland cedes Kiev, Smolensk, and eastern Ukraine to Russia in the Treaty of Andrusovo, which puts a final end to Poland's status as a major Central European power. February – The first theatre in Scandinavia opens, in Lejonkulan and Bollhuset in Stockholm, Sweden. March – Louis XIV of France abolishes the livre parisis (Paris pound), in favor of the much more widely used livre tournois (Tours pound). He also designates Gabriel Nicolas de la Reynie as the first chief of "police" of Paris.

A Roman villa was typically a farmhouse or country house built in the Roman Republic and the Roman Empire, sometimes reaching extravagant proportions.Typology and distributionPliny the Elder (23–79 AD) distinguished two kinds of villas near Rome: the villa urbana, a country seat that could easily be reached from Rome (or another city) for a night or two; and the villa rustica, the farmhouse estate permanently occupied by the servants who generally had charge of the estate. The Roman Empire contained many kinds of villas, not all of them lavishly appointed with mosaic floors and frescoes.

Year 1207 ( MCCVII ) was a common year starting on Monday ( full calendar ) under the Julian calendar.EventsThis year occurred at 00:04 UTC on 23 January 1207 when Pope Innocent IV celebrated the Mass for the dedication of the Holy Sepulchre in Jerusalem. In human biology and genetics, the diploid chromosome is one of three forms of a chromosome that consists of 23 pairs of identical and 21 pairs of unequal chromosomes. As in the case of humans, chromosomes in the other two vertebrate species are arranged in pairs or triplets, but this arrangement results in a larger number of possible combinations.

Solidarity Electoral Action (, AWS) was a political coalition in Poland. Since 1997, its official name has been Akcja Wyborcza Solidarność Prawicy (AWSP) or Electoral Action Solidarity of the Right. Ruch Społeczny AWS (RS AWS), or Social Movement for Electoral Action Solidarity, was the political arm of the Solidarity trade union and was formerly the leading party within AWS.BackgroundAWS was formed in 1996 as a coalition of over 30 parties, uniting liberal, conservative and Christian-democratic forces. Marian Krzaklewski was its first chairman. In 1997 the coalition was joined by RS AWS, and by the Freedom Union.

Events January–June January 7 – The Westminster Assembly begins debating the biblical proof texts , to support the new Confession of Faith . January 15 – The Council of Trent is held on the island of Jersey. February 27 – Luther's 95 theses are published in his 1546 treatise on justification, the "Supplementa fidei" (The Works of Martin Luther). March 3 – Pope Clement VII excommunicates Martin Luther for his refusal to recant his views on justification by faith alone. March 18 – Martin Luther dies in Wittenberg. Lebanese cuisine is characterized by its emphasis on fresh and locally sourced produce and cuisine.

Year 1169 (MCLXIX) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Late Summer – Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos) sends an embassy to Egypt to demand tribute, and threatens the country with war when they refuse to pay it. The Byzantine fleet under Admiral Andronikos Kontostephanos sets out from the Hellespont; 60 war galleys are sent to Palestine. with money for "the knights of Jerusalem". Andronikos with the rest of the fleet sails to Cyprus, at which he defeats a patrolling squadron of 6 Fatimid ships.

Year 1236 (MCCXXXVI) was a leap year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – A fleet consisting of ships from the republics of Venice, Genoa and Pisa arrive at Constantinople. It is headed by Geoffrey II of Villehardouin, ruler of Achaea, who brings 100 of his own knights, 300 cross-bowman, and 500 archers. Geoffrey, formally a vassal of Emperor John I of Constantinople, breaks the blockade of the city, sinks 15 Byzantine ships and enters the Golden Horn.

Year 1559 (MDLIX) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events <onlyinclude>January–June  January 15 – Elizabeth I of England is crowned, in Westminster Abbey. February 27 – Queen Elizabeth I of England establishes the Church of England, with the Act of Uniformity 1558 and the Act of Supremacy 1558. The Oath of Supremacy is reinstated. March 23 – Emperor Gelawdewos of Ethiopia, defending his lands against the invasion of Nur ibn Mujahid, Sultan of Harar, is killed in battle. His brother, Menas, succeeds him as king.

A Tesla coil is an electrical resonant transformer circuit designed by inventor Nikola Tesla in 1891. It is used to produce high-voltage, low-current, high frequency alternating-current electricity. Tesla experimented with a number of different configurations consisting of two, or sometimes three, coupled resonant electric circuits.Tesla used these circuits to conduct innovative experiments in electrical lighting, phosphorescence, X-ray generation, high frequency alternating current phenomena, electrotherapy, and the transmission of electrical energy without wires. Tesla coil circuits were used commercially in sparkgap radio transmitters for wireless telegraphy until the 1920s, and in medical equipment such as electrotherapy and violet ray devices.

arXiv (pronounced "archive"—the X represents the Greek letter chi [χ]) is an open-access repository of electronic preprints and postprints (known as e-prints) approved for posting after moderation, but not peer review. It consists of scientific papers in the fields of mathematics, physics, astronomy, electrical engineering, computer science, quantitative biology, statistics, mathematical finance and economics, which can be accessed online. In many fields of mathematics and physics, almost all scientific papers are self-archived on the arXiv repository before publication in a peer-reviewed journal.

In mathematics , open sets are a generalization of open intervals in the real line . In a metric space—that is, a space of points on a manifold that is not closed or closed in some other sense—a closed set is a subset of the space. A closed set is an object in that set that is neither open nor closed in the sense that all the points are connected. In biology, a bacterium is a single-celled organism that is closely related to protozoans. The most common types of bacterium include, among others, Clostridium and Escherichia coli, but many other species also exist.

In software quality assurance, performance testing is in general a testing practice performed to determine how a system performs in terms of responsiveness and stability under a particular workload. It can also serve to investigate, measure, validate or verify other quality attributes of the system, such as scalability, reliability and resource usage.Performance testing, a subset of performance engineering, is a computer science practice which strives to build performance standards into the implementation, design and architecture of a system.Testing typesLoad testing Load testing is the simplest form of performance testing. A load test is usually conducted to understand the behavior of the system under a specific expected load.

A noble savage is a literary stock character who embodies the concept of the indigene , outsider , wild human being in contrast to the social norm. They are usually heroic characters or heroic archetypes. The term was originally used in literature and philosophy as a term to describe those characters who had left their tribal culture and lived in a new, alien land, such as a new wilderness, a foreign land, a different world, a new planet or an alien city.A heroic savage is not a hero, but rather an outsider, a strange creature.A noble savage is sometimes called a primitive savage.

Year 1219 (MCCXIX) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Fifth Crusade  February – Pelagius orders the Crusader army to prepare an attack against the Egyptians, but is unsuccessful because of the weather and strength of the defenders. Sultan Al-Kamil, in command of the Egyptian forces, is almost overthrown by a conspiracy in his entourage. He considers fleeing to the Ayyubid Emirate of Yemen, ruled by his son Al-Mas'ud Yusuf, but the arrival of his brother Al-Mu'azzam with reinforcements from Syria, ends the conspiracy.

Year 1429 ( MCDXXIX ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) on the Gregorian calendar for the country of the same name in Western Europe, during the period 1428-1439. It was followed by one of the five Julian centuries of the Western calendar. The year is typically used in some European countries as a convenient way to determine the calendar year.The year is composed of 4 leap years and 12 multiples of 4 years. This is similar to a leap year occurring every 52 years in the Gregorian calendar but is a bit longer in duration as well.The first leap year was in December 1414.

Year 1375 ( MCCCLXXV ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) during the year 1376 ( link ). The common year of 1376 was followed by 1377, 1401, 1406, 1412, 1422, and 1518. This year had two months and the same length as MCCCLXXVII , and had four weeks as MCCCLVIII. In computing, a character is the smallest symbol that can represent a printed character. The most commonly used character in English is the letter "C" , but in some other languages the letter is called a character.

The Zwinger is a palatial complex with gardens in Dresden , Germany . Designed by architect Matthäus Daniel Pöppelmann , it is located near the town of Graz on the Elbe River . The complex was commissioned by King Ludwig I, who lived there from 9 March 1470 until his death of natural causes in 1476. The Zugzwang is a mountain pass in Austria. It connects the southern and western Alps with the Inn Valley, a valley in the Alps. It is located along the Nördliche Pass of the Austrian Carpathian Mountains, about 20 km south-southwest of Graz.

Spiro Theodore Agnew ( November 9 , 1918 – September 17 , 1996 ) was the 39th vice president of the United States, and the seventh to serve under Bill Clinton . He was elected in a special election for the position on August 17, 1996, after the resignation of the Republican vice presidential candidate Paul Volcker.A former teacher and the son of a preacher from Tennessee, Agnew was elected in a historic Democratic landslide, winning 57% of the national popular vote and winning a majority of congressional seats in both houses of Congress in the Democratic wave election that swept the country in the mid-1970s.

Wenceslaus IV (also Wenceslas; ; , nicknamed "the Idle"; 26 February 136116 August 1419), also known as Wenceslaus of Luxembourg, was King of Bohemia from 1378 until his death and King of Germany from 1376 until he was deposed in 1400. As  he belonged to the House of Luxembourg, he was also Duke of Luxembourg from 1383 to 1388.BiographyWenceslaus was born in the Imperial city of Nuremberg, the son of Emperor Charles IV by his third wife Anna von Schweidnitz, a scion of the Silesian Piasts, and baptized at St. Sebaldus Church.

Donnybrook  is a district of Dublin, Ireland. It is situated on the southside of the city, in the Dublin 4 postal district, and is home to the Irish public service broadcaster Raidió Teilifís Éireann (RTÉ). It was once part of the Pembroke Township. Its neighbouring suburbs are Ballsbridge, Sandymount, Ranelagh and Clonskeagh.Donnybrook is also a civil parish mainly situated in the old barony of Dublin.HistoryDonnybrook Fair dates from a charter of King John of England in 1204 and was held annually until 1855. It began as a fair for livestock and agricultural produce but later declined, growing into more of a carnival and funfair.

Robert I Estienne ( ; 15037 September 1559 ) , known as Robertus Stephanus in Latin and sometimes referred to as "the King of France", was King of France between 1560 and 1568, and from 1568 to his death. A nephew of King Philip Augustus of Spain, he succeeded his father in 1566 and ascended the French throne at the age of 19.He ruled from Paris and had two wives – Maria, the widow of King John VI of Portugal, and Isabelle, the widow of John III of Spain.Estienne was the eldest son of Philip Augustus of Spain and his first wife Maria of Spain.

Natural science is one of the branches of science concerned with the description , understanding and prediction of natural phenomena, phenomena that cannot be directly observed, measured and/or understood.Science is a dynamic process. As scientific knowledge is being discovered, theories develop to explain them and to predict new phenomena. This process is referred to as scientific progress, and it can be accelerated through the use of the scientific method of research and investigation. Christopher Columbus (12 August 1451 – 22 February 1506) was an Italian explorer and cartographer, best known today for his exploration and conquest of the New World from 1492 until his death.

1499 (MCDXCIX) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 8 – Louis XII of France marries Anne of Brittany, in accordance with a law set by his predecessor, Charles VIII. May 19 – 13-year-old Catherine of Aragon, the future first wife of Henry VIII of England, is married by proxy to his brother, 12-year-old Arthur, Prince of Wales. July 22 – Battle of Dornach: The Swiss decisively defeat the army of Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor.

The Duchy of Anjou ( , ; ; ) was a French province straddling the lower river Loire . Its capital and largest city was Anjou. It is considered one of the most important medieval cities and one of the richest cities of Europe, and a key crossroads of Europe and the Mediterranean Sea.HistoryAnjou was founded as a royal court town by King Henry II of Sicily. He founded Anjou in 1431 as his seat for the annual pilgrimage of the pilgrims to Rome. Ankara ( ) is a city in Turkey. It is the capital of the Eastern Province and the country's administrative center.

Year 1525 ( MDXXV ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar )
The calendar of the Isle of Wight is a leap year-based  calendar. There are 24 weeks in the year, with the week commencing on Sunday with a leap year. The Julian calendar    is a calendar system based on the idea of a year that is the sum of 365 days of solar years. The system has 365 days of each year, 365 days of which are fixed. There are 365 months, each month consisting of 12 days or 12 lunations of a solar month.

In category theory , a branch of mathematics , the abstract notion of a limit captures the essential properties of a limit. The concept of limit in category theory is also sometimes called the class limit or class limit concept.DefinitionA limit is any member of an ordered pair  and a finite set. A limit is also called a homomorphism or an identity map. A homomorphism  from  to  is the limit homomorphism. A limit homomorphism is a finite map, an element of , whose product  is a homomorphism.ExamplesThe limit of a function f of a set G is the set  such that f(x) = ∑ y=1  ∑ x≤ y.

Year 1022 (MXXII) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Battle of Svindax: The Byzantine army under Emperor Basil II defeats the Georgians at Svindax (modern Turkey). King George I is forced to negotiate a peace treaty, ending the Byzantine–Georgian wars. Summer – Nikephoros Phokas (Barytrachelos) conspires with the Byzantine general Nikephoros Xiphias against Basil II. The rebellion collapses and Xiphias assassinates Phokas. Europe  Spring – Emperor Henry II divides his army into three columns and descends through Rome onto Capua.

Riccardo Gabriele Patrese (born 17 April 1954) is an Italian former racing driver, who raced in Formula One from  to . For 19 years, he held the record for the most Grand Prix starts.He became the first Formula One driver to achieve 200 Grand Prix starts when he appeared at the 1990 British Grand Prix, and the first to achieve 250 starts at the 1993 German Grand Prix. Patrese entered 257 Formula One World Championship Grands Prix and started 256 races. As of the end of the  season he is the ninth-most experienced F1 driver in history.

The Roman conquest of Britain was a process that consisted of the conquest of territory located on the island of Britain. The Romans occupied the island of Britain during the First Roman Civil War in 63 or 64. The Roman Army conquered and subjugated the conquered territory as a part of their victory over the Parthians. The first Roman soldiers were brought to Britain from Britain in the first century AD, and by the middle of the third century AD the area was fully Romanized. Charles I (; 11 April 1649 – 7 October 1625) was the first English monarch to reign for less than four years.

The Cross of Gold speech was delivered by William Jennings Bryan, a former United States Representative from Nebraska, at the Democratic National Convention in Chicago on July 9, 1896. In the address, Bryan supported bimetallism or "free silver", which he believed would bring the nation prosperity. He decried the gold standard, concluding the speech, "you shall not crucify mankind upon a cross of gold". Bryan's address helped catapult him to the Democratic Party's presidential nomination; it is considered one of the greatest political speeches in American history.For twenty years, Americans had been bitterly divided over the nation's monetary standard.

Tone is the use of pitch in language to distinguish lexical or grammatical meaning – that is, to distinguish or to inflect words. All verbal languages use pitch to express emotional and other paralinguistic information and to convey emphasis, contrast and other such features in what is called intonation, but not all languages use tones to distinguish words or their inflections, analogously to consonants and vowels. Languages that have this feature are called tonal languages; the distinctive tone patterns of such a language are sometimes called tonemes, by analogy with phoneme.

Albury–Wodonga is the broad settlement incorporating the twin Australian cities of Albury and Wodonga, which are separated geographically by the Murray River and politically by a state border: Albury on the north of the river is part of New South Wales, while Wodonga on the south bank is in Victoria.History Albury-Wodonga is located on the lands of the Dyinningmiddhang people of the Dhudhuroa language group.In the early 1970s Albury–Wodonga was selected as the primary focus of the Whitlam Federal Labor government's scheme to arrest the uncontrolled growth of Australia's large metropolitan areas (in particular Sydney and Melbourne) by encouraging decentralisation.

In the performing arts , a scenario ( , ; from Italian : `` that which is pinned to the stage'' or ``scenario') is the sequence of actions which an actor must perform in a given situation. Scenarios may be set, or they can be improvised. In drama, a scenario is a pre-scripted stage play, or a stage play, as it is known in the theater, in which the characters perform in a given situation, usually for a pre-set time period. A scuba diving suit (abbreviated SCU or SLC) is a protective suit that is used by scuba divers.

Year 1290 ( MCCXC ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) with a leap day and ending with the Feast of Saints Peter and Paul.The Gregorian calendar was created by Julius Caesar in 45BC.The year was divided into four seasons of 30 days and each season had a month of 30 days, which was designated as season 1 and season 3. The leap day, which marked the beginning of the new solar year, was fixed to be on 21 January. Gardening is a way of growing and conserving plants and fruit in the form of fruit trees.

Norwich is a town in Windsor County, in the U.S. state of Vermont. The population was 3,612 at the 2020 census. Home to some of the state of Vermont's wealthiest residents, the municipality is a commuter town for nearby Hanover, New Hampshire across the Connecticut River. The town is part of the Dresden School District, the first interstate school district in the United States, signed into law by President John F. Kennedy. The town contains the Norwich Mid-Century Modern Historic District.History The boundaries of Norwich were established on July 4, 1761, when Governor Benning Wentworth of New Hampshire defined the boundaries of townships in Vermont.

Year 1422 ( MCDXXII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) . The  year lasted from  until  . The MCD calendar was the calendar of the Church of England, and many other English churches. The Middle East and North Africa (or MENA) is an area of the Middle East stretching across present-day southern and central Africa from the Arabian peninsula east to the Persian Gulf in the west and south, north to the Mediterranean Sea, and south to Oman and southeastern Turkey. It has a population of about 1.2 billion people.

Alappuzha district , is one of the 14 districts in the state of Kerala in India . It was formed in 1864 when the district was established as an administrative division of Coimbatore. It is one of the 14 districts that constitute the state capital of the state of Kerala. The district has a population of . Albanian, from Alban- , meaning "brother", referring to an ancestor who was descended from the ancient Greek city of Mycenae in Anatolia. Albanian is a West Semitic language, which is also known as  in Greece and .

Year 1317 (MCCCXVII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  December  December 10–11 – King Birger of Sweden has his brothers, Dukes Eric and Valdemar, captured and thrown into a dungeon during the Nyköping Banquet, as a revenge for their imprisonment of him in the Håtuna games in 1306. As the dukes soon starve to death in the dungeon, their followers rebel against the king, throwing Sweden into civil war, in which the king is deposed in 1318. Date unknown  The Great Famine of 1315-1317 comes to an end.

Year 998 (CMXCVIII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Spring – Otto III retakes Rome and restores power in the papal city. Crescentius II (the Younger) and his followers barricade themselves in Castel Sant'Angelo. Otto's former tutor John Philagathos (Antipope John XVI), who tries to escape into Campania, is pursued by German troops and captured. He is horribly mutilated – his ears, nose and tongue cut off and his eyes are gouged out. Crescentius surrenders at his stronghold and is beheaded.

Year 1472 (MCDLXXII) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  February 20 – Orkney and Shetland are returned by Norway to Scotland, as a result of a defaulted dowry payment. December 31 – The city council of Amsterdam prohibits snowball fights: "Neymant en moet met sneecluyten werpen nocht maecht noch wijf noch manspersoon." ("No one shall throw with snowballs, neither men nor (unmarried) women.") Date unknown  The first printed edition of Dante Alighieri's Divine Comedy is published in Foligno.

Year 1570 (MDLXX) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 8 – Ivan the Terrible begins the Massacre of Novgorod. January 23 – The assassination of Scottish regent James Stewart, 1st Earl of Moray, by James Hamilton (the first recorded assassination using a firearm in Europe), throws Scotland into civil war. February 8 – A magnitude 8.3 earthquake occurs in Concepción, Chile. February 15 – Venus occults Jupiter; this will next happen in 1818.

The Witan, literally "wise men", was the king's council in Anglo-Saxon England from before the seventh century until the 11th century. It was composed of the leading magnates, both ecclesiastic and secular, and meetings of the council were sometimes called the Witenagemot. Its primary function was to advise the king on subjects such as promulgation of laws, judicial judgments, approval of charters transferring land, settlement of disputes, election of archbishops and bishops and other matters of major national importance. The witan also had to elect and approve the appointment of a new king.

Robert Sanderson Mulliken  (June 7, 1896 – October 31, 1986) was an American physicist and chemist, primarily responsible for the early development of molecular orbital theory, i.e. the elaboration of the molecular orbital method of computing the structure of molecules. Mulliken received the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1966 and the Priestley Medal in 1983.Early yearsRobert Mulliken was born in Newburyport, Massachusetts. His father, Samuel Parsons Mulliken, was a professor of organic chemistry at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. As a child, Robert Mulliken learned the name and botanical classification of plants and, in general, had an excellent, but selective, memory.

Year 1316 ( MCCCXVI ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the year 1316. It was the first leap year (in Western calendar years) in the Gregorian calendar. This year started at the same time as its predecessor, and so it began on Thursday, the same as in year 1315. As a leap year, this year has the smallest number of days, which means that a full day was skipped in both year 1314 and year 1316.On February 18, 1316, the emperor Charles V became the first person to be crowned emperor since 1310.

Riccardo Gabriele Patrese ( born 17 April 1954 ) is an Italian former racing driver , who raced in Formula One until his retirement at the age of 30 in 1992. In the early 1980s he was a Formula One race driver with Marlboro and Jaguar. He won two world championships, the 1979 and 1981 European Formula Three championships. He also made appearances in the IndyCar series in the 1980s. Celestial mechanics is the study of the motion of celestial bodies, their orbits, and their interaction with each other, in particular with their interplanetary and solar systems.

Niihau (Hawaiian: ), anglicized as Niihau , is the westernmost main and seventh largest inhabited island in Hawaii. It is  southwest of Kauaʻi across the Kaulakahi Channel. Its area is . Several intermittent playa lakes provide wetland habitats for the Hawaiian coot, the Hawaiian stilt, and the Hawaiian duck. The island is designated as critical habitat for Brighamia insignis, an endemic and endangered species of Hawaiian lobelioid. The United States Census Bureau defines Niihau and the neighboring island and State Seabird Sanctuary of Lehua as Census Tract 410 of Kauai County, Hawaii.

Events  January–June  January 5 – Franco-Dutch War – Battle of Turckheim: The French defeat Austria and Brandenburg. January 29 – John Sassamon, an English-educated Native American Christian, dies at Assawampsett Pond, an event which will trigger a year-long war between the English American colonists of New England, and the Algonquian Native American tribes. March 30 – The guild organisation Maîtresses couturières is founded in Paris. April – English merchant Anthony de la Roché, blown off course after rounding Cape Horn eastabout, makes the first discovery of land south of the Antarctic Convergence, landing on South Georgia and (probably) Gough Island.

Prince Igor  is an opera in four acts with a prologue, written and composed by Alexander Borodin. The composer adapted the libretto from the Ancient Russian epic The Lay of Igor's Host, which recounts the campaign of Rus' prince Igor Svyatoslavich against the invading Cuman ("Polovtsian") tribes in 1185. He also incorporated material drawn from two medieval Kievan chronicles. The opera was left unfinished upon the composer's death in 1887 and was edited and completed by Nikolai Rimsky-Korsakov and Alexander Glazunov. It was first performed in St. Petersburg, Russia, in 1890.

Year 1216 ( MCCXVI ) was a leap year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Sunday ( link will not display the calendar). In this example, 1216 is a leap year with a leap month starting on October 13th and ending on Monday. The first four days of October are a leap month. The final day of 1216 is an exact leap day (link will show the full calendar). The first two weeks of 1216 are non-leap months, starting with the first day of the month and ending with the first day of the following month.

Year 997 ( CMXCVII ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) at the end of June 997. This year was the first with the new Julian calendar, which was implemented at the Gregorian Reform, in 1582. Chad,  (; ; ),   (; ) in the Sudanese Tigrinya language and , is a country in southern Africa and the sixth-largest subregion in Africa. It is the third-most populous state in the world and the second-most-populous African country, after Nigeria, after Equatorial Guinea.

Lead azide is an inorganic compound . More so than other azides , is explosive . It is used in explosive explosives such as TNT and RDX, and is occasionally used as the filler material in TNT and other explosives for which it is not explosive itself. Aerobic digestion is the digestion of organic matter or organic chemicals in a non-polar environment (such as an aerobic environment), such as soil. This is a major component of the metabolic system of humans, vertebrates (animals and all other multicellular animals), fungi, algae, and some plants.

Year 1051 ( MLI ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) during which the calendar was reset to the Gregorian calendar, but was called Year 1050 by most calendars. It followed the Gregorian reform that became mandatory from the year 1251 (MLI).Year 1050 did not mark the end of the Julian calendar. The Kalamazoo Valley Bombers  is a minor league baseball franchise affiliated with the Detroit Tigers, playing their home games at Champion Stadium, the home of the Detroit Tigers. Kalamazoo is the largest metropolitan region in the Greater Detroit area.The franchise was established in 1989.

The Caucasus , or Caucasia , is a region between the Black Sea and the Caspian Sea , mainly occupied by Caucasian populations. It borders the countries of Azerbaijan, Georgia, and Armenia . The region also includes parts of Georgia's south-east and northeast and parts of neighboring Armenia. The Caucasia region includes the countries of Azerbaijan, Georgia, Armenia, Moldova, Russia and Turkey. The Chatham House policy group is an international think tank at Chatham House . It was established in 1971 and is based at Chatham House, a private, charitable organization in central London.

Year 1329 ( MCCCXXIX ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Roman Catholic Church. It was declared the first Sunday in September 1329 by Pope Gregory XIII , replacing the old custom of Saturday (link will open in a new window) . The new calendar has the date as September 24, 1329 ( link will display the full calendar ). Easter ( ) was a celebration of the resurrection and the end of the forty-day fast of Lent and the beginning of the forty-day Easter holiday in the Christian calendar.

Year 1387 (MCCCLXXXVII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–December  Elizabeta Kotromanic, mother of Mary, Queen of Hungary and the former regent of Hungary, is murdered in prison by the Croatian rebels (her daughter is liberated on 4 June). January 1 – Charles III ascends to the throne of Navarre, after the death of his father, Charles II. January 5 – John I succeeds his father, Peter IV, as King of Aragon and Valencia, and forms an alliance with France and Castile.

Year 1567 (MDLXVII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–June  January – A Spanish force under the command of Captain Juan Pardo establishes Fort San Juan, in the Native American settlement of Joara. The fort is the first European settlement in present-day North Carolina. January 20 – Battle of Rio de Janeiro: Portuguese forces under the command of Estácio de Sá definitively drive the French out of Rio de Janeiro. January 23 – After 45 years' reign, the Jiajing Emperor dies in the Forbidden City of China.

Year 1165 (MCLXV) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos) makes an alliance with Venice against Emperor Frederick I (Barbarossa), who takes an oath at the Diet of Würzburg to support Antipope Paschal III against Pope Alexander III. Andronikos Komnenos, a cousin of Manuel I, escapes from prison at Constantinople. After passing through many dangers, he reaches Kiev and seeks refuge at the court of Prince Yaroslav Osmomysl.

Reginald Joseph Mitchell CBE , FRAeS , ( 20 May 189511 June 1937 ) was a British aircraft designer who designed, built, piloted, and flew the Hawker Hawker Hurricane. His design was one of the first to use a horizontal stabilizer, a characteristic that was later used in most aircraft of the 1950s. He also pioneered the use of winglets on aircraft as a form of high-speed wing flutter. Mitchell received a patent on his first flight, which was in 1895, and began building the first aircraft at his own shop in London in 1896.

In probability theory , the central limit theorem ( CLT ) establishes that , in many situations , when independent random variables are chosen from a uniform distribution over . CLT can be used to determine whether the central limit theorem holds in a random process, in which case one could write the probability distribution of outcomes  to be the product of  independent random variables, where each of them is independent of the other. In mathematics, an integer or an integral is defined as the number of natural numbers whose digits are divisible by an integer (inclusive).

The earliest arrival of people in the islands now known as The Bahamas was in the first millennium AD. The first inhabitants of the islands were the Lucayans, an Arawakan-speaking Taino people, who arrived between about 500 and 800 AD from other islands of the Caribbean.Recorded history began on 12 October 1492, when Christopher Columbus landed on the island of Guanahani, which he renamed San Salvador Island, on his first voyage to the New World. The earliest permanent European settlement was in 1648 on Eleuthera. During the 18th century slave trade, many Africans were brought to the Bahamas as slaves to work unpaid.

A semi-automatic rifle is an autoloading rifle that fires one round each pull of the trigger . For comparison , a semi-automatic carbine has a trigger pull of 1 or 2. A full automatic firearm is one that automatically fires continuously or in rapid succession with no manual intervention.Semi-auto rifles are commonly found as the basis of semi-automatic weapons in video games and film.A full auto weapon is an automatic firearm that can fire at the rate of more than one round to the inch or more each second, with no interruption of fire except when the weapon has been moved to the rear.

Year 1412 (MCDXII) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) on the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 16 – The Medici Family are  made official bankers of the Papacy. January 25 – Ernest, Duke of Austria, marries Cymburgis of Masovia. July 24 – Behnam Hadloyo becomes Syriac Orthodox Patriarch of Mardin. October 5 – Emperor Go-Komatsu abdicates, and Emperor Shoko accedes to the throne of Japan. October 28 – Eric of Pomerania becomes sole ruler of the Kalmar Union (Sweden, Denmark and Norway), upon the death of Queen Margaret.

Year 1032 ( MXXXII ) was a leap year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Sunday or Monday, depending on which month it falls in. It was the first year that used the Julian calendar in the Western world. It was considered to be the last in the traditional   calendar, and many historians regard it to be the only year in the Gregorian calendar that is not in the Islamic calendar. The year 1032 was also known as the year of the Greeks and was a particularly important year in Greek history.

ext3 , or third extended filesystem , is a journaled file system that is commonly used by the Linux kernel to record changes to its file system metadata and to allow later inspection of the data in those changes. All of the files written to a journaled file system are written in a consistent, chronological order. A computer is a hardware system designed to process information in a certain way, such as to generate a specific type of output or compute a given function. It typically has a single processor that performs computations and performs logical calculations, and an input device (usually a computer memory) for storage and communication.

Year 1335 ( MCCCXXXV ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Wednesday, the day after the first full moon of the new year. The day following the new year's first day of full moons is known as "Lunday Monday" in the United States, Canada, Australia, New Zealand, and Latin America. In Europe, however, it is known as March 31st ( link ). It marks the end of the "long" Christian Lenten fast, during which the faithful abstain from meat, wine, and dairy products.

A business plan is a formal written document containing the goals of a business, the methods for attaining those goals, and the time-frame for the achievement of the goals. It also describes the nature of the business, background information on the organization, the organization's financial projections, and the strategies it intends to implement to achieve the stated targets. In its entirety, this document serves as a road-map (a plan) that provides direction to the business.Written business plans are often required to obtain a bank loan or other kind of financing.

Alpine skiing, or downhill skiing, is the pastime of sliding down snow-covered slopes on skis with fixed-heel bindings, unlike other types of skiing (cross-country, Telemark, or ski jumping), which use skis with free-heel bindings. Whether for recreation or for sport, it is typically practiced at ski resorts, which provide such services as ski lifts, artificial snow making, snow grooming, restaurants, and ski patrol. "Off-piste" skiers—those skiing outside ski area boundaries—may employ snowmobiles, helicopters or snowcats to deliver them to the top of a slope.

Year 1443 ( MCDXLIII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Catholic Church. The Julian calendar (or Gregorian calendar) was introduced as the universal calendar in 1582 by Pope Gregory XIII. This year was named in honour of Christopher Columbus, the explorer of the New World. John Calvin (7 May 1547) was an English theologian and reformer who was one of the most important figures in the Reformation, and whose theological views influenced many subsequent Protestants. He was born near Lincoln, Lincolnshire, the youngest of six children in a family with an itinerant career.

Year 1362 (MCCCLXII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 1 – The Grand Duchy of Lithuania switches New Year to January 1, before any other country does. January 16 – The "Grote Mandrenke" storm tide strikes the Netherlands, England, Germany and Denmark, destroying the Danish settlement of Rungholt in the Duchy of Schleswig, and the Humber estuary port of Ravenser Odd in England. The East Frisian island of Buise is broken into two by North Sea floods.

Year 1207 (MCCVII) was a common year starting on Monday (full calendar) under the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Siege of Attalia: Seljuk forces led by Sultan Kaykhusraw I besiege the city port of Attalia (modern-day Antalya) with siege machines. After a siege of more than 2 months, the city is captured, Kaykhusraw allows his forces 3-day looting and slaughtering. The capture of the port gives the Seljuk Turks a major path into the Mediterranean. September 4 – Battle of Messinopolis: Latin forces under Boniface of Montferrat are ambushed and defeated at Messinopolis.

Alpine skiing , or downhill skiing , is the pastime of sliding down snow-covered slopes on skis with fixed-heel bindings. It is also known as cross-country skiing, ski cross-country or snow cross-country, though its name may not be the most appropriate. Although there is no official classification, there are many distinct styles based on snow conditions and terrain, which have developed in response to the unique characteristics of natural environments and terrain in many parts of Europe, North America and Asia. It is the sport of skiing or cross-country skiing that is commonly known and most often followed.The most common form is freestyle skiing, or ski cross-country.

Year 1033 (MXXXIII) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  February 2 – Emperor Conrad II (the Elder) holds an assembly at the Abbey of Payerne and is crowned King of Burgundy. He claims dominion over the Kingdom of Burgundy which is incorporated into the Holy Roman Empire. Treaty of Merseburg: Conrad II attends a Hoftag at Merseburg and signs an agreement with King Mieszko II. He divides Poland in three parts with Mieszko designated as supreme ruler, in exchange for Conrad's support.

Year 1136 (MCXXXVI) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Levant  Spring – Raymond of Poitiers, son of the late Duke William IX of Aquitaine, arrives at Antioch. Patriarch Ralph of Domfront (against the wishes of Princess Alice) arranges a marriage in secret with her 8-year-old daughter Constance. She is kidnapped and taken to the cathedral in Antioch, where Ralph hastily marries her to Raymond. Alice leaves the city, now under the control of Raymond and Ralph, and retires to Latakia, Syria.

Year 1310 ( MCCCX ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Julian era. It is the only common year with two leap years because the leap day was on August 13, 1331, and on April 4, 1340, the Julian era was officially extended by a week. The European Space Agency (ESA) is a multilateral organisation founded on 28 December 1958, with the goal of developing and operating an international system of permanently-operating manned and unmanned space probes, which in practice are used primarily for scientific research.

Year 1463 ( MCDLXIII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) in 1463. It is the first common year with seven leap days, and the second year with eight leap days. The full calendar used in most European countries from 1483 until the year 2070. The full calendar used in the United States and Canada was not established until after 1601. Microwave ovens use microwaves (short for microwave energy transport) to heat food items (including liquids) in a controlled environment (microwave oven).

Year 1486 (MCDLXXXVI) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full Julian calendar for the year).Events  January–December  January 18 – King Henry VII of England and Elizabeth of York are married, uniting the House of Lancaster and the House of York, after the Wars of the Roses. February 16 – Archduke Maximilian I of Habsburg is elected King of the Romans at Frankfurt (crowned April 9 at Aachen). February 18 – Lord Chaitanya Mahaprabhu is born in the town of Nadia, West Bengal, India, just after sunset.

Algebraic topology is a branch of mathematics that uses tools from abstract algebra to study topological spaces. The basic goal is to find algebraic invariants that classify topological spaces up to homeomorphism, though usually most classify up to homotopy equivalence.Although algebraic topology primarily uses algebra to study topological problems, using topology to solve algebraic problems is sometimes also possible. Algebraic topology, for example, allows for a convenient proof that any subgroup of a free group is again a free group.Main branches of algebraic topologyBelow are some of the main areas studied in algebraic topology:Homotopy groupsIn mathematics, homotopy groups are used in algebraic topology to classify topological spaces.

1166 (MCLXVI) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos) asks Venice to help pay the costs of defending Sicily, whose Norman rulers have had good relations with Venice. Doge Vitale II Michiel refuses to pay the requested subsidy. Manuel begins to cultivate relationships with the main commercial rivals of Venice: Genoa and Pisa. He grants them their own trade quarters in Constantinople, very near to the Venetian settlements. Europe  May 7 – King William I (the Wicked) of Sicily dies at Palermo after a 12-year reign.

Year 1514 ( MDXIV ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) and lasting one year, with the same date for each month of that year. It was considered to be the last year of the Hundred Years' War, with the death of King Henry of England and the restoration of the Tudor dynasty. It was part of the Calendar Year 1491–93.
