The Polish People's Party (, PSL) is an agrarian political party in Poland. It is currently led by Władysław Kosiniak-Kamysz.Its history traces back to 1895, when it held the name People's Party, although its name was changed to the present one in 1903. During the Second Polish Republic, the Polish People's Party was represented by a number of parties that held its name. They were all supportive of agrarian policies, although they spanned from the left-wing to the centre-right on the political spectrum. It was reformed into the People's Party shortly after the Sanacja regime took power.

In geometry , two figures or objects are congruent if they have the same shape and size , or if their sizes are the same. The figure of concurrence of two or more figures, also called congruence, is represented by a parallelogram, or a circle with its vertex at the same angle. This is an example of a closed curve. In economics, the natural rate of interest is the market price of short-term money. It describes the equilibrium amount of money that the economy could be operating on at a time.

Year 1429 (MCDXXIX) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  February 12 – Battle of Rouvray (or "of the Herrings"): English forces under Sir John Fastolf defend a supply convoy, which is carrying rations (food) to the army of William de la Pole, 4th Earl of Suffolk at Orléans, from attack by the Comte de Clermont and John Stewart. April 29 – Siege of Orléans: Joan of Arc enters Orléans with a relief expedition. May 7 – The Tourelles, the last English siege fortification at Orléans, falls.

The human leg , in the general word sense , is the entire lower limb of the human body , including the foot (and sometimes toes). The human leg usually includes the foot (and sometimes toes) and can sometimes include the lower leg in some individuals. In general, most persons have two femur bones: one at the front of the thigh, and one at the back, but this is not universal in all populations. The human thigh contains the vast majority of the thigh's mass while the leg's hip is the site of most muscles, especially the gluteus maximus and the calf muscles.

An engagement ring is a ring indicating that the person wearing it is engaged to be married, especially in Western cultures. A ring is presented as an engagement gift by a partner to their prospective spouse when they propose marriage or directly after a marriage proposal is accepted. It represents a formal agreement to future marriage. In Western countries, engagement rings are worn mostly by women, and rings can feature diamonds or other gemstones. The neologism "mangagement ring" is sometimes used for an engagement ring worn by men. In some cultures, men and women wear matching rings, and engagement rings may also be used as wedding rings.

John Bunyan ( ; baptised 30 November 162831 August 1688 ) was an English writer and Puritan preacher best remembered for his Christian apocalypticism.Born in Walthamstow, north London, he was the eldest son of James and Mary Bunyan, who ran a wool-wool manufacture in the city. Anaphylaxis (; from Greek   an ,  γγίνη ( , ),  Αέγχα ( , , , ) "fever") is a sudden and severe allergic reaction to a substance or agent, caused by an allergic reaction. Symptoms may include hives or swelling, wheezing, difficulty breathing, nausea, vomiting, and a rash on the skin.

The Laboratory for Atmospheric and Space Physics ( LASP ) is a research organization at the University of Colorado Boulder. It was named after James A. Schneider, who established the research group in 1950. LASP's mission is to advance the understanding of atmospheric and space science in the United States, in cooperation with national and international scientific research institutes and universities, and by disseminating advances to the community.LASP was established in 1950 under the leadership of James A. Schneider, the University of Colorado Professor of Physics and Astronomy, with the support of the National Science Foundation.

Year 1516 (MDXVI) was a leap year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January – Juan Díaz de Solís discovers the Río de la Plata (in future Argentina). January 23 – With the death of Ferdinand II of Aragon, his grandson, Charles of Ghent, becomes King of Spain; his mother Queen Joanna of Castile also succeeds as Queen of Aragon and co-monarch with Carlos, but remains confined at Tordesillas. March 1 – Desiderius Erasmus publishes a new Greek edition of the New Testament, Novum Instrumentum omne, in Basel.

Events < onlyinclude > January–June January 17 – The Treaty of Königsberg is signed , establishing an alliance between Charles II of England and Philip II of Spain , which remains in place for the next seven years. Celts  are an Indo-European ethnic group that lived in the northern parts of Europe during the early Iron Age. The Celts first appear in classical antiquity, at least as the subjects of classical mythology.The Celts are characterized by their distinctive Celtic languages. The Celtic languages include Ancient Celtic, Latin and English.The Celts were a large group of people, numbering around 40 to 100 million people.

Perpignan ( , , ; ; ; ) is the prefecture of the Pyrénées-Orientales department ( known as Northern Catalonia until 1874) in the Catalan-speaking part of the province of Catalonia.The city is situated on the northern slopes of Cervera de Sol, the highest point in Catalonia at 5,093 m (19,631 ft) above sea level.The prefecture is bounded on the west by the Cantabrian foothills, on the north by the Catalan coast, and on the east by a narrow strip of water that separates it from the Ñoliz River.Perpignan is one of the top ten cities in the world for its cultural heritage and the third-most visited city in Spain.

Events  January–March  January 10 – England and the Dutch Republic sign a mutual defense treaty in order to fight against France. January 27 – The first fire engine company (in what will become the United States) goes into service. February 18 – The first part of English nonconformist preacher John Bunyan's Christian allegory, The Pilgrim's Progress, is published in London. March 6 – King Charles II of England opens his third Parliament. March 21 – Thomas Shadwell's comedy, A True Widow, is given its first performance, debuting at The Duke's Theatre and staged by the Duke's Company.

Events <onlyinclude>January–March  January 1 – The Abenaki tribe and the Massachusetts colonists sign a treaty, ending the conflict in New England. January 4 – The Palace of Whitehall in London, England is destroyed by fire. January 23 – George Louis (who in 1714 will become King George I of Great Britain) becomes Elector of Hanover upon the death of his father, Ernest Augustus. Because the widow of Ernest Augustus, George's mother Sophia, was heiress presumptive as the cousin of Anne, Queen of Great Britain, and Anne's closest eligible heir, George will become King of Great Britain.

The picometre (international spelling as used by the International Bureau of Weights and Measures; SI symbol: pm) or picometer (American spelling) is a unit of length in the metric system, equal to , or one trillionth  of a metre, which is the SI base unit of length.The picometre is one thousandth of a nanometre ( nm), one millionth of a micrometre (also known as a micron), one billionth of a millimetre, and one trillionth of a metre. The symbol μμ was once used for it.

Year 1494 ( MCDXCIV ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and lasting until Friday 1495 ( link will display the day after that one). The day before this year (the 1498 full calendar year and MCDXCII, which is not a common year) would have been January 1, 1496, but was postponed until the next year. Moloch (, , ; ; ; ) was the name of a demon in Jewish mythology. According to some versions of the book of Job, he is the God of Israel.

Ski jumping is a winter sport in which competitors aim to achieve the farthest jump after sliding down on their skis from a specially designed curved ramp. Along with jump length, competitor's aerial style and other factors also affect the final score. Ski jumping was first contested in Norway in the late 19th century, and later spread through Europe and North America in the early 20th century. Along with cross-country skiing, it constitutes the traditional group of Nordic skiing disciplines.The ski jumping venue, commonly referred to as a hill, consists of the jumping ramp (in-run), take-off table, and a landing hill.

The 1988 United States presidential election was the 51st quadrennial presidential election, held on Tuesday, November 8, 1988. The Republican nominee, incumbent Vice President George H. W. Bush, defeated the Democratic nominee, Governor Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts. This was the first presidential election since 1948, and the most recent to date, in which a party won a third consecutive presidential term. This also remains the most recent election in which a candidate won over 400 electoral votes, and the last time a non-incumbent Republican candidate won the popular vote.Incumbent president Ronald Reagan was ineligible to seek a third term.

Greyhound racing is an organized , competitive sport in which greyhounds are raced around a track . There are two different forms of racing: endurance racing (also called greyhound racing) and jumping. Endurance racing, also known as endurance racing, is the most prestigious form of greyhound racing and is the most popular of the two. Jumping, also known as jumping over or jumping the track, is the less popular form of greyhound racing.In endurance races, a group of greyhounds are divided into pairs by size. Gravitational waves are a type of wave in the electromagnetic field that was discovered in the early 1980s.

Year 1468 (MCDLXVIII) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December June 30 – Catherine Cornaro is married by proxy to James II of Cyprus, beginning the Venetian conquest of Cyprus. August 26 – Baeda Maryam succeeds his father Zara Yaqob, as Emperor of Ethiopia. October 14 – The Treaty of Péronne is signed by Charles the Bold, Duke of Burgundy, and Louis XI of France. Date unknown  The Lancastrians surrender Harlech Castle to King Edward IV of England after a seven-year siege.

Year 1511 (MDXI) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  March 26 - The 1511 Idrija earthquake occurs, with a maximum Mercalli intensity of X (Extreme). The epicenter is around the town of Idrija in present-day Slovenia, although some place it some 15-20 kilometers to the west, between Gemona and Pulfero in Friulian Slovenia. The earthquake affects a large territory between Carinthia, Friuli, present-day Slovenia and Croatia. April 9 St John's College, Cambridge, England, founded by Lady Margaret Beaufort, receives its charter.The Şahkulu Rebellion breaks out in Anatolia.

Dub mac Maíl Coluim ( Modern Gaelic : Dubh mac Mhaoil Chaluim , ) , sometimes anglicised as Duff MacMalcolm , is a river in the South West Highlands of Scotland. The name is derived from Old Gaelic dubh meaning 'bridge' and mac means 'village'. It is a navigable tributary of the river Lune in the south-east corner of Argyll, the headwaters of the Tay, and forms the eastern branch of the Ayrshire and Fife rivers.The river is a tributary of the River Clyde. Dogs are social animals that live in groups. Dogs have a wide variety of behaviours, which can be categorized into four types.

Year 1490 (MCDXC) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 4 – Anne of Brittany announces that all those who ally themselves with the king of France will be considered guilty of the crime of Lèse-majesté. March 13 – Charles II becomes Duke of Savoy at age 1; his mother Blanche of Montferrato is regent. March or April – 1490 Ch'ing-yang event, a presumed meteor shower or air burst over Qingyang in Ming dynasty China, said to have caused casualties.

Events  January–March  January 11 – 1693 Sicily earthquake: Mount Etna erupts, causing a devastating earthquake that affects parts of Sicily and Malta. February 8 – The College of William & Mary in Williamsburg, Virginia is granted a Royal charter. March 27 – Bozoklu Mustafa Pasha becomes the new Grand Vizier of the Ottoman Empire, after Sultan Ahmed II appoints him as the successor of Çalık Ali Pasha. April–June  April 4 – Anne Palles becomes the last accused witch to be executed for witchcraft in Denmark, after having been convicted of using powers of sorcery.

Maximilian II (31 July 1527 – 12 October 1576)  was Holy Roman Emperor from 1564 until his death in 1576. A member of the Austrian House of Habsburg, he was crowned King of Bohemia in Prague on 14 May 1562 and elected King of Germany (King of the Romans) on 24 November 1562. On 8 September 1563 he was crowned King of Hungary and Croatia in the Hungarian capital Pressburg (Pozsony in Hungarian; now Bratislava, Slovakia). On 25 July 1564 he succeeded his father Ferdinand I as ruler of the Holy Roman Empire.Maximilian's rule was shaped by the confessionalization process after the 1555 Peace of Augsburg.

Year 1578 (MDLXXVIII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 31 – Battle of Gembloux: Spanish forces under Don John of Austria and Alexander Farnese defeat the Dutch; Farnese begins to recover control of the French-speaking Southern Netherlands. April 27 – The Duel of the Mignons claims the lives of two favorites of Henry III of France, and two favourites of Henry I, Duke of Guise. May 26 – The Alteratie in Amsterdam ends Catholic rule, and open Catholic worship there.

Eric Arthur Heiden (born June 14, 1958) is an American physician and a former long track speed skater, road cyclist and track cyclist. He won an unprecedented five individual gold medals, and set four Olympic records and one world record at the 1980 Winter Olympic Games. Heiden was the most successful athlete at those Olympic Games, single-handedly winning more gold medals than all nations except for the Soviet Union (10) and East Germany (9). He is the most successful Winter Olympian from a single edition of any Winter Olympics. He delivered the Athlete's Oath at those same 1980 Games.

Year 1231 ( MCCXXXI ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Monday. It was used as a unit of measurement in medieval Europe and was the equivalent of a year. The year is also known as a millennium and a diocesan year in Ireland. In medieval times, the year was the basis for reckoning years in the calendars of Scotland, France, the United Kingdom and the Holy Roman Empire. The term 'year' also refers to a calendar year, the calendar year.

Observations show that the expansion of the universe is accelerating , such that the velocity at which a distant galaxy is traveling away from us is increasing by approximately the same amount as the velocity at which it is moving away from us. Since light has a finite wavelength, the distance light has travelled is limited by a limit called the Hubble constant, which is written as

Year 1556 ( MDLVI ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and finishing on the preceding Sunday ( link will display Sunday's calendar if the current week is Monday or Sunday and the current calendar is Sunday's). It is also known as Leap Day. It was used as an unofficial calendar until the year 1564. It was last used on December 30, 1586 at the First Council of Florence. The British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) is the British public service television, radio, and video service, and is headquartered in London, England.

Events  January–June  January 24 – King Charles II of England dissolves the "Cavalier Parliament", after nearly 18 years. February 3 – Moroccan troops from Fez are killed, along with their commander Moussa ben Ahmed ben Youssef, in a battle against rebels in the Jbel Saghro mountain range, but Moroccan Sultan Ismail Ibn Sharif is able to negotiate a ceasefire allowing his remaining troops safe passage back home. February 5 – The Treaty of Celle is signed between France and Sweden on one side, and the Holy Roman Empire, at the town of Celle in Saxony (now in Germany).

OCaml ( , formerly Objective Caml ) is a general-purpose , multi-paradigm programming language which extends the Caml dialect of Common Lisp to support dynamic and strict data types. The language was written in the OCaml programming language, a dialect of Common Lisp, which was itself based on Scheme, a dialect of Lisp. It is widely used for embedded systems development. In mathematics, a Hilbert space  is a category of space  with an element , and an open subset of . The Hilbert space is not an abelian group; for a group , the subgroup  is in .

Events January – March January 7 – In India , Sufi rebel leader Shah Inayat Shaheed from Sindh who had fought under the leadership of his father and uncle, Ahmad Shah Abdali and Shah Abdul Ghafar Shah , is assassinated, triggering an armed revolt in Afghanistan . February 6 – A bomb explodes in New Delhi, India, killing two and injuring more than 100 people; the attack is blamed on Hindu extremists. A computer is a machine whose input and output operations are specified by programs. This includes not only the operations of the machine as an electronic computer, but also the operation of individual programs within that machine.

Year 1442 ( MCDXLII ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Gregorian calendar, but for the Roman Catholic Church (and other Christian churches) began on the Tuesday following Ash Wednesday. It also marked the end of the Thirty-seven Weeks of Daniel, with the Revelation of John appearing on its first Monday.HistoryThe calendar used for the year 1442 was established by a decree of Pope Innocent IV on 28 July 1346, but its name remained unknown at the time of writing until 1450, when the order of the year was fixed by Gregory XIII.

Events  January–June  January 10 – The Royal African Company is granted a Royal Charter by Charles II of England. February – English pirates carry out the sack of Campeche in Mexico. March 4 – The Prince Edward Islands in the sub-antarctic Indian Ocean are discovered by Barent Barentszoon Lam, of the Dutch ship Maerseveen, and named Dina (Prince Edward) and Maerseveen (Marion). March 5 – Emperor Go-Sai's reign ends, and Emperor Reigen ascends to the throne of Japan. March 24 – King Charles II of England issues the Charter of Carolina, establishing the Province of Carolina, and dividing it between eight Lords Proprietors.

A killer is someone or something that kills, such as a murderer or a serial killer. Killer or The Killer may also refer to:Arts, entertainment, and mediaFictional characters Killer (Home and Away), a character from Home and Away Killer Kane, the villain of the 1939 Buck Rogers film serial Ghostface (Scream), aka "The Killer" - the murderer in the Scream movie seriesFilms The Killer (1921 film), an American western film directed by and starring Jack Conway (filmmaker) The Killer (1953 film), a Turkish adventure film Killer!

Niihau ( Hawaiian : ) , anglicized as Niihau , is the westernmost main and seventh largest inhabited island in the Hawaiian archipelago. It is the largest and most prominent of the island chain in the Hawaiian chain of islands, forming a part of its western coast, and lies to the south of Kauai. The New World (from the Latin New,  "new, new" "world") is an area that is now the southwestern hemisphere, bounded by the Atlantic Ocean and the Pacific Ocean to the east, the Indian Ocean to the west, and the Arctic Ocean to the north and south.

Year 1442 (MCDXLII) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March 18–25 – Battle of Hermannstadt: John Hunyadi defeats an army of the Ottoman Empire 80,000 strong, led by Mesid Bey of Vidin, near Sibiu in Transylvania. June 2 – Alfonso of Aragon proclaims himself King of Naples. September – John Hunyadi defeats another army of the Ottoman Empire (70,000 strong), led by Hadım Şehabeddin, Beylerbey (or governor) of Rumelia, near the Ialomița River. Following this, he places Basarab II as ruler of Wallachia.

Year 1340 ( MCCCXL ) was a leap year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) on which the day of the week changed from Saturday to Sunday. In the Greek religion, Zeus  (, ) was the Greek god of the sky, storms and thunder. He was worshipped as a god of thunderstorms and was associated with thunder. Zeus is believed to be the source of thunder and lightning and is considered to be god of war. Zeus also had a role in mythological events. He was the god of justice and the creator of all other deities.

Solidarity Electoral Action ( , AWS ) was a political coalition in Poland . Since 1997 , its official name was Democratic Left Alliance of the South (DLA Sącz), and it was a coalition of the Democratic Left Solidarity (LSD), the Left Alliance (LA) and the New Right (NRW), or "New Right".The DLA Sącz was headed by former prime minister Donald Tusk and led the Polish government in the early years of the current Polish government of Donald Tusk, now the President of Poland since 2014.

Year 1434 (MCDXXXIV) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  April 14 – The foundation stone of Nantes Cathedral in Nantes, France, is laid. May 30 – Hussite Wars – Battle of Lipany: The Catholics and Ultraquists defeat the Taborites, ending the Hussite Wars. June 19 or 20 – Zara Yaqob becomes Emperor of Ethiopia. Late June – Miner Engelbrekt Engelbrektsson begins a Swedish rebellion against King Eric of Pomerania (named the Engelbrekt rebellion after him), eventually leading to the deposition of the king.

The Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse (often referred to as the Four Horsemen) are figures in Christian religion, first appearing in the Old Testament's prophetic Book of Zechariah and in the Book of Ezekiel, where they are named as punishments from God, and later in the New Testament's final book, Revelation, an apocalypse written by John of Patmos.Revelation 6 tells of a book or scroll in God's right hand that is sealed with seven seals. The Lamb of God/Lion of Judah opens the first four of the seven seals, which summons four beings that ride out on white, red, black, and pale horses.

Jon Howard Appleton (January 4, 1939 – January 30, 2022) was an American composer, an educator and a pioneer in electro-acoustic music. His earliest compositions in the medium, e.g. "Chef d'Oeuvre" and "Newark Airport Rock" (1967) attracted attention because they established a new tradition some have called programmatic electronic music. In 1970, he won Guggenheim, Fulbright and American-Scandinavian Foundation fellowships. When he was twenty-eight years old, he joined the faculty of Dartmouth College where he established one of the first electronic music studios in the United States.

Symbiosis ( from Greek , , `` living together '' , from , , `` together '' , and , "together") was the reciprocal association of individual organisms. Symbiosis may be defined in terms of the ability of two species to exchange genes or other resources, or a symbiont may form with a host organism. It may occur via asexual or sexual reproduction or may result from symbiosis with another species of similar nature. Symbioses range from the simplest organisms to the most complex. Strawberries are a member of the rutabagas family of flowering plant.

The Motorola MC68010 processor is a 16/32-bit microprocessor from Motorola , released in 1982 as the successor to the Motorola 68000. It is one of the two remaining Motorola MC68000 family microprocessors. In quantum mechanics, a Bohmian mechanics is the description of a particle as a wave with a definite time-dependent amplitude and frequency. It is often used to describe electron-positron pair excitation in atomic hydrogen, in which there is a wavefunction with definite period and definite phase. A Bohmian model is sometimes called a wave function, and the wavefunction can be described by a wave equation.

Year 1239 (MCCXXXIX) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Summer – A German expeditionary force under Emperor Frederick II invades the Romagna and Tuscany, hoping to capture Rome. He appoints his 21-year-old son, Enzo of Sardinia, as imperial vicar general for Northern Italy. Frederick also threatens with war against Venice, who has sent ships to blockade the harbors on Sicily. In order to finance his growing need for arms, he institutes an administrative reorganization of the Holy Roman Empire (among others, the formation of 10 vice regencies in Italy).

The 8th century BCE started the first day of 800 BC and ended the last day of 701 BC. The 8th century BC is a period of great change for several historically significant civilizations. In Egypt, the 23rd and 24th dynasties lead to rule from Nubia in the 25th Dynasty. The Neo-Assyrian Empire reaches the peak of its power,  conquering the Kingdom of Israel as well as nearby countries.Greece colonizes other regions of the Mediterranean Sea and Black Sea. Rome is founded in 753 BC, and the Etruscan civilization expands in Italy.

Dari (, , ), or Dari Persian , is a political term used for the various dialects of the Persian language spoken in Afghanistan. Dari is the term officially recognised and promoted since 1964 by the Afghan government for the Persian language, hence it is known as Afghan Persian or Eastern Persian in many Western sources. As Professor Nile Green remarks "the impulses behind renaming of Afghan Persian as Dari were more nationalistic than linguistic" in order to create an Afghan state narrative. Persian in Afghanistan is generally called Fārsi (فارسی) by Persian-speakers and Pārsi (پارسی) by ethnic Pashtuns.

Events June 16 – The deposed and imprisoned Mary , Queen of Scots , recognizes Philip II of Spain as king of Great Britain and the Holy Roman Empire, a position he retains until the Treaty of Utrecht , signed by Mary and Philip in June 1559. The modern world is a collection of states that began to exist in Europe around 1500 CE. In the process of coming together, the European countries that would form the modern states developed distinctive cultures, political systems, economies, and cultures, as well as histories and cultures that developed from the earliest migrations into and from Europe.

Heinrich Christian Wilhelm Busch ( 15 April 1832 – 9 January 1908 ) was a German humorist , poet , essayist, playwright and writer. He is one of the best-known German cartoonists of the nineteenth and twentieth centuries.Busch first gained widespread notice in 1851, when he satirized Karl Maria Wiehm, one of Germany's most influential statesmen at the time, and became well-known during his career.In the 1860s, he was the principal illustrator of Punch magazine in London, and was among the few comic artists in that era to become internationally known.Early lifeBiologyBusch was born into a family of musicians, in Koln, West Prussia.

Year 1413 ( MCDXIII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) which began in the Gregorian calendar with a leap year of March 1414.
is the name of at least five planets (Mercury, Venus, Mars, Jupiter, Saturn) or comets, and the first planet in our Solar System to acquire such a name. Mercury, first observed by the Italian astronomer Pio Pico in 1478, was named after the Roman goddess of wisdom. The Latin name Mars means "little god" or "god of war", and is a derivation of the Latin Mater Marsi.

Louis the Roman ( 7 May 1328 – 17 May 1365 ) was the eldest son of Holy Roman Emperor Henry IV, who ruled from 1399 until his death. He was the only son of Emperor Conrad III, who had been killed in 1362 and left no surviving heir. He succeeded his older brother Louis III as Emperor of the Holy Roman Empire. In quantum field theory, a quantum field is a region of space that is characterized by a nonzero field theory vector, whose magnitude is determined by the nonzero Hamiltonian. This field can be characterized by a field vector, a quantum field operator, or both.

Year 1510 ( MDX ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the year 1510, which was also known by the Roman year of the Emperor Julian II as MDXII. It is named after Pope Gregory XIII as a successor of Julian II.HistoryThe new year began with Pope Paul III's proclamation on 8 January 1510 that all Roman citizens were required to celebrate the feast of Saturnalia. On 30 January 1510 Pope Pius VII confirmed the decree of Pope Paul III, while on 14 March 1510 Pius VIII confirmed Pope Paul III's decree.

Jochem Simon Uytdehaage ( born 9 July 1976 ) is a Dutch former long track speed skater who won two Winter Olympics gold medals for the Dutch team in Lillehammer and Salt Lake City, as well as six World Championships medals. He is the only Winter Olympic skater from a non-European country to have won a medal in multiple Winter Olympics events. He also won two world records in his career.In the 2012 Olympics, he became the youngest athlete to win three World Championship gold medals in his career, while he won the silver medal in Lillehammer, with a time of 5 minutes, 5.57 seconds.

Year 1162 (MCLXII) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  March 6 – German forces, led by Emperor Frederick I (Barbarossa), capture Milan; much of the city is destroyed three weeks later, on the emperor's orders. The fortifications are demolished, and the churches are destroyed. The population is dispersed, and the commune abolished. The fate of Milan leads to the submission of Brescia, Piacenza, and many other northern Italian cities.

The Battle of the Teutoburg Forest , described as the Varian Disaster by Roman historians , took place at modern-day Odenwalde in the Teutoburg-Ruhr region of central Germany on 28 September 1813. It is the worst single-day loss of life during the Thirty Years' War and the first major battle to be fought on the Eastern Front.After an attack by the Prussian Army on the Polish town of Wagram (now Wroclaw), the Austro-German forces launched a counter-attack to regain their lost ground. The Austro-Germans were able to regain the initiative and drive the Prussian force back, with some troops even crossing the Danube into Austro-Hungary in the process.

Pearl Harbour is a small harbour at the head of the Waiau River , in the town of Manapouri on the west coast of New Zealand's North Island.The harbour is one of the few places in North Island that can be reached directly from Parnell Highway, the main road that crosses the Waianua River. A small ferry service to Manapouri operates year round, from early May to late October . It is a popular fishing and tourism destination. Buddhist temples were built around the fourth century in the Indian subcontinent. Buddhist architecture has become one of the major expressions of India's distinctive style as the dominant religion of South Asia.

Year 1342 ( MCCCXLII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Christian calendar of the Eastern Roman Empire, in use since 752. It is the twelfth of twelve months, and the fifteenth of the twenty-six year-long cycle of the Julian calendar, which was adopted by the Eastern Roman Empire following the reforms of Julius II in AD 313. The Julian calendar was replaced in the West with the Coptic calendar on 31 October 1582. The first year in the Common Era was 1452, when the Emperor Constantine converted to Christianity.

In the Swedish calendar it was a leap year starting on Wednesday , one day ahead of the Julian and Gregorian calendars. It was celebrated by a public celebration at the Cathedral of Stockholm in the spring, on May 11, 1453. The festival is also celebrated annually on December 25 in the year 498, after which the celebration of St. Magnus on January 12th is celebrated. This article is about an in-universe event that took place in a certain fictional universe in the Fallout video game series created by Bethesda Softworks. In this game, the Big Empty has been empty for roughly 15 years.

Abolitionism , or the abolitionist movement , was the movement to end slavery . In Western Europe and the Americas, the movement originated in the late 17th century and led to widespread abolitionist campaigns in Britain, Ireland, the United States, the United States of America, Canada and South Africa. The  is the ninth and ninth-ranked supermassive black hole in the night sky, according to the International Astronomical Union's list of supermassive black hole candidates. It is the second-largest black hole in the Milky Way, after M81 (or the Sagittarius arm), and is about 30 times larger than the Sun.

The Witan , literally `` wise men '' , was the king 's council in Anglo-Saxon England from before the Norman conquest through the Norman period. The group was responsible for the selection of kings and for all important decisions. Wisdom (also wisdom and wisdom ) is a state of knowledge or of understanding. In ancient societies wisdom was thought to be associated with the capacity to discern, understand, and apply knowledge and skills. The word came from the Ancient Greek, μυστός ,  to know, πολιτεύση,  to know the reasons. Wine is a spirit distilled from the grape by fermentation in a number of alcoholic beverages.

Year 1350 ( MCCCL ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) in 1350 in the Gregorian calendar of the Roman Catholic Church; it is also known as the Year of Faith. It was the first year on which the Pope of Rome proclaimed a universal Roman Catholic calendar. It marked the transition to the modern calendar from the Julian calendar and the new year of the Gregorian Church.The Year of Faith, as it was known from 1350, had a fixed day of celebration in the ecclesiastical year.

The Æsir ( Old Norse : ) are the gods of the principal pantheon in Norse religion . They include Thor, the god of thunder; Baldr, the god of wisdom; Freya (or Freya-Grímnismál; Old Icelandic ; modern: Grímnismál; "Grímnist" in Old Icelandic; "Lord of Wisdom", "Wisdom" in modern Scandinavian) and Loki, the god of mischief, mischief-making, mischief-making magic, and mischief. They are usually depicted as being bearded and having long hair that is either unkempt or closely cropped.

Ski jumping is a winter sport in which competitors aim to achieve the farthest jump after sliding down on their hands, feet and/or skis while standing on a log with the skis in their hands, or with their feet and/or skis in the snow. It is considered the equivalent of skiing, but less technical and less risky.The sport evolved from snow jumping, a form of ski jumping involving a long skis, not skis on a long ski jump. Kaballah,  in Arabic, is a political movement within the Zionist movement for the establishment of an independent Palestinian state in the Middle East.

Dissociative identity disorder (DID), previously known as multiple personality disorder (MPD), is a mental disorder characterized by the maintenance of at least two distinct and relatively enduring personality states. The disorder is accompanied by memory gaps beyond what would be explained by ordinary memory issues. The personality states alternately show in a person's behavior; however, presentations of the disorder vary. Other conditions that often occur in people with DID include post-traumatic stress disorder, personality disorders (especially borderline and avoidant), depression, substance use disorders, conversion disorder, somatic symptom disorder, eating disorders, obsessive–compulsive disorder, and sleep disorders.

The French and Indian War ( 1754–1763 ) was a theater of the Seven Years ' War , which pitted France against England and the Netherlands, and led to the establishment of many new colonies in the West Indies, North America, and South America, including the territories of Louisiana, West Florida and Florida. It was a conflict of French colonial expansion and Anglo-French wars in the French West Indies and Caribbean. The war began in November 1754, when an alliance of Britain, the Netherlands, and their Dutch and Spanish allies invaded the French colony of Saint Domingue.

Berchtesgaden  is a municipality in the district Berchtesgadener Land, Bavaria, in southeastern Germany, near the border with Austria,  south of Salzburg and  southeast of Munich. It lies in the Berchtesgaden Alps, south of Berchtesgaden; the Berchtesgaden National Park stretches along three parallel valleys.The Kehlstein mountain , with its Kehlsteinhaus (Eagle's Nest) is located in the area.EtymologyBerchtesgaden, Upper Bavaria (Achental), earlier Perchterscadmen, Perhtersgadem, Berchirchsgadem, Berchtoldesgadem; the word underwent a Latin distortion of Old High German parach, Romance bareca 'hay shed'.

Year 1392 (MCCCXCII) was a leap year starting on Monday (link will display full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  June 13 – An assassination attempt by Pierre de Craon against Olivier de Clisson, Constable of France, fails. August 5 General Yi Seong-gye crowns himself Taejo of Joseon, ending the Goryeo Dynasty in the Korean Peninsula, and establishing the Joseon Dynasty, which will last for more than 500 years. Charles VI of France (later known as "Charles the Mad") suffers a serious bout of psychosis, which will continue throughout his life.

Year 1361 ( MCCCLXI ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) in March in the Roman Catholic and Eastern Orthodox Church calendars. In music theory, a chromatic scale or harmonic scale (also called chromatic major or minor scale) is a scale of three or more notes, which are each a different pitch within a scale. Each of the notes can be sung or played as its own note. Some chromatic scales are more commonly called harmonic minor or major scales, but there are also chromatic scales called melodic minor or harmonic major, which have only minor thirds and major thirds.

Sigismund (26 October 1427 – 4 March 1496), a member of the House of Habsburg, was Duke of Austria from 1439 (elevated to Archduke in 1477) until his death. As a scion of the Habsburg Leopoldian line, he ruled over Further Austria and the County of Tyrol from 1446 until his resignation in 1490.BiographySigismund (or Siegmund, sometimes also spelled Sigmund) was born at the Tyrolean court in Innsbruck; his parents were the Further Austrian duke Frederick IV of Austria and his second wife , a daughter of the Welf duke Frederick I of Brunswick-Lüneburg.

Year 1037 ( MXXXVII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Monday. In computing, a hash function is a type of mathematical function that can be used to transform a string of data into a digest of a fixed-size key. Hash functions are used to ensure that the original data was never altered and to verify that the modified data has not been changed after being encrypted, without revealing its original contents.Hash functions are one of many cryptographic tools used in encryption, data integrity, and data verification.

The Air Ministry was a department of the Government of the United Kingdom with the responsibility of managing the affairs of the Royal Air Force, that existed from 1918 to 1964. It was under the political authority of the Secretary of State for Air.Organisations before the Air MinistryThe Air CommitteeOn 13 April 1912, less than two weeks after the creation of the Royal Flying Corps (which initially consisted of both a naval and a military wing), an Air Committee was established to act as an intermediary between the Admiralty and the War Office in matters relating to aviation.

Year 1047 ( MXLVII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Sunday, 1 December. At its end, a new year began on the first Monday following the last Wednesday of October. The calendar is also used to represent the Julian Calendar. A calendar, also known as a calendar system, is an arrangement of a year consisting of fixed days that are arranged according to a fixed cycle. It is a system of timekeeping in which the year has no inherent length and, therefore, it represents an approximation to a single day in time.

Year 1235 (MCCXXXV) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  Connacht in Ireland is finally conquered by the Hiberno-Norman Richard Mór de Burgh; Felim Ua Conchobair is expelled. A general inquisition begins in France. The Byzantine emperor John III Doukas Vatatzes and the Bulgarian tsar Ivan Asen II besiege Constantinople, in an attempt to take it from its Latin rulers, John of Brienne and Baldwin II. Angelo Sanudo successfully negotiates a two-year truce. Elizabeth of Hungary (d. 1231) is canonized, by Pope Gregory IX.

Mariner-H (Mariner Mars '71), also commonly known as Mariner 8, was (along with Mariner 9) part of the Mariner Mars '71 project. It was intended to go into Mars orbit and return images and data, but a launch vehicle failure prevented Mariner 8 from achieving Earth orbit and the spacecraft reentered into the Atlantic Ocean shortly after launch.MissionMariner 8 was launched on an Atlas-Centaur SLV-3C booster (AC-24). The main Centaur engine was ignited 265 seconds after launch, but the upper stage began to oscillate in pitch and tumbled out of control.

Year 1575 ( MDLXXV ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) that had three leap years. The Great Library of Alexandria was a massive collection of the world's great works of classical literature, from the Greek and Roman classics up to the Middle Ages. It was built between AD 486 and 484, and became one of the greatest libraries in the known world, but it has also been called the world's biggest museum.

Year 1175 (MCLXXV) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  England  King Henry II begins living openly with his mistress Rosamund Clifford, raising suspicions about their relationship and alienating Henry's wife, Queen Eleanor of Aquitaine. Eleanor of Aquitaine is held under house arrest at Old Sarum Castle in Wiltshire. She is kept in comfort there – fine clothes for her are dispatched regularly from London. Treaty of Windsor: High King Ruaidrí Ua Conchobair (or Roderic O'Conner) relinquishes his title and agrees to submit to Henry II as vassal of Connacht in Ireland.

Year 1443 (MCDXLIII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events <onlyinclude>January–December  July 22 – Battle of St. Jakob an der Sihl (Old Zürich War): The forces of the city of Zürich are defeated, but the Swiss Confederacy have insufficient strength to besiege and take the city. November 8 – Battle of Niš: John Hunyadi and the army of the Crusade of Varna defeat three armies of the Ottoman Empire, and capture the city of Niš in modern-day Serbia; Skanderbeg deserts the Ottoman camp and goes to Albania.

Year 1409 (MCDIX) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 1 – The Welsh surrender Harlech Castle to the English. March 25 – The Council of Pisa opens. On June 5 it deposes Pope Gregory XII and Antipope Benedict XIII, and on June 26 crowns Petros Philargos as Pope Alexander V; he is subsequently regarded as an antipope. July – Martin I of Aragon succeeds his own son, as King of Sicily. August 7 – The Council of Pisa closes. December 2 – The University of Leipzig opens.

The 1988 United States presidential election was the 51st quadrennial presidential election , held on Tuesday , November 8 , 1988. John Anderson was elected as the winner of the Democratic Party primary on March 22, 1988, defeating incumbent Vice President Walter Mondale, who had been elected the Democratic Party candidate the previous week after a long and bitter primary battle that began in December 1987 and continued through March 1988. American football is an American sport in which the players are divided into two teams with opposing teams of eleven players on each side of a field with a goal at each end.

A Tesla coil is an electrical resonant transformer circuit designed by inventor Nikola Tesla in 1891 . It is used as a frequency-controlled oscillator (FCO) that can be tuned to produce a wide range of frequency-independent signals. The resonant frequency of a coil is the resonance frequency of the circuit. Tesla coils can be used for many types of purposes including power transmission, medical imaging, communication, and surveillance. The first human-made object to be propelled by rockets was the first stage of the first American manned spacecraft , the United States' Mercury capsule.

Year 1444 ( MCDXLIV ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Gregorian calendar. It happened on the  th day of  November. It is also known as the Great Leap Year because of the political turmoil it caused in China. For a full history of the Great Leap Forward, including how it happened, see Wikipedia's entry . In biology, the chromosome (plural, chromosomes) or ploidy (plural ploidies; Latin, plōrum, plural plōridēs) is a long chain of repetitive DNA segments that constitutes a cell's genetic material.

Year 1132 ( MCXXXII ) was a leap year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) and lasting for 31 days, except for the first year of 1337. It is the second-least-commonly observed of all leap years, and is the least common after the year 1111.The first Leap Year (MCXXXIII, 1331) was observed on the 1st February, 1382. In computer science, a process model is a computational model of a machine, in this case a computer's memory, processor, or both, that specifies all of the operations that can possibly be executed.

Political identity came to the territory now occupied by the Principality of Liechtenstein in 814 , with the formation of the Liechtenstein Empire. In 915, a short-lived succession crisis over the succession of the Principality of Liechtenstein to the Austrian Habsburgs led to the assassination by the Habsburgs of Prince Ludwig I of Liechtenstein, who refused to become the heir apparent of the Austrian throne. Following this incident, the Principality became part of the Holy Roman Empire. Liechtenstein then remained part of the Holy Roman Empire until 1797 when it joined the German Confederation. In computer science, virtual memory is the memory architecture used in computer systems.

Events January–March January 5 – The Brandenburger—African Company , of the German state of Brandenburg , signs a greaty with the United States . Brussels Airport, which is the largest in the European Union (EU) and the ninth-busiest worldwide, is a municipal airport located in Brussels Airport District. Brussels Airport is a hub for international airlines, European airlines, and some national airlines as well as one of the main transport hubs for Belgium. The airport is located on the northern edge of Brussels, close to both the train station and Molenbeek, Belgium's largest district.

Year 1185 ( MCLXXXV ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the 12th century. It was the year in the Julian calendar (as opposed to Gregorian or Roman calendars) which has the greatest number of leap years.The Julian calendar is the calendar adopted throughout much of the Christian world from the year 354 AD to the year 1492 A.D. The Roman calendar, however, was gradually adopted in Europe until the 18th century. Johann Wolfgang von Goethe (; 21 August 1749 – 23 February 1832) was a German Romantic writer.

The Mattachine Society , founded in 1950, was an early national gay rights organization in the United States, perhaps preceded only by Chicago's Society for Human Rights. Communist and labor activist Harry Hay formed the group with a collection of male friends in Los Angeles to protect and improve the rights of gay men. Branches formed in other cities, and by 1961 the Society had splintered into regional groups.At the beginning of gay rights protest, news on Cuban prison work camps for homosexuals inspired Mattachine Society to organize protests at the United Nations and the White House in 1965.Founding Harry Hay conceived the idea of a gay activist group in 1948.

Year 1432 ( MCDXXXII ) was a leap year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Monday ( link will display a full week of the leap year's days). A leap year was celebrated on a Friday and a Saturday for most of the year. The years before 1430, and even before 1422, were Leap Years because the first two digits of both years were zero, and it was assumed that that was the normal number of days to count from leap year to normal year.

Three bobsleigh events were competed at the 2002 Winter Olympics, at Utah Olympic Park. The competition took place between February 16 and February 23, 2002.For the first time since 1932, Olympic bobsleigh added a new event, with the first ever women's competition, won by Jill Bakken and  Vonetta Flowers of the United States.The competitions comprised four heats. Teams raced in the first and third heats in the order of the draw. The second heat was raced in order of ranking after the first heat, and the fourth heat is raced in order of the ranking after the first three heats.

Albury–Wodonga is the broad settlement incorporating the twin Australian cities of Albury and Wodonga , which are separated geographically by the Great Dividing Range.Wodonga is located on the south coast of the Australian continent, on the south bank of the River Murray.Wodonga is Australia's largest city and third-most populous municipality, after Sydney and Melbourne . It is located on an elevated peninsula at the confluence of the Wodonga and Clarence Rivers. It is approximately 1,000 km (660 mi) north of Albury.Albury is situated on the opposite side of the river, on the north bank.

Year 1303 ( MCCCIII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Julian calendar, the Gregorian calendar, and the Islamic calendar. It was designated 1330 by Pope Julius II, and 1331 by the Pope Gregory XIII. The year 1330 was declared to be the start date of the Gregorian calendar as the new Julian calendar year began with the Monday of the month of February. The last week of November, 1332, is often designated as the anniversary of the year 1330.

A shank is a type of knot that is used to shorten a rope or take up slack , such as a fishing line or a parachute cord. Shanks were commonly used by fishermen as a back-up for the end of the line when the main strand failed. Some fishermen, particularly in the maritime trades, would cut off the end of a rope with a single shank on the line, and tie on a new, shorter one by pulling down the original knot with one hand while slipping the shank over the original and pulling the knot back up with the other hand.

Year 1570 ( MDLXX ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) or Wednesday in a Gregorian calendar system. A calendar is a record of time, usually of some length, for a particular calendar year. Calendars can be in two basic types: solar and lunar. In either case, a calendar includes the months and day numbers of each year. It is an attempt to define a sequence of days in a particular period, or to determine that sequence from the observation of astronomical phenomena (such as the phases of the moon).

In probability theory, the central limit theorem (CLT) establishes that, in many situations, when independent random variables are summed up, their properly normalized sum tends toward a normal distribution (informally a bell curve) even if the original variables themselves are not normally distributed. The theorem is a key concept in probability theory because it implies that probabilistic and statistical methods that work for normal distributions can be applicable to many problems involving other types of distributions. This theorem has seen many changes during the formal development of probability theory.

Year 990 (CMXC) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Al-Mansur, de facto ruler of Al-Andalus, conquers the Castle of Montemor-o-Velho (modern Portugal), expanding the Umayyad Caliphate of Córdoba. The city of Lund, Sweden is founded, during the reign of the Danish king Sweyn Forkbeard (approximate date). Africa  The Ghana Empire takes the Berber town of Aoudaghost (modern Mauritania) as the West African nation makes further gains. Construction of the Al-Hakim Mosque by orders of the Fatimid vizier Gawar Al-Siqilli begins in Cairo (modern Egypt).

Year 1347 (MCCCXLVII) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar, and a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Proleptic Gregorian calendar.Events  January–December  January 26 – Charles University in Prague is founded by a bull issued by Pope Clement VI at the request of Charles I, King of Bohemia. February 2 – The Byzantine civil war of 1341–1347 between John VI Kantakouzenos and the regency for John V Palaiologos ends with Kantakouzenos entering Constantinople. April – The Knights Hospitaller defeat a Turkish fleet, and sink 100 ships off Imbros.

Leisure Suit Larry is an adult-themed video game series created by Al Lowe . It was published by Sierra from 1995 to 1998, after which it was absorbed by Activision. The first three games in the series were made by Sierra and released in 1995, 1996, and 1997 respectively. The fourth title was released in 2000, with an English translation, and the fifth, The Lost Generation, was released in 2002. Larry series has over 25 million copies in print worldwide as of 2011.The series consists of 12 games, with the sixth released in 2000.

Year 1037 (MXXXVII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Spring – A revolt in northern Italy is started by Archbishop Aribert of Milan. King Henry III (eldest son of Emperor Conrad II) travels south of the Alps to quell it. February – At an Imperial Diet in Pavia (assembled by Conrad II), Aribert is accused of fomenting a revolt against the Holy Roman Empire, Conrad orders his arrest. May – Conrad II, with Pavian assistance, lays siege to Milan at the Porta Romana side, but the city holds out.

Year 1290 (MCCXC) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Year without winter – Exceptionally rare instance of uninterrupted transition, from autumn 1289 to the following spring, in Great Britain and mainland western Europe. March 1 – The University of Coimbra is founded in Lisbon, Portugal by King Denis of Portugal; it moves to Coimbra in 1308. July 10 – Ladislaus IV of Hungary is assassinated by three Cumans (Árbóc, Törtel and Kemence), at the castle of Körösszeg (modern-day Cheresig) in Romania.

Events January–June March – The Synod of Jerusalem brings together bishops and representatives from the whole of Eastern Orthodox Christendom to discuss questions of Christian doctrine, spirituality, liturgy, and liturgical renewal. October–March April–December The Council of Chalcedon brings together bishops of Eastern and Western Churches to discuss important doctrinal issues, such as the role of the Pope and the primacy of jurisdiction. November–January The Third Ecumenical Council, also known as the Second Lambeth Conference, brings together bishops, representatives from many other churches, and scholars to discuss the issues of concordance, communion, and the nature of the Christian church.

Year 1175 ( MCLXXV ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) on 1 January 1201. The year was named after Edward I, King of England. The Algarves (; , ) are a group of four coastal regions in southern Portugal, and are the smallest autonomous region in the Portugal. It is situated between the Mediterranean Sea and the Atlantic Ocean. The Algarves consist of the provinces of Algarve and Faro. The Algarves have a population of around 1.3 million in the year 2017, of which around 1.2 million live in the province of Algarve.

Year 1527 ( MDXXVII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) with the day of Sunday as 1 and the day of Thursday as 1 . The month is divided into two months, December (1) and January (2) . In chemistry, a compound is a naturally occurring mixture of one or more compounds. Compounds may be compounds in which a single element or group is the only (or only one) of the compounds. Compounds may also include combinations of two or more compounds.

Year 993 ( CMXCIII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Gregorian calendar ( link will display the full calendar ) in use in the European Commonwealth from 1864.HistoryThe common year date was first mentioned in John Milton's Paradise Lost (1667) when Milton writes the word "common-years" in italics. The Common Market , sometimes also referred to as the European Community , or Eur-Europe , is an intergovernmental organization in Europe consisting of 28 European countries (the countries of the European Union) and the European Commission.

CBE may refer to : Travel CBE , IATA code for Greater Cumberland Regional Airport . CBE , ICAO code for Greater Cumberland Airport , is a private aviation facility that is located on the shores of the River Fens in Cumberland, England. Carnegie Mellon University (CMU; pronounced [kɔrnəm ɔ ndʒɛn ɐ] ;  , pronounced [kɔrnəm ɔ ɔ̀n] ), founded in 1895 as Carnegie Institute of Technology, is an American public research university and research institution in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania. It was named for industrialist and philanthropist Andrew Carnegie in honor of his contributions to public education and to the arts.

Business is the activity of making one's living or making money by producing or buying and selling products (such as goods and services). Simply put, it is "any activity or enterprise entered into for profit. "Having a business name does not separate the business entity from the owner, which means that the owner of the business is responsible and liable for debts incurred by the business. If the business acquires debts, the creditors can go after the owner's personal possessions. A business structure does not allow for corporate tax rates.

Year 1427 (MCDXXVII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January – Spring – Radu II of Wallachia resumes the throne for the fourth time, but a seven-year struggle for it ends when he is defeated in battle, and probably killed, by Dan II, who resumes the throne for a fifth term. April – The House of Balsic's rule of Montenegro comes to an end with the death of Balša III. August 4 – Hussite Wars: Battle of Tachov – The Hussites decisively beat the crusader armies, ending the Fourth Anti-Hussite Crusade.

Year 1332 ( MCCCXXXII ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in 1332, the year after Pope Alexander VI abdicated on March 10, 1331 and was succeeded by Alexander V. The full-year date was January 15, 1332.1332-1333March 26, 1333Alexander V reigned until his death, which occurred on September 15, 1335. El Dorado is the fictional country that appears in the works of Spanish writer Miguel de Cervantes. It is known as the land of Gold and its capital is called La Mancha.

Year 1230 (MCCXXX) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  March 9 – Battle of Klokotnitsa: Byzantine forces under Theodore Komnenos (Doukas) invade Bulgaria, breaking the peace treaty with Tsar Ivan Asen II. Theodore gathers a large army, including western mercenaries. The two armies meet near the village of Klokotnitsa. Ivan applies clever tactics and manages to surround the Byzantines. They are completely defeated, only a small force under Theodore's brother Manuel Doukas manages to escape the battlefield.

Year 994 (CMXCIV) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  September 15 – Battle of the Orontes: Fatimid forces, under Turkish general Manjutakin (also the governor of Damascus), besiege Apamea (modern Syria). Emperor Basil II sends a Byzantine expeditionary army, led by Dux Michael Bourtzes, to relieve the city in alliance with the Hamdanid Dynasty. Manjutakin defeats with his forces the Hamdanids, and attacks the Byzantine force in the rear. The Byzantine army panics and flees, losing some 5,000 men in the process.

Year 1325 ( MCCCXXV ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Sunday, December 25, 1327. In the Middle Ages, each Christian region used a common day of rest between Monday and Saturday: Monday was the beginning day of the week, Saturday was the end day of the week, and each region was allotted a day in its own week, which it designated with a letter. For example, the  was reserved for those regions that kept the Latin calendar, and so had a Wednesday and Friday.

Year 1176 (MCLXXVI) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Summer – Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos) assembles a Byzantine expeditionary force and marches towards Iconium the Seljuk capital. Meanwhile, hordes of Seljuk Turks destroy crops and poison water supplies, to make Manuel's march more difficult, and harass the Byzantine army in order to force it into the Meander valley. Kilij Arslan II, ruler of the Sultanate of Rum, hears of the expedition and sends envoys to ask for peace.

Year 1140 ( MCXL ) was a leap year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) in October in the Gregorian calendar. In mathematics, a matrix (also called a vector field or a vector space ) is an ordered set of vectors that can be indexed and manipulated independently of each other. Matrices are commonly represented by vectors, but there are many other types.The term matrix (from Latin matrixum ) is also used to refer to an algebraic expression that is a vector, for instance: a matrix is an adjoint of the matrix multiplication.

Albert III ( 9 November 141411 March 1486 ) was Elector of Brandenburg from 1471 until his death , the youngest of the Holy Roman Emperors from 1481 until his accession in 1486. Germanic languages, collectively known as Germanic languages, include Old Norse, Old Saxon, Old English, Old High German, Middle High German, and Modern German. According to the Merriam-Webster's Third Collegiate Dictionary (1995), English is considered to be the oldest language in the Germanic family, having evolved from Proto-Germanic. In contrast to many of its Germanic cousins, the Germanic languages are not mutually intelligible within the group.

Mariner 3 (together with Mariner 4 known as Mariner-Mars 1964) was one of two identical deep-space probes designed and built by the Jet Propulsion Laboratory (JPL) for NASA's Mariner-Mars 1964 project that were intended to conduct close-up (flyby) scientific observations of the planet Mars and transmit information on interplanetary space and the space surrounding Mars, televised images of the Martian surface and radio occultation data of spacecraft signals as affected by the Martian atmosphere back to Earth.Although the launch was initially successful, there was a separation issue and Mariner 3 stopped responding when its batteries ran out of power.

Events January–March January 7 – the Republic of Genoa forbids the unauthorized printing of newspapers and all handwriten newssheets . March 3 – the Constitutional Court rules in favor of a motion for a public referendum on a constitutional change that would allow the president to declare a state of emergency for up to 60 days. The Federal Constitution of the United States of America (Constitution) is a political constitution of the United States. The constitution was first adopted in 1787 and revised over several cycles of debate and legislation before being approved by the people as the first United States Constitution on November 15, 1789.

Electroporation , or electropermeabilization , is a microbiology technique in which an electrical field is applied to cells in order to induce a biological reaction, the desired effect being that of forming hydrogels and biofilms. The field is applied with sufficient voltage that the resulting chemical reaction can be observed and measured.The electropermeability of a cell membrane depends on its electrochemical properties (e.g. electrochemical gradient and ionic potential). Elvis Costello is one of the most influential musicians of all-time. His musical genius was evident from early childhood, and he performed at a very young age.

Year 1401 ( MCDI ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) which was considered the start of the Year of the Pig. A common year was also a month (MCDM), in which it overlapped the Gregorian calendar year with the preceding year, as a result of the Julian and Gregorian calendars not using leap years.A year began on the day after  , and ended the day after .The  day was the same as the preceding year. For example, in 1401/1402 the calendar year was  years.

Year 1317 ( MCCCXVII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the 13th century in the Eastern Orthodox Churches, Western Patriarchates of Antioch, Jerusalem, Egypt, Lebanon and the Syrian Orthodox Church, and Eastern Orthodoxy in general. It was also observed in a number of smaller communities.The year 1317 was the first year to be observed in the Eastern Orthodox Church, but the first year to be observed in Western Orthodoxy (as distinct from Russia). It was observed by a number of small communities throughout the Byzantine Empire (including Constantinople and Alexandria) as early as 1318.

The Laboratory for Atmospheric and Space Physics (LASP) is a research organization at the University of Colorado Boulder. LASP is a research institute with over one hundred research scientists ranging in fields from solar influences, to Earth's and other planetary atmospherics processes, space weather, space plasma and dusty plasma physics. LASP has advanced technical capabilities specializing in designing, building, and operating spacecraft and spacecraft instruments.HistoryFounded after World War II, the first scientific instruments built at LASP were launched into space using captured German V-2 rockets. To this day LASP continues a suborbital rocket program through periodic calibration instrument flights from White Sands Missile Range.

Observations show that the expansion of the universe is accelerating, such that the velocity at which a distant galaxy recedes from the observer is continuously increasing with time.The accelerated expansion was discovered during 1998, by two independent projects, the Supernova Cosmology Project and the High-Z Supernova Search Team, which both used distant type Ia supernovae to measure the acceleration. The idea was that as type Ia supernovae have almost the same intrinsic brightness (a standard candle), and since objects that are further away appear dimmer, we can use the observed brightness of these supernovae to measure the distance to them.

Edmund of Abingdon (also known as  Edmund Rich, St Edmund of Canterbury, Edmund of Pontigny, French: St Edme; c. 11741240) was an English-born prelate who served as Archbishop of Canterbury. He became a respected lecturer in mathematics, dialectics and theology at the Universities of Paris and Oxford, promoting the study of Aristotle. Having already an unsought reputation as an ascetic, he was ordained a priest, took a doctorate in divinity and soon became known not only for his lectures on theology but as a popular preacher, spending long years travelling within England, and engaging in 1227 preaching the sixth crusade.

Moore's law is the observation that the number of transistors in a dense integrated circuit (IC) doubles about every two years. Moore's law is an observation and projection of a historical trend. Rather than a law of physics, it is an empirical relationship linked to gains from experience in production.The observation is named after Gordon Moore, the co-founder of Fairchild Semiconductor and Intel (and former CEO of the latter), who in 1965 posited a doubling every year in the number of components per integrated circuit, and projected this rate of growth would continue for at least another decade.

Year 1472 ( MCDLXXII ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) . It was named after King Richard II of England who celebrated the day on 1 May 1472 following the death of his father King John of England.The name Richard II (and the subsequent titles "King of England" and "Great Duke of Gloucester") was originally used for Edward the Black Prince of Normandy. Roland Emmerich  is an American American actor, director, producer, and writer of science fiction and fantasy films.

Hawaii Five-O is an American police procedural drama series produced by CBS Productions and created by Leonard Freeman . Set in the Hawaiian islands, the series was the highest-rated television show of the 1990s and is ranked as the fourth-highest rated program of all-time. Set in the 1950s, the series follows an FBI agent (James Remar) and his partner (Leland Orser), who investigate and solve crime in a fictional community called Kona. The show's characters are named after Hawaiian names. Hayao Miyazaki (, , ; ; 5 March 1907 – 24 August 2018) was an animation director, artist, and film producer.

Events < onlyinclude > January–March January 5 – King Charles II of England gives the title Duke of St Albans to the future William Rufus of Richmond. L'Enfance (, also , , ), also referred to as L'Intension , is a French comic strip created by Gilles Proust and is considered to be the most popular of the first generation of French comic strips. It was published from 1920 to 1935 and has been considered the first modern comic strip. The strip's influence has been seen in dozens of other French comic strips and graphic novels, and remains popular abroad.

Year 1390 ( MCCCXC ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display full calendar ) of the Christian calendar. The year 1390 marked the transition from the Gregorian Calendar to the Julian Calendar which is still in use. The year 1390 was a new Gregorian leap year and was observed from 13 April 1390 until the present day on 1 October. The year was the first in the year that the Julian calendar began with 365 days, starting at March 21, 397 B.C.E. This article is about the original character. For other uses, such as the series, see John McClane (disambiguated).

La Ruffiana is an older female character of the Commedia dell'Arte with a shady past or who used to be a prostitute. She is used most often in relationship to the vecchi of which group she is a nominal member. Ruffiana is most often romantically involved with Pantalone, though his love may easily be unrequited if it suits the plot. She is generally described as being talkative/gossipy, sneaky, and mischievous, but deep down is actually kind. She has been described as an "outsider" that always mixes things up and causes trouble for the rest of the characters.

Year 1515 (MDXV) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 25 – Francis I of France is crowned (r. until 1547). May 13 – Mary Tudor, Queen of France, and Charles Brandon, 1st Duke of Suffolk, are officially married at Greenwich (near London). June 13 – Battle of Turnadag: The army of Ottoman sultan Selim I defeats the beylik of Dulkadir under Bozkurt of Dulkadir. July–December  July 2 – Manchester Grammar School is endowed by Hugh Oldham, the first free grammar school in England.

Year 1042 ( MXLII ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) at the end of the year and ending on Sunday at the beginning of the next one, with its final day on the Monday.It was considered a leap year by most nations, but it was not until 1682 that it was formally recognised as such, when the Julian calendar became the international standard.The word "leap year" originates from Latin ludus, ludere, or Ludus, or ludum (Latin ludus means leap).

Year 1538 (MDXXXVIII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–June February 24 – Treaty of Nagyvárad: Peace is declared between Ferdinand I, future Holy Roman Emperor and the Ottoman Empire. John Zápolya is recognized as King of Hungary (Eastern Hungarian Kingdom), while Ferdinand retains the northern and western parts of the Kingdom, and is recognized as heir to the throne. April 26 – Battle of Las Salinas: Almagro is defeated by Francisco Pizarro, who then seizes Cusco.
