The Commonwealth Games, often referred to as the Friendly Games, is an international multi-sport event involving athletes from the Commonwealth of Nations. The event was first held in 1930, and, with the exception of 1942 and 1946, has taken place every four years since then. The Commonwealth Games were known as the British Empire Games from 1930 to 1950, the British Empire and Commonwealth Games from 1954 to 1966, and British Commonwealth Games from 1970 to 1974. Athletes with a disability are included as full members of their national teams, making the Commonwealth Games the first fully inclusive international multi-sport event.

Year 1237 (MCCXXXVII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Summer – Emperor Frederick II assembles an expeditionary force (some 15,000 men) to crush the rebellious Lombard League. He crosses the Alps to Verona – where he is joined by Lord Ezzelino III da Romano, including troops from Brescia, Vicenza, Padua, and Treviso. Frederick relies on his allies for support, and in doing so he provokes the opposition of earlier supporters, such as the House of Este, who now sides with the Lombards.

Events January–March January 17 – Tuscarora War : Colonel James Moore leads the Carolina militia out of Albemarle County , North Carolina, on January 17, 1775. This battle was the first of the war between the United States and the Province of North Carolina over the future of the state. The conflict began when British General Cornwallis, commander of the American First Corps, ordered the British to occupy the French Fort Duquesne, south of New Bern. Moore was among the troops who attacked Duquesne. Moore is known as the Father of the Mountain Men (FoM) for his actions.

In the Swedish calendar it was a common year starting on Friday , one day ahead of the Julian and Gregorian calendar years. It is commonly referred to simply as Julian year because it was the only Julian calendar year in the Gregorian calendar, and because it was in the Julian calendar. In both calendars it is counted from the  January  year, but in the Julian calendar, it begins on  and counts backwards from January. Johann Georg Friedrich Büchner (4 April 1810 – 13 March 1904) was a German mathematician, physicist, astronomer and philosopher.

A lever ( or ) is a simple machine consisting of a beam or rigid rod pivoted at a fixed hinge, or fulcrum. A lever is a rigid body capable of rotating on a point on itself. On the basis of the locations of fulcrum, load and effort, the lever is divided into three types. Also, leverage is mechanical advantage gained in a system. It is one of the six simple machines identified by Renaissance scientists. A lever amplifies an input force to provide a greater output force, which is said to provide leverage.

The Asian Games , also known as Asiad , is a continental multi-sport event held every four years among athletes from all continents. The Asian Games consists of five events: men's beach volleyball, men's weightlifting, men's hockey, women's beach volleyball, and women's weightlifting.In addition, the 2018 Asian Games will also include a women's beach volleyball and men's shot put. In 2018, beach volleyball will be held in three cities: Singapore, Vietnam and Thailand. The Arctic is an area of land situated between the North Pole and the Equator.

Events January–June January 8 – The Jesuit educational plan , known as the Ratio Studiorum , is issued . March 17 – Cardinal Robert Bellarmine and the Council of Trent are restored to Catholic teaching. February–July 1774 – A French invasion of the Austrian Empire leads to the final defeat of Napoleon III at the Battle of Tannenberg and the declaration of the First Republic of France. March–December 1814 – Napoleon III abdicates as Emperor of France to his brother Joseph, and the Kingdom of Prussia is formed. The International Court of Justice (I.C.J.) is an international institution established in 1946 by the United Nations.

Bacillus cereus is a Gram-positive, rod-shaped, facultatively anaerobic, motile, beta-hemolytic, spore-forming bacterium commonly found in soil, food and marine sponges. The specific name, cereus, meaning "waxy" in Latin, refers to the appearance of colonies grown on blood agar. Some strains are harmful to humans and cause foodborne illness, while other strains can be beneficial as probiotics for animals. The bacteria is classically contracted from fried rice dishes that have been sitting at room temperature for hours. B. cereus bacteria are facultative anaerobes, and like other members of the genus Bacillus, can produce protective endospores.

Year 1149 (MCXLIX) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos) recovers Corfu with the help of the Venetians, who defeat the Sicilian fleet. During the three-month siege, Byzantine admiral Stephen Kontostephanos  is killed by a stone thrown by a catapult. Manuel prepares an offensive against the Normans, King Roger II sends a fleet (some 40 ships) under George of Antioch to pilliage the suburbs of Constantinople.

The history of Anguilla runs from the beginning of human habitation , probably via settlement from South America , through occupation by Polynesians and other groups and to colonization by the Spanish and the Dutch in the late 16th century. Anguilla is a Caribbean island in the southwestern Caribbean Sea, between Venezuela to the south and Puerto Rico to the north. Its capital, San Juan, is on the southeast coast of the Island of Hispaniola.Anguilla has two major ports, San Juan and Cartagena. Anguilla is the capital and largest town of the West Indies, and a major tourist destination.

Year 1391 ( MCCCXCI ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display full calendar ) of 1391 and ending on the following Sunday, 1 March 1401. This would make 1391 the 3rd of April in the Gregorian calendar, although in practice this would be the 19th or 20th day after the 1st. It also would be the first in a series of 13 Gregorian calender years.The 1390s saw major changes in British history, beginning with the Battle of Trafalgar and culminating with Henry VII's marriage to Margaret Tudor. In physics, an emulsion  is a solid that forms an anionic liquid phase with an ionic solvent.

EventsJanuary–March January 20 – The Parliament of England ( under Tory dominance ) limits the size of the country 's legislative assemblies to one for every 20,000 people. April 1766 – England becomes a Republic for the first time in its history and its government forms the first democratically elected Parliament since 1366. It is also the first time in a British monarch to abdicate in the event of a civil war or an emergency situation. Etymology The word etymology is a part of the field of linguistic research. It aims to describe the processes that take place in the derivation of word meanings from a language.

Year 1335 (MCCCXXXV) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  May 2 – Otto the Merry, Duke of Austria, becomes Duke of Carinthia. July 30 – Battle of Boroughmuir: John Randolph, 3rd Earl of Moray defeats Guy, Count of Namur in Scotland. November 30 – Battle of Culblean: David Bruce defeats Edward Balliol in Scotland. December 1 – Abu Sa'id Bahadur Khan dies, a victim of the plague that ravages the Ilkhanate. This is an early outbreak of the Black Death.

In computer programming , a postcondition is a condition or predicate that must always be true just after the execution of a mathematical expression is complete, or that must always hold just after the execution of a function call.The postcondition is often used to ensure that a program's behavior will always be consistent. The postfix increment operator ! is used in computer programming, especially in assembler, to increment the current memory pointer in the context of an instruction. It may be introduced by an operator prefix, or by an operator, such as + , which incrementes the current position in memory.

Year 1176 ( MCLXXVI ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) and followed by a lunar new year. This leap year was the first to be leap years in both the Roman Catholic and the Eastern Orthodox calendars and was celebrated on 12 February in each year, although in the Eastern Orthodox calendars the date was 14 February. Leap years are a special situation during an irregular year, where the year is divided into 24 months, each divided into 12 days. The number of days in each month varies between different calendar implementations.

Events  January–June  January–June – The Swiss Peasant War is fought. January 3 – By the Coonan Cross Oath, the Eastern Church in India cuts itself off from colonial Portuguese tutelage. February 2 – New Amsterdam (later renamed New York City) is incorporated. February 3 – Cardinal Mazarin returns to Paris from exile. March 14 – A Dutch fleet defeats the English in the Battle of Leghorn; the Dutch commander, Johan van Galen, later dies of his wounds. April 20 – Oliver Cromwell expels the Rump Parliament in England.
